<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Texas 4thLd-Writethru a0996 03-08 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Texas, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0996, a0923,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Wins `Home' State; Dukakis Wins Top Three Delegate States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to combines previous, Recast lede, UPDATE
results; Picks up 4th graf, `Also on ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis won
delegate-rich Texas on Tuesday, sweeping the top three delegate
states in Democratic presidential primaries, while Vice President
George Bush coasted to victory in the Republican race.
   In the Democratic race, with 3,506 of 6,933 precincts or 51
percent reporting, Dukakis had 233,204 votes or 32 percent;
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 166,692 votes or 23 percent;
Jesse Jackson had 139,612 votes or 19 percent; Missouri Rep.
Richard Gephardt had 118,127 votes or 16 percent; former Colorado
Sen. Gary Hart had 39,444 votes or 5 percent; and Illinois Sen.
Paul Simon had 13,533 votes, or 2 percent.
   With 2,013 of 5,616 precincts or 36 percent reporting, Bush had
184,472 votes or 63 percent; Pat Robertson had 46,629 votes or 16
percent; Kansas Sen. Bob Dole had 40,808 votes or 14 percent; and
New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 14,366 votes or 5 percent.
   Texas offered the highest number of Democratic delegates on
Super Tuesday, with 183. Dukakis also carried Florida, which has
136 Democratic delegates, and Massachusetts, which has 98 delegates.
   Also on the ballot, three-term Sen. Lloyd Bentsen won
renomination against Democratic primary opponent Joe Sullivan, a
San Antonio college professor. Republicans seeking to challenge
Bentsen were Rep. Beau Boulter of Amarillo, former state Rep.
Milton Fox of Austin, Georgetown industrialist Ned Snead and
Houston businessman Wes Gilbreath.
   Bush, who rents a motel in Houston so he can vote in Texas,
pushed hard for the biggest prize of Super Tuesday: Texas' 111
convention delegates.
   ``Texas is the jewel in the crown of the 20-state Super
Tuesday,'' former U.S. Sen. Ralph Yarborough said in reference to
the state offering more delegates than any other in Tuesday's
primaries.
   Voter registration was up by more than 500,000 and Secretary of
State Jack Rains predicted the total vote could go as high as 2.5
million.
   Bush, who built an oil business in Texas, led in polls
throughout the campaign.
   ``As a Texan, I know our state's special needs,'' Bush said in a
letter to potential GOP primary voters. ``For 20 years in public
life and for 20 years in business in Midland and Houston, I've
prepared for this campaign and the challenge of serving as
president.''
   Bush has staked a claim as ``native son'' in other states. He
was born in Massachusetts, reared in Connecticut, and maintains a
home in Maine as well as in Washington.
   Dole insisted he was giving nothing away although his campaign
appearances were limited and he skipped a major Dallas debate.
   Since Texans don't register by political party, Robertson said
he was counting on substantial crossover support. ``That's my
secret weapon. I've got tremendous appeal among Democrats, and
George Bush doesn't,'' he said.
   Also up for election this year are five seats on the Texas
Supreme Court, a bench wracked by negative national publicity over
large campaign contributions to judges by lawyers, the public
reprimands of two sitting justices and the failure of the
nine-member court to even hear the appeal of an $11 billion
judgment awarded in the Texaco-Pennzoil lawsuit.
</TEXT>
