<1ST_LINE>r p BC-MississippiAt-A-Glance     03-08 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mississippi At-A-Glance,240</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from Mississippi to attend the 1988 Democratic and
Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Tuesday, March 8
   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, Richard
Gephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon
   Pledged delegates: 40
   Super delegates: 5
   Total: 45
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, March 19 and Saturday, March 26
   All of Mississippi's 40 pledged Democratic National Convention
delegates will be allocated among presidential candidates in
proportion to results of the state primary March 8.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Tuesday, March 8
   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, Pat
Robertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig
   Delegates: 31
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, April 30 and Saturday, May 21
   The results of Mississippi's primary govern how its Republican
national convention delegates are allocated among presidential
candidates.
   Three delegates from each of the state's five congressional
districts are awarded on a winner-take-all basis to the candidate
receiving the most votes in that district.
   The remaining 16 delegates at-large are allocated among
presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the
primary. Only those candidates receiving at least 10 percent of the
vote statewide are eligible to claim national convention delegates.
</TEXT>
