<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Malaysia-Names     03-08 0105</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Malaysia-Names,0109</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Malaysia Standardizes Spelling Of A Common Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has decided to
standardize the spelling of a common name in Malaysia.
   Current variations on the name include Mohamed, Mohamad,
Mohamat, Muhamat and Muhammad.
   To simplify matters for the bureaucracy, the National
Registration Department recently issued an order standardizing the
spelling to Muhammad.
   This does not mean that Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and
Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat will have to change the
spelling of their names.
   A spokesman for the department said Tuesday the directive only
applies to names recorded on birth certificates after the order was
issued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0106EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Labor     03-08 0124</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Labor,0126</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Has 20 Million Surplus Workers, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has 20 million surplus workers, although
there are substantial manpower shortages in jobs requiring heavy
labor, the official China Daily said today.
   The newspaper said surplus workers in the work force of 132
million are costing the state billions of dollars and are a heavy
burden to enterprises.
   It quoted the director of a boiler factory as saying his
operation would be more efficient if the current staff of 10,000
was reduced by 4,000.
   But it said workers in overstaffed plants and unemployed youths
are reluctant to volunteer for jobs in repair businesses or those
requiring heavy labor. Such jobs are filled mainly by surplus
agricultural workers, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
