<DOCNO> AP880308-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChallengerSettlements Bjt   03-08 0879</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Challenger Settlements, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Thiokol Settlements Said To Shortchange Four Challenger
Families</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for five relatives of Challenger
astronauts says that other families who settled with the government
and with rocket maker Morton Thiokol for $7.7 million were
shortchanged.
   ``That settlement is woefully inadequate,'' said Ronald D.
Krist, a Houston attorney who represented astronauts' survivors
from the Apollo spacecraft fire in 1967 as well as three families
from the 1986 space shuttle disaster.
   Krist said the four Challenger families in the
government-company settlement should have and ``would have netted
more money'' if they had hired lawyers.
   The cost of the four-family settlement, which came in cash and
annuities, was disclosed in government documents released Monday.
   The documents show that Morton Thiokol, which produced the
faulty booster rocket blamed for the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of
the space shuttle Challenger, paid $4,641,000, or 60 percent. The
government's share of the settlements was $3,094,000, or 40 percent.
   The documents were released by the Justice Department to settle
a civil suit brought under the Freedom of Information Act by The
Associated Press and six other news organizations.
   In court papers, the government acknowledged that the four
settling families did not hire lawyers, relying instead on informal
advice from Leo B. Lind, Jr., executor of the estate of Christa
McAuliffe, a 37-year-old Concord, N.H., public high school teacher
killed in the explosion. Lind is the law partner of McAuliffe's
husband, Steven.
   Michael D. Oldak, an attorney and ex-husband of mission
specialist Judith A. Resnik, represented her father, Marvin, in
settlement talks with the Justice Department.
   ``I think it was a big mistake'' for the four settling families
not to hire lawyers, Oldak said Monday. ``I think if I hadn't been
involved, they probably may have coerced the Resniks into accepting
their original offer. These are people in the midst of their
grief.''
   Oldak said the original government-company offer was ``a few
hundred thousand,'' and ``I told them nicely what they could do
with it.'' He rebuffed them again when ``nearly a year later, they
doubled the offer.''
   Instead, Marvin Resnik settled with Morton Thiokol last month
for an amount he put at between $2 million and $3.5 million. The
government refused to contribute to the settlement.
   The government's treatment of the four families was viewed
differently by Betty Grissom, whose husband Gus died in the Apollo
fire.
   Mrs. Grissom said she received only $350,000, and had to sue
North American Rockwell on her own for that.
   ``I never heard from the Justice Department,'' she said. ``I
thought we got an injustice done to us. They act like they care
now, but they didn't back then.
   ``It kinda hurts,'' she added. ``It stings that ... we never got
treated like that. It hurts when I think that they're getting that
much money.''
   The settlements were reached Dec. 29, 1986, with the immediate
survivors of spacecraft commander Dick Scobee, 46, a retired Air
Force officer employed by the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration; mission specialist Ellison S. Onizuka, 39, an Air
Force lieutenant colonel; payload specialist Gregory Jarvis, 41, an
employee of Hughes Aircraft Co.; and McAuliffe.
   The surviving four spouses and six children will receive more
than $7,735,000, because each was given an annuity, which pays
benefits larger than its cost but over a period of many years.
   The total dollar amounts they will receive over time and the
breakdown by family were not released.
   Among the disclosures:
   _The Justice Department did all the negotiating for Morton
Thiokol as well as the government. The families never spoke to
company officials.
   _The rocket maker tried to have the settlements cover any
property damage Morton Thiokol might have caused, such as
destruction of the orbiter and payload, but the government refused.
   _Although the Justice Department claims it cannot legally be
sued by the families of military or federal civilian employees who
die on duty, it contributed 40 percent to each of the settlements.
Only the Jarvis and McAuliffe relatives had a right to sue the
government directly; all the astronaut families could sue the
company.
   Morton Thiokol attorney John W. Adler said the government was
being unfair to the parents of Resnik, a 36-year-old civilian NASA
employee, because of ``the government's refusal to participate to
any degree at all'' in a settlement the company considered
acceptable.
   Resnik's mother, Sarah Resnik Belfer, and Jarvis' father, Bruce,
settled with Morton, Thiokol but the government did not contribute.
So did Cheryl McNair, wife of mission specialist Ronald E. McNair,
35, a civilian NASA employee who had two infant children. All five
were represented by Krist.
   Jane Smith, wife of pilot Michael J. Smith, 40, a Navy
commander, has a suit pending in federal court against the company.
The government last month got itself dismissed as a defendant,
because military personnel may not sue the government for wrongful
death.
   Justice spokeswoman Amy Brown said the government made
settlement offers to attorneys for the Resniks, Smiths and McNairs
based on the same formula used for the other families, but they
were rejected. She said the government would not offer them
settlements which exceeded the guidelines used for the other
families or which were separate from settlements with Morton
Thiokol.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-South Bjt   03-08 0903</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-South, Bjt,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On Super Tuesday, Jackson Hopes To Win Votes Outside His Black
Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonore Sarabia, clutching her sweater
against the morning chill, awaited Jesse Jackson's arrival at the
Mirasol housing project, a heavily Hispanic neighborhood where the
presidential hopeful was searching out votes for today's election.
   She had come ``to check him out,'' she said, even though she
already knew she would vote for him. She didn't really know
anything about the other five Democratic contenders, but Jackson
``is more for the people,'' she explained as the candidate emerged
from a limousine.
   Two days earlier, it was Tom Trantham's dairy farm in the South
Carolina county where Jackson grew up. There, he talked farm policy
and shared a breakfast of grits and eggs with Trantham and a few
neighbors as cameras and reporters jostled around the table.
   The white farmers said they were grateful for Jackson's support
during the 1986 drought, when he helped unload trucked-in hay. But
they were noncommittal about whether they would vote for him.
   ``I haven't made a decision,'' said Bertha Tinsley. Her husband
Doug Tinsley, fetching coffee refills for the Jackson group, said
he was a Republican and would probably vote GOP.
   The two campaign stops illustrate the challenge and the success
Jackson has had as he tries to expand his base beyond his core of
black supporters.
   In the South, voters today are deciding if he can overcome what
he describes as an ``ancient cultural barrier,'' and pull white
support here as he did in five northern states with fractional
black populations.
   Today's Super Tuesday election, with 14 Southern states among
the 20 where voters are going to the polls, has shaped up as the
day when Jackson's presidential bid will shine.
   It is virtually certain he will be picking up more non-black
votes than he did in his 1984 race. And he hopes to do well enough
to lay to rest the so-called electability question, the notion that
he can't be elected because he is black.
   Casual interviews along the campaign trail indicate Jackson has
engendered considerable respect among Southern whites. Although
some say the racial issue is not as much a factor as it was in
1984, they acknowledge it still remains for many.
   ``The older group, they won't change,'' Jackson supporter Thomas
DeLong, a 57-year-old white student at Mississippi State College,
said of Mississippi voters. He and others interviewed, said that
among students, a group the campaign is targeting, Jackson has
considerable support.
   Jackson's campus rallies are a big draw, and the enthusiastic
audiences are sprinkled with whites, including Republicans, who
seem to come as much out of curiosity as anything.
   At the University of Arkansas, white economics student Tony
Green was impressed by Jackson's powerful delivery, commenting,
``Wow, quite a speech.''
   He said race is not an issue for him but Jackson ``is just too
liberal.'' He may even vote Republican if Vice President George
Bush wins the GOP nomination, he said.
   Jackson has touted the endorsements of a handful of prominent
white Southern politicians including Texas Agriculture Commissioner
Jim Hightower, Oklahoma State Sen. Gene Stipe, and Tennessean John
J. Hooker, a former gubernatorial candidate with close ties to
former Sen. Albert Gore Sr., the father of one of Jackson's rivals.
   In Texas, with its large Hispanic population, he was joined on
the campaign trail by New Mexico Gov. Toney Anaya, a prominent
Hispanic leader.
   And Selma, Ala., last week saw a historically dramatic moment.
The white mayor who had had Dr. Martin Luther King and other civil
rights activist arrested more than two decades ago welcomed
Jackson, a King protege and longtime civil rights activist, giving
him the key to the city.
   Mayor Joe Smitherman then joined Jackson for a stroll through
streets that saw some of the most tense moments of the civil rights
struggle.
   The mayor said he was wrong to oppose the civil rights movement
and while he's not officially endorsing Jackson, he supports his
message. The message, powerfully hammered home in Jackson's stump
speech, is:
   _That ``the new South'' is one of equal civil rights but
economic inequity.
   _That greater efforts are needed to fight the drug influx, the
No. 1 national security threat.
   _That multinational corporations are to blame for loss of U.S.
jobs because they take their business to cheap labor markets
overseas.
   _That corporate agribusiness is to blame for squeezing the
family farm.
   _That the minimum wage should be increased, and health care and
day care programs are needed for the poor.
   _That overall hemispheric cooperation is needed to help ease
Latin nations' debts, increase U.S. exports and make peace with
Cuba and Nicaragua.
   ``This is a referendum on economic violence,'' Jackson says.
``People who are unemployed are rebelling. People who have jobs are
insecure. People feel abandoned by the government.''
   There also is considerable evidence that Jackson is benefiting
from being a celebrity in a contest where the other five candidates
are a blur in many voters' minds.
   The other Democrats have made multimillion-dollar media buys,
compared to Jackson's paltry $100,000 worth of ads in mostly
non-major markets.
   Jackson relies on the free media attention that follows him on
his 18-hour campaign days, filled with TV-oriented events and photo
opportunities.
   Campaign manager Gerald Austin says the chartered DC-9 that
carries the candidate and traveling press corps is Jackson's media
expenditure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
