<DOCNO> AP880308-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AfricanIncome     03-08 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-African Income,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Bank Sees 25 Percent Drop in African Incomes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Average incomes have dropped 25 percent in the
countries of black Africa during the 1980s, according to the latest
figures from the World Bank.
   ``The seriousness of the short-term economic outlook ... must
not be underestimated,'' Eugene V.K. Jaycox, the bank's vice
president for Africa, said in a speech Monday to the United Nations
advisory panel on Africa.
   The bank released 1987 figures showing incomes were down by 4
percent from a year earlier. That drop followed a more than 2.7
percent decline reported for 1986 and an average annual decline
from 1980-85 of 3.7 percent.
   Exports and imports both declined for the year, but there was a
1.6 percent improvement in prices that Africans got for their
products, compared with what they had to pay for foreign goods.
That was a lot better than 1986, when there was a drop of 25.2
percent.
   Gerard Rice, a World Bank spokesman, said its economists are
looking for a better year in 1988 with the average income holding
steady. Some countries have had continuous declines since they won
independence in the 1960s.
   The figures cover what the bank calls ``sub-Saharan Africa,''
which includes the whole continent except for South Africa and the
northern tier countries Algeria, Egypt, Libya, Morocco and Egypt.
   Carol Lancaster, who deals with Africa at the Institute for
International Economics, said the countries in worst shape are
those hit by war and drought, such as Angola, Ethiopia and
Mozambique. The institute is a private study group financed largely
by the West German Marshall Fund.
   Nigeria, the most populous country on the continent and the one
with by far the biggest economy, has been hurt by the drop in the
price of oil, its dominant export. The decline in its income has a
big effect on the overall figure.
   The World Bank is the single biggest source of loans to improve
living standards in the Third World. In 1985 Treasury Secretary
James A. Baker III said the bank should take the lead in planning
new programs with heavily indebted countries. Since then it has
been giving more emphasis to broad lending programs, though the
majority of its loans are still for individual projects.
   For the year ending June 30, it is expected to lend Africa $5
billion.
   The International Monetary Fund, the bank's sister organization,
is expected to make another $1.5 billion worth of loans at minimal
interest.
   But the United Nations advisory panel on Africa said the
continent also needs about $1 billion a year in relief from its old
debts, most of them to governments, and another $1 billion in new
aid.
   Africa's $200 billion dollar debt is less than half Latin
America's, but its population is poorer, smaller and growing fast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScotusRdp     03-08 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus Rdp,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court To Examine How Much Proof Must Be Given Against Sex
Discrimination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court is beginning another
examination of sex discrimination in the American workplace,
agreeing to decide how difficult it should be for employers to
disprove charges of sexist stereotyping.
   Setting the stage for an important ruling likely to be announced
in 1989, the justices on Monday said they will hear an appeal by
Price Waterhouse, one of the nation's leading accounting firms.
   The company is accused of allowing sexism, some of it perhaps
unconscious, to play a key role in denying a woman a partnership in
the firm.
   A federal appeals court placed a heavy burden on the firm to
disprove the sex bias charges.
   Price Waterhouse, one of the nation's so-called ``big eight''
accounting firms, is accused of discriminating unlawfully against
Ann Hopkins. She quit the firm's office here after she was denied
promotion to partnership, a move that would have made her a part
owner.
   Ms. Hopkins joined the firm in 1978 and was nominated for
partnership in 1982, the only woman among 88 candidates for
partnership that year. At the time, the company had more than 660
partners in 90 offices nationwide.
   Ms. Hopkins had been very successful in getting business for the
company, winning government contracts worth an estimated $34
million to $44 million.
   Of the 88 candidates in 1978, 47 were invited to become
partners; 21 were rejected outright; and 20 including Ms. Hopkins
were placed on hold.
   The following year she was told she would not become a partner
and she resigned in 1984 to set up her own consulting firm.
   Both her critics and supporters at Price Waterhouse said she
sometimes was overly aggressive, too harsh, impatient with her
staff and very demanding.
   One critic suggested she needed to take a ``course at charm
school.''
   A partner in the firm who urged her promotion told her she would
stand a better chance of becoming a partner if she would ``walk
more femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear
makeup, have her hair styled and wear jewelry.''
   Others said her use of profanity was a black mark against her.
   Ms. Hopkins then sued Price Waterhouse, accusing the company of
violating Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act prohibiting
on-the-job sex discrimination. She said that sex stereotyping,
unconscious or otherwise, barred her from being named partner.
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1984, in the case of a woman denied
partnership in a law firm, that professional partnerships are
covered by the 1964 law.
   A federal judge ruled Price Waterhouse must prove ``by clear and
convincing evidence'' it would not have made her a partner
regardless of whether sexual stereotyping played a part in its
decision.
   Price Waterhouse did not provide such proof.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here last August said there is
``competent evidence that ... the partnership selection process at
Price Waterhouse was impermissibly infected by stereotypical
attitudes toward female candidates.''
   The appeals court said even if there is evidence that Ms.
Hopkins' personality played a part in her denial of partnership,
Price Waterhouse is unable to prove ``impermissible bias was not
the determinative factor.''
   The appeals court ordered further hearings to determine what
back pay and other remedies the company must provide.
   In other matters, the court:
   _Ruled that companies have a heavy burden of proof when
defending themselves against investor lawsuits alleging the
companies withheld information about merger discussions.
   _Agreed to decide whether states may use anti-racketeering laws
to close down adult bookstores accused of selling obscene
materials. The court said it will review free-speech challenges to
Indiana's Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law,
patterned after the much-used federal RICO act.
   _Agreed to use a case from Canton, Ohio, to try again to decide
whether cities may be sued successfully by citizens who say their
rights were violated by inadequately trained city employees.
   _Ruled that financially troubled farmers may not avoid
foreclosure under federal bankruptcy law by promising to pay back
debts by using their labor and expertise while continuing to
operate their farm.
   _Said it will decide in a case from Chicago whether a criminal
defendant's right to a jury selected from a cross-section of the
community is violated when prosecutors disqualify potential jurors
based on their race.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
