<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TooLate     03-08 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Too Late,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Non-Candidates, It's Too Late To Win The Nomination Through
Primaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the Democratic Party's most prominent
non-candidates, Super Tuesday marks a milestone _ it's too late to
step in and win the presidential nomination through the primaries.
   By the numbers, it just can't be done.
   That's not to say that New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley or Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn couldn't wind up with
the nomination. But as of Wednesday, they would have to get it by
making political deals with the announced candidates for delegates
or by swaying a deadlocked national convention.
   Neither scenario can be ruled out because none of the three has
ruled out accepting a draft for the nomination. Cuomo has gone so
far as to say he would accept such a draft at a deadlocked
convention if party leaders made it his ``obligation.''
   Just last week, former President Jimmy Carter said there was an
even chance that no Democrat would clinch the nomination before the
July convention in Atlanta.
   There will be 4,160 delegates to the national convention and
2,081 are needed to win the nomination. With the passing of Super
Tuesday there will be 2,279 delegates available from the 31
primaries and caucuses that remain.
   However, the problem for any late-starting candidate is that
most of the filing deadlines to get on the later primary ballots
will have passed with Super Tuesday.
   A new candidate could get on primary ballots in just five
states, participate in caucuses in six other states, in caucuses
for Democrats in Guam and the Virgin Islands and in a primary for
Democrats living elsewhere outside the United States.
   In all, by winning 100 percent of the delegates available in all
those post-Super Tuesday contests qualified for, the candidate
would wind up with 628 delegates going into the convention.
   Cuomo, talking about the mathematics of a late start, said:
``Number one, you can't do it. Number two, it's irrelevant because
I wouldn't anyway.''
   The major contests still open after Super Tuesday are the June 7
primaries in New Jersey and California. The filing deadlines are
March 24 for California and April 13 for New Jersey.
   In California, some Democrats are trying to collect enough
signatures to get Cuomo's name on the ballot. In New Jersey,
meanwhile, a group of prominent, pro-Bradley Democrats announced
late last month that it would attempt to run an uncommitted slate
of delegates in the June 7 primary to give Bradley strength at the
national convention, if he wanted it.
   In New York, a group of pro-Cuomo Democratic county clerks has
already qualified an uncommitted slate for the state's April 19
primary even though Cuomo asked them not to do it. The New York
primary is for 255 delegates.
   By getting into some of the later primaries, such as California
and New Jersey, a new candidate could demonstrate strength among
the electorate.
   Cuomo says the nomination shouldn't go to someone who hasn't
been tested in the primaries. The candidates already in the race
share that sentiment.
   ``If I lose the nomination, I want to be eliminated by someone
who has played in the same league,'' said Jesse Jackson late last
year when asked about a possible Cuomo convention draft.
   Nonetheless, Nunn said last week that if no clear favorite
emerges from Super Tuesday, the pressure will increase on Cuomo and
the other prominent non-candidates. Also last week, former Virginia
Gov. Charles Robb said Cuomo was the only non-candidate who could
possibly capture the nomination at a deadlocked national convention.
   While Robert Beckel, Democrat Walter Mondale's 1984 campaign
manager, said he thinks the nomination will go to one of the
current crop of candidates, he also said ``there's a possibility of
chaos.''
   ``You will hear about a Cuomo run between now and June 7, I'm
convinced of that,'' said Beckel. ``Whether it will happen or not,
I'm much less convinced.''
   David Garth, the New York-based political consultant and
occasional Cuomo adviser, said he doesn't expect any immediate move
from the New York governor.
   ``I think he's going to do nothing until the convention. I think
it's going to the convention and at that point he's got some very
difficult decisions to make,'' said Garth. ``He's going to have a
difficult time at the point saying no.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
