<DOCNO> AP880308-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson-ChurchBulletins     03-08 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson-Church Bulletins,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letter From Robertson Backer Irks Pastors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATAVIA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political organizers for GOP presidential
hopeful Pat Robertson have been asking local pastors to use church
bulletins to solicit support for their candidate, Robertson aides
acknowledged Monday.
   ``I don't think it's out of line,'' said Henry Hughes,
Robertson's chief organizer in New York state. ``We are not taking
up collections in church like (Jesse) Jackson's campaign.''
   He said pastors should be free to provide political guidance to
their congregation as long as it does not actively involve the
``structure'' of the church.
   But several pastors in this rural upstate community disagreed.
   ``I very strongly object to that and I don't support endorsing
any political candidate,'' the Rev. D. Gregory Van Dussen, pastor
of the Bergen United Methodist Church told the Batavia Daily News.
   Van Dussen said he received a letter from the regional committee
of Americans for Robertson based in Rochester asking for the use of
church bulletins to announce its organizing meetings.
   He said the letter steered clear of asking for donations or
recommendations from the pulpit.
   ``Mainly it was for behind-the-scenes support,'' he said. ``They
were asking us, somewhat diplomatically, to use church sponsorship
and organize support for Robertson.''
   The letter, according to the pastor, said that Robertson was a
Christian candidate presenting the views of Christians and that
``Christians of like mind would support him.''
   Robertson, a former Baptist minister and television evangelist,
scored well in the Iowa primary last month, coming in second behind
Sen. Bob Dole. But his campaign has since faltered. He predicted a
win in South Carolina Saturday, but came in a distant third behind
Vice President George Bush and Dole.
   Van Dussen said it was the first time he has ever received a
letter asking for the church's political support. He said he has
asked his fellow clergymen to refuse to allow the Robertson
campaign or any other campaign to use the church for political
purposes.
   Another pastor, Douglas Spencer of the First United Methodist
Church in Batavia, said, ``I didn't think the church should make
that type of decision. The church contains people from various
backgrounds. The letter sought institutional support for one
candidate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SuperVignettes     03-08 1095</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Super Vignettes,1050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scenes from the Trail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Al Gore's strawberries ... Bob Dole's generic airliner ... Jesse
Jackson's missing tree ... Michael Dukakis' hopes for a ``Super
Martes'' ... George Bush's return ``home''... Richard Gephardt's
mom goes to bat...
   Vignettes from the campaign at the end of the long Super Tuesday
trail:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Paul Simon wrote a book a few years ago called ``The Tongue-Tied
American.'' It deplored Americans' ignorance of foreign languages.
It was written in English, the only language that Simon speaks.
   By contrast, Michael Dukakis grew up in a home where both Greek
and English were spoken. He became fluent in Spanish as a college
student on visit to Mexico and Peru.
   Dukakis put his language facility to good use before ``Super
Martes,'' as he called it. He read a lesson in Spanish at a
televised mass in San Antonio, and finished stump speeches across
Texas with the words: ``Poco a poco. Paso a paso. Mano en mano.
Juntos. Vamos a ganar.'' Or, as he translated: ``Little by little.
Step by step. Hand in hand. Together. We shall succeed.''
   Near the border with Mexico, Dukakis did not just sprinkle a few
words of Spanish into his speech: he delivered a five-minute
portion in Spanish after his English opening.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Like his rivals, Al Gore dashed back and forth across the
Southeast in the days leading up to today's primaries and caucuses
in 20 states. He managed sometimes to touch down in half a dozen
states or more in a single day.
   He traveled in a fleet of four or five Lear jets, a curious
caravan that made for speedy flying time but sometimes meant the
candidate cooled his heels on the tarmac while waiting for his
Secret Service agents and traveling press corps to land.
   Gore's campaign couldn't afford a big jet and couldn't locate a
mid-sized jet to accommodate the entourage of candidate, aides,
Secret Service agents, reporters and television crews.
   Gore earlier traveled in a single-prop airplane, a slow but
comfortable aircraft not much younger than the 39-year-old
candidate. But the campaign eschewed it after repeated mechanical
breakdowns _ a couple times in flight.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush, by contrast, had a full-size chartered Boeing 727 to carry
his press corps _ which sometimes numbered so few the entire lot
could sit in the first-class section. And did.
   That meant comfort and convenience for the travelers _ and
sometimes staggering bills for their employers. Campaign aides said
the cost billed to news organizations was in the thousands of
dollars a day for some days of heavy flying.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Campaign travel for reporters was feast or famine. Jesse
Jackson's campaign press corps took a petition to the candidate to
protest ``nutritional violence'' _ they weren't getting fed. He
signed too, scrawling, ``Let My People Go.''
   In Gore's caravan of Lear jets, the problem was too much food.
   There were platters of fresh strawberries as well as sandwiches,
egg rolls, barbecue and chicken. On one day of travel, reporters
noted they had faced five platters of food on five separate legs of
travel, plus a bag-snack of submarine sandwiches for a
midnight-flight snack.
   Somehow, they managed to eat most of it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bob Dole's campaign differed from the others in one striking
way: no Secret Service. Dole refused the protection, making a
visible contrast with Bush's almost imperial parade of escorts.
   Dole traveled on the same plane with his troupe of reporters and
sometimes wandered along the aisles to chat.
   His chartered airplane bore the words of its operating airline
on one side: ``Presidential Airways.'' But some of the words were
missing on the other side of the Boeing 737 aircraft; it said just
``Airways.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   This truly was the ``Tarmac Campaign.'' Super Tuesday eve sent
three Republican candidates to Tulsa International Airport within a
four-hour period Monday afternoon, but their paths never crossed.
The scheduled did keep reporters crisscrossing the windswept
tarmac, however.
   Bush touched down in Air Force II right on schedule at 12:05
p.m. and made quick work of a rally at an American Airlines hangar.
He toured the company's Tulsa maintenance and engineering facility
and talked briefly with reporters before lifting off again about 2
p.m.
   Meanwhile, Jack Kemp took over a nearby hangar for a 12:30 p.m.
news conference, then took off for Oklahoma City, where he
addressed the Oklahoma Legislature at 2:30 p.m.
   Dole was taking off from Oklahoma City about the same time Kemp
was speaking at the Legislature. He arrived at a private business
office at the Tulsa airport for a 3:20 p.m. news conference.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson led his entourage through Fieldcrest Village, the
spartan brick apartment complex in Greenville, S.C. where he grew
up as a boy.
   In fact, he said, ``I planted this tree right there.''
   Not so, the current residents told him. The tree he planted was
struck a while back by lightning.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In some ways, Dukakis' Super Tuesday campaign has been Southern
in latitude only.
   While his Democratic rivals were talking about grits and home
fries, Dukakis cracked jokes Monday morning with a largely Jewish
crowd of senior citizens in North Miami Beach, Fla., where many
Jews from the North have retired.
   ``There's nothing I like better than to walk on a Cape Cod beach
and finish it off with a bowl of clam chowder,'' Dukakis told the
gathering, many of whom, no doubt, have been to the Cape.
   `Of course,'' he added, deferential to his audience, ``I don't
have to worry about the dietary laws.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt's longest-standing supporter _ his mother
_ led the Gephardt campaign in South Florida on the eve of Super
Tuesday. She faced rush-hour highway traffic on U.S. 1, posting
herself at roadside with a sign: ``Support My Son.''
   The 80-year-old Loreen Gephardt has stumped for Gephardt in
Iowa, New Hampshire, Texas, South Dakota, Louisiana, Georgia and
Alabama.
   ``The last four digits in my social security number are 1988.
It's a good omen! A good omen!'' she said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, who worried aloud earlier this year
that his supporters might be delayed at debutante balls or the
country club, picked a prosperous section of Houston to await the
Super Tuesday election returns.
   Bush, who long has fought the image of being a New England
preppie, decided to hold his party tonight in the posh Westin Oaks
hotel here.
   Both Westin Oaks and the Houstonian, where Bush has a
condominium he lists as his legal residence, are nestled in an
opulent section west of downtown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0141EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Delegates     03-08 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delegates,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Super Tuesday Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican rules in eight of today's Super
Tuesday states could mean the biggest delegate prize for George
Bush, while bylaws and home-town contests for three of the
Democratic contenders may prevent an outright winner.
   Bush, who currently has 126 delegates, could pad his lead
considerably as the four GOP candidates battle for 712 national
convention delegates in 16 state contests, including Virginia's
non-binding primary.
   While the Democrats allot delegates based on a percentage of the
vote, Republicans in eight Super Tuesday states _ Alabama, Florida,
Georgia, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, Oklahoma and Texas _
award delegates on a winner-take-all basis in each district and
statewide.
   The vice president, who stands as the front-runner in many of
those states, is expected to reap the benefits of the GOP process.
   According to the latest polls, Bush leads in 14 states that hold
GOP primaries or caucuses, including delegate-rich Texas with 111,
Florida with 82, Massachusetts with 52 and Georgia with 48.
   The vice president also is ahead in Alabama with 38 delegates,
Louisiana and Maryland with 41 each, Mississippi with 31, Arkansas
with 27, Kentucky with 38, Oklahoma with 36, Rhode Island with 21
and Tennessee with 45.
   Bush is even expected to win in rival Pat Robertson's home state
of Virginia, where no delegates are at stake on Super Tuesday.
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole is hoping for some success in Missouri,
which has 47 delegates at stake, and North Carolina with 54.
   According to The Associated Press survey, Dole has 65 delegates
heading into the Super Tuesday events while New York Rep. Jack Kemp
has 35 and former television evangelist Robertson has 8. Twelve
delegates remain uncommitted.
   The Democrats will be competing for 1,307 delegates in 21 states
or territories. But the party requires that a presidential
candidate reach a certain level of support to be eligible for
winning delegates _ a system that decreases the chance of a
clear-cut Super Tuesday winner.
   Each candidate must receive at least 15 percent of the vote in
any given congressional district or statewide.
   Fueling the possibility of a four-way Democratic race are
contests in three of the candidates' home states _ Michael Dukakis'
Massachusetts, Richard Gephardt's Missouri and Albert Gore Jr.'s
Tennessee.
   Dukakis, who leads the AP survey of delegates with 69.50, is
counting on success in Massachusetts with 98 delegates at stake,
and possibly a large share of the delegates from Florida with 136,
Maryland with 67, Rhode Island with 22 and Washington with 65.
   Dukakis' chief rival in Florida is Gephardt, who has obvious
high expectations for Missouri with 77 delegates, and hopes to do
well in Oklahoma with 46, and plans to fight it out in Texas, which
boasts the biggest prize _ 183 delegates.
   Gephardt has 50 delegates so far, while Gore has 21.80, Jesse
Jackson 27.55, Paul Simon 35.50 and 258.65 remain uncommitted.
   Jackson looks to do well in the South, especially in Alabama
with 56 delegates, Georgia with 77, Louisiana with 63, Mississippi
with 40 and perhaps Hawaii with 20. Jackson enrolled 2,000 new
Democrats in the island state.
   Gore and Gephardt are expected to be locked in a close race in
Arkansas with 38 delegates. Gore is hoping to grab a large portion
of delegates in Kentucky with 55 at stake, Nevada with 16, the
obvious _ Tennessee _ with 70, and Virginia with 75.
   In North Carolina, Jackson, Gore and Dukakis are vying for 82
delegates, while in Idaho, Dukakis and Gore are battling for 18
delegates although state officials would prefer an uncommitted
slate.
   Three Democratic delegates are at stake in American Samoa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
