<DOCNO> AP880308-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Phones     03-08 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phones,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Greene Lets Bell Companies Offer Computerized Answering
Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge's ruling will allow the
regional Bell telephone companies to offer consumers new
computerized services that do the work telephone answering machines
now do.
   In his decision, U.S. District Judge Harold Greene said the
risks that the local phone companies would monopolize the market
were outweighed by the benefits this new service and others like it
would provide consumers.
   ``What has until now been a relatively quiescent market is
likely to become a broad, vigorous and competitive one'' that will
make the service available to a broad base of consumers, he said in
a 66-page decision Monday.
   About 10 percent of American households use answering machines,
he said.
   Besides voice messaging, as it is called, the Bell companies
also could provide electronic mail services, which allow
computer-to-computer transfer of messages, Greene said.
   In addition, he outlined a set of computer ``gateway'' functions
the companies can provide to guide a computer user to various
information services. But he restricted these functions to services
like data transmission, billing management and services that enable
different computers to ``speak'' to each other.
   In so doing, he refused to retreat from his September ruling in
which he said phone companies could transmit information services
but could not generate or manipulate the content of the information.
   The Bell companies generally praised Greene's decision as a
``first step'' toward making a wide range of information services
available to the public, but they said the judge didn't go far
enough.
   ``We view this as a start, but only a start. We still are not
allowed to provide content for information services,'' a BellSouth
statement said.
   The Bell companies have lobbied heavily for full participation
in the information services market so they could provide services
that would enable consumers with personal computers to bank and
shop from home, make travel arrangements and even read newspapers.
   Bell Atlantic Chairman Thomas E. Bolger said the company is
``particularly concerned'' that Greene is continuing to forbid the
Bell companies from electronic publishing of yellow page phone
directories.
   Though Greene's decision lifts the legal barrier to the Bell
companies' offering of voice messaging and electronic mail, the
companies still would need state and federal regulatory approval
before they could offer the services to consumers.
   Industry experts and Bell company officials say the computer
software for these services has been developed and could be offered
to consumers in some parts of the country within one to two years.
   Greene, who oversees the antitrust decree that stripped American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. of its Bell operating companies four
years ago, reiterated in his ruling that the baby Bells should not
be permitted to compete in content-based information services
because they continue to control the local phone networks. With
this advantage, he maintains, the Bells could control the
information services market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0158EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     03-08 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Good Morning' Refuses To `Move'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' remained the top box
office hit last weekend despite heavy pressure from ``Moving,'' a
new movie starring comedian Richard Pryor.
   ``Good Morning'' earned $5.1 million while ``Moving'' earned
more than $4 million in its debut weekend.
   The film stars Pryor as a New York engineer forced to relocate
his family to Boise, Idaho, with more than a little trouble along
the way.
   ``Frantic,'' a thriller from Roman Polanski, earned more than
$3.7 million. The movie about an American heart surgeon whose wife
disappears during a medical conference in Paris stars Harrison Ford
and Betty Buckley.
   The romantic comedy ``Moonstruck'' was in fourth place with $3.2
million, followed by ``Three Men And A Baby,'' which earned more
than $3.1 million in its 14th week, bringing it to a total gross of
$144.2 million for Disney-Touchstone.
   ``Switching Channels,'' a broadcast version of the venerable
newsroom comedy ``The Front Page,'' earned $3.1 million for its
debut week.
   The Tri-Star movie stars Kathleen Turner as a network news
reporter who keeps trying to quit her job, get away from her
ex-husband played by Burt Reynolds, and marry her new love, a
sporting goods company owner played by Chistopher Reeve.
   ``Shoot To Kill,'' a thriller starring Sidney Poitier as an FBI
agent chasing a maniac in the Northwest woods, earned $3.1 million
for seventh place. It was followed by ``Action Jackson'' with $1.8
million.
   ``A Night In The Life of Jimmy Reardon,'' starring ``Stand By
Me'' star River Phoenix, earned $1.4 million for ninth place.
   ``The Last Emperor,'' director Bernardo Bertolucci's Oscar
nominated movie about the China's last emperor, Pu Yi, was in 10th
place with $1.3 million.
