<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Iditarod     03-08 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iditarod,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iditarod Pace Slows With New Snow On Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROHN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fresh snow on the trail continued to slow
the pace of the 1,150-mile Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race as mushers
slogged their way down from the frosted peaks of the Alaska Range.
   On Monday, Jan Masek of Anchorage led a tightly grouped caravan
of more than 20 mushers to Rohn Roadhouse, a remote log-cabin
checkpoint 271 miles from the start in Anchorage.
   Masek arrived at 3:10 p.m., followed eight minutes later by
Lavon Barve of Wasilla. Defending champion Susan Butcher arrived at
3:20 p.m., followed closely by Jerry Austin of St. Michael and
Jacques Philip of Thomery, France.
   Tim Moerlein of Kasilof pulled in at 3:31 p.m., trailed four
minutes later by four-time Iditarod champion Rick Swenson, in
seventh position.
   By 8:30 p.m., half the 52 mushers in the race had made it to
Rohn. The rest were spread the 78 miles back to Finger Lake.
   Racers were slowed by up to 6 inches of new snow as they mushed
down to Rohn from Rainy Pass, at 3,400 feet the highest point along
the trail.
   Rohn is a favorite point for mushers to take the 24-hour layover
required of all mushers sometime during the Anchorage-to-Nome race.
The isolated cabin provides a refuge from spectators and reporters,
and the dogs often are tired from crossing the rugged mountains.
   The race, which started at 9 a.m. Saturday, has been slower than
last year's record-setting pace, when Butcher reached Nome after 11
days, 2 hours on the trail.
   The race is inspired by a 1925 dog sled relay that rushed
diphtheria serum to Nome during an outbreak of the disease. The top
20 mushers will split a purse of $150,000. The winner will get
$30,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
