<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0219EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Polarization     03-08 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Polarization,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Stirs Class Animosity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's strongman, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, is emphasizing class and racial distinctions in
what appears to be an effort to rally support by polarizing society.
   ``The humble, the poor, the blacks, they are the utmost
authority of this people,'' Noriega, commander of the country's
15,000-strong Defense Forces, told a crowd Friday in the provincial
town of Carriazo.
   His regime, under mounting economic pressure from the United
States, has tried to characterize domestic opposition as rich and
white. In government newspapers and on official radio and TV
stations, Noriega's opponents are termed ``oligarchs'' and
``sellouts.''
   ``Whiteys, to the firing squad,'' says graffiti scrawled on
walls in some of this capital's more affluent neighborhoods. The
message is signed VT, for Victoria Torrijista, a populist
organization that reveres the late strongman Omar Torrijos.
   In speeches, Noriega repeatedly invokes Torrijos _ killed in a
1981 airplane crash _ as inspiration for his defiance of Washington.
   VT, like all groups supportive of the Defense Forces' de facto
rule, is subsidized by the government, according to former
government officials now at odds with Noriega.
   Panama, with 2.2 million people, is a racially mixed nation with
African, Indian and European heritage. As is the case throughout
Latin America, people of European or predominantly European
heritage are generally better off than descendants of those their
forefathers conquered or enslaved.
   Compared with the rest of the region, there is a relatively
large middle class. But there is also a big gap between rich and
poor.
   The National Civic Crusade _ an opposition alliance of about 200
business, professional, political and labor groups _ has struggled
to overcome the popular perception of it as representative of
limited and privileged interests.
   In the dining room of the opulent Marriott Hotel, Ernesto
Gonzalez de la Lastra, a leader of the Crusade, rose in response to
a question about the government claim it is ``oligarchic.''
   Gonzalez de la Lastra, in stylish clothes, a Rolex watch
gleaming on his wrist and gold chain around his neck, escorted
Foodworkers' Union official Martin Gonzalez, in humbler garb, to
the table.
   ``I'll let Don Martin answer that,'' said the president of the
Association of Panamanian Executives.
   ``Oligarchy means government by the few,'' said the union man
from a working-class district just outside the capital of Panama
City. ``So the Defense Forces and their government is the real
oligarchy.''
   Noriega does not hold pro-government demonstrations at the
Marriott, and those who attend rallies supporting him are poorer
than the drivers of the cars that join the Crusade's occasional
protest caravans through town. But the opposition has significantly
broadened its appeal.
   ``Noriega tries to represent himself as the standard-bearer of
the poor,'' said Dedys Ramos, saleswoman at a clothing store in the
downtown area. ``But it is the poor who suffer more than anyone
because of him.''
   From a lower-class neighborhood, Mrs. Ramos earns just above the
minimum wage of $150 a month and is an adamant opponent of the
regime.
   Referring to the beginnings of hardship _ including the closure
of banks last week _ resulting from U.S. economic pressure on
Panama, she said:
   ``He (Noriega) is not going to go without. He has food and a
roof. But what about those abuelitos (little grandfathers) who
can't cash their paltry pension checks? That's why you can see me
out there waving my white hankie with the civilistas (Civic Crusade
backers).''
   Supporters of the Civic Crusade, which has spearheaded
opposition to Noriega since its formation in June, wave white
handkerchiefs at their demonstrations.
   A Gallup poll taken in August indicated that nearly 75 percent
of Panamanians would like to see Noriega out.
   A power struggle earlier this month between Noriega and ousted
President Eric Arturo Delvalle sparked the current crisis.
   Noriega loyalists in the National Assembly dismissed Delvalle
Feb. 26, a day after Delvalle had tried to fire Noriega.
   Noriega was indicted last month in Florida on federal drug
trafficking charges. He has denied those accusations.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
