<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-GulfWar     03-08 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Gulf War,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skepticism Meets Soviet Call For Condemnation Of `War Of Cities'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's surprise call for
Security Council condemnation of the Iran-Iraq ``war of the
cities'' was greeted by Western skepticism and renewed U.S. calls
for an arms embargo against Iran.
   Iraq said the U.N. body should stick to its cease-fire
resolution, while Iran supported the Soviet proposal and called
again for condemnation of Iraq.
   ``Under the circumstances, the Security Council has to do
something in order to eliminate the damage of the further
escalation of the military conflict between Iran and Iraq,'' Soviet
Ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov told reporters Monday after
closed-door Security Council consultation.
   But when asked whether the Soviet Union would approve an arms
embargo, he did not reply directly and said more diplomatic efforts
were needed.
   Iran and Iraq, fighting a 7{-year-old war, have fired dozens of
missiles at each other's cities since last Tuesday, killing
hundreds of civilans.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert Okun told reporters after council
consultations that a Soviet resolution on the ``war of the cities''
should not ``undercut or erode'' Security Council Resolution 598 of
July 20 which demanded an immediate cease-fire and provided for
sanctions against the belligerents.
   ``We don't need a new resolution. We need observance of the
resolution which is already in front of us,'' he said.
   The United States has been pushing for an arms embargo against
Iran, and the 15-member Security Council is working on an embargo,
but it has not been approved.
   Iran on Monday again called on the Security Council to condemn
Iraq for escalating the latest round of missile bombardment of
Tehran and Baghdad.
   ``Iraq is trying to spoil the atmosphere for a political
settlement by escalating the current conflict,'' said Iran's acting
ambassador, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati.
   The Iraqi ambassador, Ismat Kittani, told reporters after the
council session that his government will insist the council act
within Resolution 598 and that other action sought by the Soviet
Union be secondary.
   Moscow has been under international pressure to agree to
punitive action against Iran, or both belligerents. It has been
wooing Iran and is reluctant to impose an embargo against the
Tehran government.
   Western diplomats said the new Soviet proposal might be intended
to deflect world criticism, delay an arms embargo resolution by the
council and portray Moscow in a positive light as an initiator of a
strong peace proposal.
   Some of the missiles used by both Iran and Iraq have been made
in the Soviet Union, according to experts. But the Soviet Union
denies that Iraq is using Soviet-made missiles in its bombardment
of Tehran.
   The Soviet ambassador said he expected a meeting on the Soviet
request today or Wednesday, but none was scheduled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
