<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Burns     03-08 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Burns,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>S.F. Chronicle Editor Dies Of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Burns, editor of the San Francisco
Chronicle's editorial page and a respected newsman at the paper for
more than 20 years, has died of cancer at age 51.
   Burns, who first sought care for his illness in August, died
early Monday at his home here with his family by his side.
   Burns held several important positions during his career at the
Chronicle, including City Hall reporter, chief political
correspondent and city editor.
   Former Mayor Dianne Feinstein remembered Burns' ``wonderful
sense of humor, twinkling eyes and sharp wit.''
   ``He was really concerned about what happened to the city,''
said Feinstein, whose career Burns covered. ``If his byline was on
a story, it was reported fairly and squarely.''
   Chronicle Editor and Publisher Richard T. Thieriot said Burns
was ``universally beloved'' at the paper.
   ``As a journalist, Jerry always saw both sides of complex issues
fairly and objectively, and he maintained a solid intellectural
integrity in the editorial pages,'' Thieriot said.
   Burns, who was born in Hollywood on Nov. 28, 1936, graduated in
1958 from the University of Southern California. He later received
a master's degree in journalism from University of California, Los
Angeles.
   After working for the Santa Monica Evening Outlook, he was hired
at the Chronicle in 1964 as a night police reporter
   Three years later, Burns was given the City Hall beat, and in
1976, he was promoted to chief political correspondent. In 1979, he
became city editor and in 1984 editorial page editor.
   Survivors include his wife, Marilyn Burns, a son and daughter.
   A memorial service will be held Thursday at Temple Emanu-el in
San Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
