<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Afghanistan     03-08 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghanistan,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pressure Mounting On Afghan Talks; Rebels Reaffirm Opposition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lede prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a Soviet deadline drawing closer, pressure is
mounting on negotiators seeking a settlement to end the 9-year-old
war in Afghanistan.
   It remained uncertain Monday whether Pakistan, which is
representing the Afghan guerrillas and does not recognize the
Soviet-backed Afghan government, will drop its demand for a
broad-based transitional government to replace the existing regime
after Soviet troops withdraw.
   The transitional government could ensure the safe return of more
than 5 million refugees from Pakistan and Iran because guerrillas
vow to fight on if the Soviet-backed government remains in power.
   Sources close to the talks, which continue today, said the
Afghan government has shown some flexibility, giving hope that a
compromise could be worked out, perhaps with Pakistan signing the
pact in return for assurances that an interim government would be
formed within weeks.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev says Moscow will begin
withdrawing its estimated 115,000 soldiers in mid-May if the accord
is signed by mid-March.
   Pakistani President Zia Ul-Haq was quoted Monday as saying an
Afghan peace accord must and will be signed soon.
   ``There is no question of the accord not going through,'' Zia
was quoted as telling the Gulf News, a United Arab Emirates
newspaper. ``Allowing it to be dropped is no option.''
   Pakistan's chief representative in the peace talks, acting
Foreign Minister Zain Noorani, said Islamabad hopes for Soviet
cooperation, even though his country wants an interim government to
replace the Soviet-backed regime.
   ``It is in their interest, too, to see that there is peace and
calm after they leave,'' said Noorani after talks resumed Monday
after a weekend recess.
   A representative of the largest group in the seven-party
alliance of Moslem guerrillas reiterated on Monday that the
resistance is determined to fight on if a peace deal is struck on
``Moscow's terms.''
   Speaking at a news conference, Professor Abdul Kadir Kariab said
signing the settlement ``in the present shape will be a historic
treason to the Afghan people'' which he said was mourning 1.3
million dead.
   Sources close to the U.N.-sponsored talks, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said negotiators seemed to remain
cautiously optimistic that a peace package can be tied up by next
week.
   They said the slow pace _ with Monday meetings only during the
morning _ did not indicate a deadlock.
   The talks moved speedily last week with agreement announced
Friday on the timetable and logistics of the proposed Soviet troop
withdrawal from Afghanistan. This had been, according to U.N.
mediator Diego Cordovez, the last major ``difference of substance.''
</TEXT>
