<HEAD>Congressman Says Soviets Renege on Pledge to Free
Lithuanian-American</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has confirmed that the
Soviet Union is not allowing Lithuanian-American Povilas
Peciulaitis to emigrate despite a statement last December that he
would be free to leave, according to Rep. Edward Feighan.
   Feighan, D-Ohio, urged Secretary of State George P. Shultz to
quickly intervene and Monday requested a meeting with Soviet
Ambassador Yuri Dubinin. He also sent a letter to Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev asking that the matter be resolved quickly.
   ``They have the audacity to tell us now that it was a mistake,''
Feighan said of the Soviets. ``If the Soviets think I'm going to
stand by and meekly accept this broken promise, they had better
think again.''
   Peciulaitis, 64, was born in Lithuania and exiled to Siberia for
22 years, but his parents were naturalized American citizens.
   Feighan said he fears for Peciulaitis' personal safety, adding
that verbal attacks against the man have recently appeared in
newspapers and on television in Lithuania.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Justice Office Adds 9,800 Former Nazi Guards To Watch List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department's Nazi-hunting unit has
identified 9,800 people as former concentration camp guards and
says it will have them placed on the immigration watch list of
individuals to be barred from the United States.
   The Office of Special Investigations compiled the names with the
assistance of a sophisticated new computer database.
   Names of suspected criminals and Nazi persecutors are
systematically checked against immigration records to determine if
they are in the United States.
   The names of individuals not found to be in this country are
included in the watch list to prevent them from entering.
   A provision of a federal law, known as the Holtzman Amendment,
was invoked when Austrian President Kurt Waldheim was placed on the
watch list last year following a decision by Attorney General Edwin
Meese III.
   OSI has listed thousands of such people in the past few years.
But the 9,800 now to be placed on the watch list of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service ``for serving as
concentration and death camp guards is probably the greatest
number'' to be added at one time, said the office's chief, Neal
Sher.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Would Welcome North Korean Participation in Olympics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States would welcome participation
by North Korean athletes in the Seoul Olympics, according to a
senior U.S. diplomat.
   ``The Olympics would be better off if North Korea chooses to
participate,'' said Assistant Secretary of State Edward Derwinski.
``But time is running out.''
   He added that ``we have nothing but a positive attitude'' toward
participation by Pyongyang.
   Derwinski said Monday the United States will have ``some
additional naval units'' in the region at the time of the September
Olympic Games. Speaking at the U.S. Information Agency's Foreign
Press Center, he said the additional naval presence was ``a very
timely, practical coincidence.''
   Other U.S. officials have said the additional presence probably
will consist of one or two aircraft carriers.
   Derwinski warned that any attempt by the North Koreans to
disrupt the games ``would make them a total pariah.'' North Korea
is one of only a handful of countries, including Cuba, which is
boycotting the games.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gambia To Provide Emergency Landing for Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airport in Gambia will become an emergency
landing site for the space shuttle under a new agreement between
the United States and the African nation.
   Gambia, Africa's smallest nation, is a narrow strip of Mango
grove swamps, no more than 30 miles wide and 200 miles long, that
snakes in from the Atlantic Ocean on the western coast of Africa.
It is surrounded by Senegal.
   Under the agreement, signed Monday by Ambassador Herbert
Horowitz for the United States and M.C. Cham, minister of works and
communications for the government of Gambia, the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration will locate specialized
navigational aids at Banjul airport.
   The landing strip would be used if a failure or poor performance
of rockets causes the shuttle to fall short of the speed needed to
get into orbit.
   Banjul airport is almost directly below the normal flight path
of a shuttle launched into a standard orbit.
</TEXT>
