<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ThrillKilling     03-08 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thrill Killing,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Rests In ``Thrill Killing'' Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for a youth accused of bludgeoning
a classmate to death for a thrill rested their case after
psychiatrists gave conflicting testimony about whether the
defendant had a chronic psychotic disorder.
   Closing arguments were expected to be delivered this afternoon.
   Rod Matthews, 15, of Canton, has admitted killing 14-year-old
Shaun Ouillette, but defense attorneys contend Matthews was unable
to control himself because of a mental disorder aggravated by his
use of a drug prescribed to hyperactive youths.
   Prosecutors say Matthews, who is on trial as an adult, clubbed
Ouillette to death with a baseball bat for a thrill.
   Classmates have testified that Matthews took them to view the
body in a wooded area where it remained for three weeks after the
November 1986 killing.
   Dr. Kenneth Holbert, director of the state's Gaebler Children's
Center in Waltham, testified that while Matthews has had a
long-term mental illness that may have contributed to his behavior,
he should have been able to control his actions the day he killed
Ouillette.
   ``I don't believe he was suffering from a chronic psychotic
disorder,'' Holbert said. ``He could have used his cognitive
strengths to behave in another manner.''
   But Dr. Bernard Yudowitz of Belmont's McLean Hospital said
Matthews ``was suffering from an atypical psychosis which in every
manner impaired his ability to conform his conduct to the standards
of law.''
   Matthews first decided to kill someone after viewing the
videotape Faces of Death, which shows animal and human killings and
tortures, said Yudowitz. He said Matthews' use of the drug Ritalin
may have made it harder for him to control himself.
   Matthews did not kill for reasons of vengeance but ``to get rid
of the urge to kill,'' said Yudowitz, a former director of
Bridgewater State Hospital.
   Yudowitz said he knows of hundreds of cases in which children
and adults are misdiagnosed as hyperactive and given Ritalin.
   ``There is no way of knowing what the exact effect Ritalin had''
on Matthews, said Yudowitz. ``There was a distinct possibility'' it
contributed to a loss of impulse control, he said.
   Assistant Norfolk County District Attorney Peter Casey
questioned the methodical manner with which Matthews approached the
killing of Ouillette and the cover-up of the killing.
   Yudowitz said that the methodical nature of the act ``in no way
contradicts the fact that Rod Matthews is an extremely sick
individual. It's consistent with this boy having a disturbed mind.''
   Former friends have said Matthews told them he wanted to see
what it was like to kill someone. They said he named several
potential victims before settling on Ouillette.
   The teen-agers testified last week about viewing Ouillette's
body only hours after a pre-Thanksgiving pep rally, then bicycling
with Matthews to a shopping mall pizza parlor for a snack.
</TEXT>
