<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthKorea 1stLd-Writethru a0812 03-08 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0812,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Passes Election Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf ``Under the...'' to ADD more
detail of new law, opposition leaders vowing to fight it. Pickup
12th graf pvs ``Differences on...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Democratic Justice Party
declared its new set of election laws passed early Tuesday despite
attempts by members of the opposition to disrupt the National
Assembly session.
   The bill was passed in less than a minute after a plenary
session was called at 2:10 a.m.
   Deputy speaker Chang Sung-man declared it passed when members of
the governing party on the floor said, ``No objection.''
   Opposition lawmakers had tried to stop passage by occupying the
speaker's platform since the previous night. A pushing-and-shoving
contest began when some governing party memebrs tried to remove
them.
   Chang had to use a back door to reach the podium.
   The governing party has 160 of the 276 seats in the National
Assembly, more than the simple majority required to pass the bill.
Assembly officials said they could not say immediately how many
governing party lawmakers were present when the bill was declared
passed, but most were believed to be there.
   Opposition lawmakers protested the passage, but the spokesman
for the governing party said it was unavoidable because the new
constitution requires legislative elections to be held by April 28.
   The trouble was caused by a last-minute opposition demand to
change some parts of the bill, including the the total number of
lawmakers, poll watching in barracks and campaign methods.
   A new system of electing one lawmaker in each constituency
instead of two is at the heart of the proposed changes. That would
handicap the governing party in big cities and the opposition in
rural areas, where there are far more election districts.
   The new bills would increase membership in the National Assembly
to 299.
   Under the proposals, 224 members would be chosen by direct
popular vote and 75 under a proportional system based on each
party's total vote. The opposition wants to increase the number of
lawmakers to more than 330.
   The new legislation also limits the number of campaign rallies
in any district to three joint meetings including all candidates.
It bans any rallies by individual parties, prohibits street
campaigning with loudspeakers and would exclude appearances by
national political leaders.
   Opposition leaders said they would fight to overturn the
sections of the law that limit campaigning, but it was unclear how
they could succeed.
   Differences on election laws have caused friction between the
two main opposition parties. They hope to merge in time for the
legislative election to avoid the defeat they suffered in
December's presidential ballot by running rival candidates.
   They agreed on the new election formula last week, but a dispute
over future leadership created a new split.
   Kim Young-sam's Reunification Democratic Party said rival Kim
Dae-jung must take a back seat in a new party, but Kim Dae-jung's
Party for Peace and Democracy described the demand as ``meddling in
private matters.''
</TEXT>
