<DOCNO> AP880308-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArkBuilder     03-08 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ark Builder,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Builder Trying To Save Ark Before Court-Ordered Deadline To
Destroy It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who built an 80-ton wooden ark from
salvaged timber is dismantling part of the vessel in an effort to
beat a court deadline ordering it off a church's property.
   But Kea Tawana, who calls the ark her ``life's sweat and
blood,'' says she needs more time to move the 86-foot-long craft,
which has been termed a work of art by the American Museum of Folk
Art but an eyesore by the city.
   ``It's consumed 20 years of my life. Short of a miracle ... the
ark is doomed,'' Tawana said.
   Tawana had been working under a March 31 court deadline to move
the ark from the parking lot of the Humanity Baptist Church to
Newark Bay, three-quarters of a mile away. Superior Court Judge
Harry A. Margolis recently extended the deadline until April 15.
   But Tawana, who says she built the ark from oak, hemlock and
pine to live in, not for religious reasons, says she needs more
time to dismantle part of it for the move and obtain Coast Guard
approval of the ship's seaworthiness.
   ``Bad weather this winter prevented work on the ship from
continuing,'' Tawana said, adding that she will ask Margolis at a
March 22 hearing for a 90-day extension. ``April 15 does not give
me enough time to render the ship floatable.''
   Tawana said she plans to sail the ark to the Great Lakes region
and live there, although she did not say where.
   Newark officials have long wanted the ark torn down. The city
went to court over the issue, saying it was an eyesore and health
hazard and violated zoning laws.
   However, Margolis last spring prohibited the city from
destroying it after the American Museum of Folk Art in New York
City wrote to Mayor Sharpe James and Gov. Thomas H. Kean, urging
them to preserve the structure.
   ``The ark is a very important and very rare example of urban
folk art expression,'' said Didi Barrett, the museum's director of
publications.
   The Humanity Baptist Church had allowed Tawana to live on the
property as a caretaker in a ramshackle house next to the ark until
last year, when it ended the relationship, saying that the court
battle over the ark cost too much.
   ``The city wants to drive me out and turn this over to
developers for condominiums,'' Tawana said.
   But Audrey Davidson, assistant corporate counsel for Newark,
said zoning laws are the issue.
   ``I have no idea whether the city is trying to build something
there. All I know is that the structure there is illegal,'' Ms.
Davidson said.
   Tawana said she will cut 4 feet off beams in the ark to reduce
the vessel's height to 17 feet from 21 feet so it will not get
snagged on cables running over streets on the trip to Newark Bay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
