<HEAD>Mercedes Prices to Go Up Average 1.6 Percent in Mid-April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mercedes-Benz of North America has announced its
fourth price increase since March 1987 because of the continuing
weakness of the dollar against the West German mark.
   Mercedes said Monday prices on nine of its 13 models will
increase an average 1.6 percent on cars delivered to dealers
starting April 18.
   The three least expensive Mercedes models, the 190Es, will not
be affected by the increases, which will boost the price of the
next model, the 260 E sedan, to $37,845 from $37,250.
   At the other extreme, the price of 560SEC will jump to $77,065
from $75,850, said Mercedes spokesman A.B. Shuman.
