<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CattleRustling     03-08 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cattle Rustling,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pregnant Cows Stolen By Cattle Rustlers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators searching for the cattle
rustlers who stole 25 cows from a western Illinois farm know they
aren't dealing with amateurs.
   Of the 80 cows at Two Rivers Farm, the thieves took only the
ones that were pregnant.
   ``All had been bred and were ready to calve, some of them within
24 hours,'' state police Sgt. Mike Ernst said Monday.
   ``It would have had to have been somebody familiar with cattle.''
   The cows were stolen late Saturday or early Sunday from a
holding barn 2 miles north of Kingston, Ernst said.
   ``It's in a pretty secluded area,'' he said. ``There's no house
and no house in sight. The nearest house is a half mile away.''
   The mixed-breed cows, which Two Rivers was feeding and housing
for their owners, are more valuable because they are pregnant,
Ernst said.
   ``A calf would be worth at least $150 by itself,'' he said
   Investigators have few leads, Ernst said. There are indications
that a truck was used to haul the cows away, police said.
   The thieves also took a motorcycle, a welder, a saddle, tools
and several bags of orchard grass and clover seed, police said. The
loss of the animals and equipment was valued at $30,000, Ernst said.
</TEXT>
