<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Fashion     03-08 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Fashion,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy's Stylists Clean Up Their Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEONORA DODSWORTH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poufs, ruffles, frills and furbelows are
banished from the fashion scene, say the cream of Italy's designers
showing their fall-winter collections in Milan.
   Coming on strong is a cool, calm and collected look that is both
elongated and elegant. Pants play a major role in preference to
last season's mini skirts.
   The new, haughty look is one which is right up Gianfranco
Ferre's alley. He has always designed with a high-stepping female
in mind rather than a romantic heroine.
   In his show Monday, the dramatic shirts that are his signature
had important, stiffly up-standing collars that jutted forward into
crumb-catcher folds.
   Actress Ali McGraw, who was a guest at the show, said: ``I love
them.''
   Slim pants in smooth wools or crushed velvet provided the
perfect accompaniment to these important shirts.
   Ferre's color choice, in scarlet, black and white, was as
forceful as his fashion statement. He even dyed beaver fur scarlet
for blouses and detachable cuff collars that trimmed coats and
jackets.
   But one red touch he could have done without was the scarlet
eyeshadow daubed on the models' eyelids.
   Big winter coats were cut slim and straight and almost brushed
the ankles. Jackets that were neat and short and minus collars were
wrapped up in matching wool stoles.
   And he had lots of little foxes running down the runway in a
variety of guises, spiralling round sleeves, forming skirts and
curling round necks and hemlines.
   Evenings were largely based on black, looking good on
long-length smartly tailored redingotes that flared into fullness
from a lowered waistline. White lace kerchiefs _ another McGraw
favorite _ spilling from collars and cuffs gave a dandified look.
   Earlier on Monday, leather fashions specialist, Mario Valentino,
was another pants fan but with a difference. He cut them newly
wide-legged and floppy, stemming from a high waistline, in supple
suede.
   Accompanying jackets were also loose and boxy. He took the
padding out of shoulders on a handsome coat in calf that flared out
to its near floor-length hemline.
   And he struck a blow for the return to the straight and narrow
with his super-slender suit comprising a trim little jacket and
pencil-slim, calf-length skirt in glossy leather. Aviators' jackets
and top coats in dark chocolatae brown were treated to fur linings.
   With Ferre and Versace now both creating couture fashions in
addition to their lines of deluxe ready-made styles, there is news
that the fashion house of Andre Laug, which showed in Milan Sunday,
has also reversed its decision to no longer make clothes for
private clients.
   This house, famed for its superb sartorial skills, suspended the
custom-made side of the business for a brief period but now intends
to reinstate it.
   Couture provides a fashion house with allure and gives
invaluable promotional power that can aid other activities
belonging to the same establishment.
   Milan shows swing into their third day today. Highlights are to
include the fabulous furs of the famed Fendi family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0068 </DOCNO>
