<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everywhere Evan L. Mecham goes, people ask
him about his political and legal problems. He tells them he has
none.
   Evan L. Mecham is not the governor of Arizona. He is not facing
impeachment, a recall election or a trial in Superior Court.
   He lives in Denver, owns a liquor distributorship, and in his
travels around the country is constantly telling people, ``No, no,
no, I'm not THAT Evan Mecham.''
   When he first heard that Arizona's Mecham had been elected
governor in November 1986, Colorado's Mecham said he was encouraged.
   ``Well, you would hope some good would come of it,'' said
Mecham, 38. ``I'd hate to run for public office now. My political
aspirations would have to be put on the back burner.''
   To say that he takes the notoriety in stride is an
understatement. A call to his home phone gets the recorded voice of
his daughter, Tiffany, 11.
   ``If you're trying to reach Governor Evan Mecham, you have the
wrong number,'' the recording says. ``However, if you have a
campaign contribution of $300,000 or more and wish to keep it
confidential, please leave your name and number and we'll get back
to you. Thank you for your support.''
   Playing in the background is The Battle Hymn of the Republic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The demolition of the 16-story Travelers Insurance
building provided some surprises for its downtown neighbors. One
was a phenomenon little seen by city dwellers: sunlight.
   A restaurant manager directly across from the rubble-filled site
in Boston's financial district jokingly complained Monday that
light now beats through his floor-to-ceiling windows without the
skyscraper to block it out.
   ``They should start issuing sunglasses to the employees,'' said
manager Frank Strangie, manager of Sandwich Expressions.
   But others in the area weren't amused by the dusty windows,
dirty floors and shattered glass resulting from Sunday's demolition.
   ``There was a little bit more broken glass than we had
expected,'' said Bill Ramsey of Control Demolitions Inc., which
conducted the blast that caused the building to implode, or
collapse inward.
   Up to two dozen windows at Strangie's building were shattered,
said its manager, David Ham.
   ``The whole building is filthy, we have to have it washed
down,'' Strangie said.
   The demolition company has agreed to pay for the cost of
replacing the panes but plans to look at clean-up costs on a
case-by-case basis, Ramsey said.
</TEXT>
