<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-08 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Springlike Weather In Much Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The weather seemed springlike across much of the nation early
today, with mild temperatures and rainshowers common.
   But on Monday, a severe thunderstorm struck north-central Texas,
producing hail an inch in diameter in some places. Lightning
sparked numerous grass fires.
   Milder, springlike thunderstorms developed across parts of
northern Texas and Oklahoma, while showers extended across western
Missouri, western Iowa, parts of Kansas, northwest Oklahoma, the
Texas Panhandle, western Louisiana and southeast Texas. Light rain
covered much of southern Minnesota, Wisconsin and parts of lower
Michigan.
   Rain mixed with sleet and wet snow fell in northern Wisconsin,
while snowfall in the northern Plains diminished late Monday. Some
light snow extended from western Nebraska across parts of the
Dakotas to northern Minnesota. An inch of wet snow was reported at
Duluth, Minn., early today.
   Windy conditions covered portions of the northern and central
high Plains. Winds gusted to between 40 and 50 mph throughout
Monday evening and early today at Rapid City, S.D.
   Other than scattered light rain in western Washington, the
western third of the nation was dry, as was the East Coast and much
of the Southeast.
   Mild temperatures prevailed over much of the nation, and even
the colder air in the Rockies and northern Plains lacked a wintry
punch.
   The high for the nation Monday was 88 at Thermal, Calif.
   The forecast for today called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern and eastern Texas across eastern Oklahoma to the lower and
middle Mississippi Valley; scattered showers from lower Michigan to
Alabama late in the day; rain or snow from northeast New Mexico and
northwest Texas to upper Michigan, with snow likely over Minnesota
and the eastern Dakotas; sunny skies over the Atlantic Coast states
and west of the Rockies, except for light rain spreading into
western Washington state; strong winds over south Texas and the
northern high Plains.
   Much the nation is expected to have highs in the 50s or 60s.
Highs will be in the 30s and 40s from the central Rockies across
the central and northern Plains, from the upper Mississippi Valley
to upper Michigan, and from upstate New York to northern and
central New England; 40s from northern New Mexico to central
Oklahoma; and 70s and lower 80s in California, the desert Southwest
and from southern Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from zero at
Yellowstone, Wyo., to 73 at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 53 cloudy; Boston 34 fair; Buffalo 27 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 47 foggy; Cincinnati 40 fair; Cleveland
32 foggy; Detroit 35 foggy; Miami 71 fair; New York 39 fair;
Philadelphia 35 fair; Pittsburgh 31 foggy; Portland, Maine 30 fair;
Washington 37 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck, N.D. 30 windy; Chicago 47 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 62 fair; Denver 24 fair; Des Moines 43 windy;
Indianapolis 41 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 41 foggy; Nashville 40
fair; New Orleans 63 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 31 fair; Anchorage 29 fair; Las Vegas 44
fair; Los Angeles 56 foggy; Phoenix 56 fair; Salt Lake City 25
fair; San Diego 55 fair; San Francisco 48 fair; Seattle 44 rain.
</TEXT>
