^Independent Voters OK'd For GOP Primary</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has given permission
to unaffiliated voters to cast ballots in the North Carolina
Republican presidential primary, according to state GOP Chairman
Jack Hawke.
   The last-minute ruling clears up confusion that arose last week
when a department official said the state party had failed to
obtain necessary clearance to open its primaries to independents.
   The department said its decision applied only to today's
presidential primary and that the state Republican Party would have
to submit another request for the policy to receive permanent
approval.
   ``We have constantly tried to show that we're a party with an
open door and want people to join us ... and this is just another
step,'' Hawke said at a news conference.
   Hawke declined to predict how many unaffiliated voters would
take advantage of the opportunity or which of the four Republican
presidential hopefuls stood to benefit most from the new policy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Most Washington State Voters Would Replace Caucus With Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly half of Washington state's voters would
prefer to replace the state's existing caucus system with a
presidential primary election, a poll says.
   The sample of 500 registered voters found 48 percent preferred a
primary, 27 percent want to stick with the caucus system and 25
percent with no preference between the two options.
   The poll, conducted Feb. 24-27 for The Seattle Times, had a
margin of error of 5 percent.
   The preference for a primary election was stronger among
Democrats than Republicans and stronger among men than women, the
poll found.
   The caucus method is ``just a good-ol'-boy system,'' said Oliver
Smith, 55, a Renton elementary school teacher. ``I've had friends
that have gone to the caucuses and they weren't given the time of
day unless they were insiders.''
   But Barbara Clark, a mental health therapist from Bainbridge
Island, favored the caucuses.
   ``It gives people a chance to come out and debate things face to
face,'' she said. ``That's more than you get in a primary.''
   The idea of a presidential primary has been introduced
repeatedly in the state Legislature, with no success.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Gets `Condo Boss' Endorsement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis planned to vote in a Boston suburb today, after frenetic
campaigning that included a Super Tuesday endorsement from South
Florida's elderly ``condo boss.''
   Dukakis was picked from among the Democratic contenders who
courted Annie Ackerman, a 74-year-old former Chicago ward organizer
who has a knack for getting out the vote among this area's vast
retirement community.
   ``You have come out to listen to the man who will be the next
president of the United States,'' Mrs. Ackerman told about 500
senior citizens at Point East condominiums Monday. She spoke of
Dukakis' immigrant roots, something he had in common with many of
those at the rally.
   ``My mother would have said he's a mensch,'' Mrs. Ackerman said,
referring to the Yiddish word for good man. ``He's a person of
integrity who gets things done.''
   Dukakis planned to vote this morning, spend a quiet day at his
Statehouse office and then fly to Chicago to begin campaigning for
the Illinois primary.
</TEXT>
