<2ND_LINE>PM-Psychologist Ambushed,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Patient Pleads Guilty to Attempted Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who ambushed and shot her former
psychologist, his wife and young daughter after harassing them for
years pleaded guilty to attempted murder and assault and faces a
mandatory life prison term.
   Kimberly A. Gracyalny, 30, entered her plea Monday before
Municipal Court Judge David M. Horwitz.
   Ms. Gracyalny began harassing David Fox, a neuro-psychology
specialist, and his family soon after he treated her between
November 1982 and March 1983 for an undisclosed problem,
authorities said.
   On Dec. 20, Ms. Gracyalny hid in the front yard of the family's
suburban home and opened fire with a handgun as they returned from
dinner, chasing them around the house to the back yard before the
couple was able to subdue her.
   The attack left Fox, 34, shot in the arm, his wife Deborah, 31,
shot in both legs, and their 6-year-old daughter shot in the left
leg. Three sons, ages 9, 10, and 18 months, were unharmed.
   Under the terms of a plea bargain, Ms. Gracyalny pleaded guilty
to one count of premeditated attempted murder, which carries the
mandatory life term, and two counts of assault. Five additional
premeditated attempted murder counts are to be dropped at the April
5 sentencing.
   In 1986, the psychologist obtained a Superior Court restraining
order against Ms. Gracyalny after she allegedly stalked the family,
made threatening phone calls and trespassed on their property,
sometimes shooting off flashbulbs in front of their windows.
</TEXT>
