<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against nearly all major
currencies in active European trading early today, partly depressed
by a surge in the British pound, dealers said. Gold bullion also
fell.
   Dealers said investors continued to focus on the pound, selling
large amounts of dollars for pounds for a second straight day. They
said it became clear Monday that the Bank of England had not
intervened with substantial sales of pounds to rein in the currency.
   The pound was boosted by strong economic growth and relatively
high interest rates in Britain, dealers said. Sterling rose to
$1.8270 from $1.8135 late Monday, more than 5 cents higher than
Monday's opening.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before it begins in Europe, the
dollar fell to a closing 127.80 Japanese yen from 128.87 yen at
Monday's close. But later in London, the dollar edged back up to
128.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.6755 West German marks, down from 1.6765
   _1.3825 Swiss francs, down from 1.3870
   _5.6730 French francs, down from 5.6880
   _1.8790 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8840
   _1,236.75 Italian lire, down from 1,239.75
   _1.2542 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2562
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $435.60 a troy ounce,
down from $437.20 bid late Monday. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $435.70.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $435.60, down from $436 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell to a closing bid of $438.00,
down from $438.75 late Monday.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $6.38 a troy
ounce, down from $6.42 late Monday.
</TEXT>
