<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeSillers     03-08 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ronnie DeSillers Estate Frozen By Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge froze the remainder of a half million
dollars donated to save liver-transplant patient Ronnie DeSillers
after officials complained that his mother squandered money on a
luxury waterfront apartment, clothes and jewelry.
   ``Immediate and irreparable injury will result to assets of the
estate of Ronald DeSillers Jr. if Maria DeSillers is permitted to
withdraw the funds deposited in the account,'' Dade Circuit Judge
Francis J. Christie wrote in his order Monday.
   When Ronnie died at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh last April
29 at age 7, an account in his name had accumulated $509,913, state
officials said. The account balance on Feb. 17 was $239,288, said
Fred Kerstein, assistant Dade County state attorney.
   ``Our concern was that the remaining assets would be wasted,''
Kerstein said. ``We wanted to safeguard those assets and let the
court determine how they'll be distributed.''
   As recently as Jan. 19, $25,000 was withdrawn from the fund,
said a court document filed by state Attorney General Bob
Butterworth and State Attorney Janet Reno of Miami.
   The state accusation said bank records indicated Ms. DeSillers
spent at least $47,000 on jewelry, clothing, furniture, housing
expenses, an automobile and auto expenses.
   Ronnie, who died last year while awaiting a fourth transplant,
attracted donations from around the country, including $1,000 from
President Reagan, after news reports that money raised by his
classmates had been stolen.
   Ms. DeSillers, who created a foundation to assist other children
in need of organ transplants after her son's death, denied
squandering any of the donations.
   ``Why do they not say that money went to charity?'' Ms.
DeSillers told The Associated Press on Monday night. ``Why do they
not say that some of that money was assigned to me personally? ...
How come they don't say how much of that money went to kids?''
   She said she would straighten out the status of the frozen money
in probate court and use the funds to provide organ transplants for
two children.
   ``There are two children that have less than six months to live,
and that's what I want to do with the money,'' she said.
   Ms. DeSillers' lawyer, Harry Robbins, said his client maintains
she never asked the public to donate money and thus was not legally
a charity. She also has said she was entitled to the money as
Ronnie's sole heir.
   Ms. DeSillers' finances came under question when it was learned
she lived in a luxury apartment building on Biscayne Bay and was
driving a 1985 BMW equipped with a telephone. She contends the car
was second-hand and bought with a loan, that the car telephone was
a gift and the apartment doubled as her office.
   Ms. DeSillers is being sued by Children's Hospital for failing
to pay $261,189 of Ronnie's $424,302 bill. She has charged the
hospital with giving poor care to her son.
</TEXT>
