<HEAD>Soviet Official Cuts Silicon Valley Visit Short</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Gorbachev's chief economic adviser
has cut short his visit to Silicon Valley because of his mother's
death in the Soviet Union.
   Abel Aganbegyan had planned a three-day tour that included
visits to Sun Microsystems and Acuson, both in Mountain View. Sun
Microsystems makes desktop workstations while Acuson produces
medical imaging equipment.
   Aganbegyan held a brief news conference at San Francisco
International Airport on Monday.
   ``American citizens know very little about joint ventures with
the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   The Soviet official said the United States is ``putting up
obstacles in the way of technology transfers. Other countries, such
as Japan, do not.''
   Aganbegyan is an architect of ''perestroika,'' Gorbachev's
wholesale restructuring of the stagnant economy.
   The visit to Santa Clara County was to have been the final part
of an 18-day trip through six American cities to increase interest
among U.S. companies in joint ventures with the Soviets.
