<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChurchShooting     03-08 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church Shooting,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged in Church Shooting Spurned by Former Member</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EMPORIA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who killed one worshipper and wounded
four others in a church shooting spree had been spurned by a former
member of the congregation and talked about her after he was
captured, parishioners said.
   Cheun-phon Ji, 29, a native of Taiwan who earned a master's
degree from Emporia State University in December 1984, was charged
Monday with one count of first-degree murder and six counts of
attempted first-degree murder. Bond was set at $1 million and a
preliminary hearing was scheduled for March 31.
   One person was killed and four wounded in the Sunday morning
shooting spree at Calvary Baptist Church. Parishioners wrestled the
gunman to the ground after a church trustee chased him outside and
struck him with a hymnal.
   As he was being brought to the courthouse Monday past a crowd of
journalists, Ji was asked why the shootings occurred. He shouted,
``Justice, revenge.''
   Church members said Monday that Ji had attended a church service
or Bible study with a woman named Georgia Ann Mejia several years
ago. He apparently was rejected by the woman when he asked her to
marry him, they said.
   Allen Bush, a church trustee, said he and three other men
surrounded Ji outside the church after the shooting.
   ``He said, `Don't you remember? Don't you remember?''' Bush
said. ``We said, `Remember what?' He said, `Georgia.' More than one
of us said, `Georgia who?' At that point he answered, `Georgia
Mejia.'''
   Mejia, 27, was married Nov. 4, 1985 and her name is now Georgia
Ann Johnson, according to court records. She transferred to another
Baptist church about four years ago, her mother said.
</TEXT>
