<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Panama-BankSuit     03-08 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Bank Suit,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Extends Order Restraining Local U.S. Banks From Giving Funds
to Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has tacked an additional 10 days
onto a restraining order preventing two American banks from
transferring an estimated $50 million to the national bank of
Panama.
   On Monday, U.S. District Judge Lloyd F. MacMahon extended the
order he had issued Thursday that prevented three banks from
transacting any business with or transferring funds to the Banco
Nacional de Panama.
   He also said he would sign a stipulation dropping Irving Trust
as the third bank in the suit, which was filed on behalf of the
Republic of Panama at federal court in Manhattan.
   Ousted Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle is still
recognized by the U.S. government as the legitimate head of Panama,
and the order effectively prevents the funds from being transferred
to the regime of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's military
leader.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Kenneth Handal told the court that
Irving Trust had agreed to a permanent injunction against
transferring funds until the situation in Panama has been resolved.
   Lawyers for Marine Midland and Bankers Trust told the court that
the situation in Panama remained unclear and said they would
respect the court's wishes.
   Criminal attorney Barry Slotnick asked to intervene on behalf of
Banco Nacional de Panama because of what he said was Panama's
urgent need for cash. Banks in Panama remained closed for a fifth
day Monday, sparking a demonstration by thousands of retired people
unable to cash their pension checks.
   Last Wednesday another bank, Republic National Bank of New York,
agreed to transfer $10 million to the Federal Reserve Bank.
   Two U.S. grand juries in Florida indicted Noriega on drug
charges Feb. 4. Delvalle sought to dismiss Noriega Feb. 25, but was
ousted the next day by Noriega supporters and went into hiding.
   Last Tuesday, Delvalle froze all Panamanian assets outside the
country.
</TEXT>
