<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LibrarySatan     03-08 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Library Satan,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sheriff Wants List of Occult Readers From Libary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rapides Parish sheriff's office,
trying to find local satanists, has ordered the library here to
turn over a list of people who have checked out books on the occult
in the last year.
   Assistant District Attorney Dexter Ryland said he has advised
Rapides Parish Library officials to withhold the information until
his office can determine if the order is an invasion of privacy.
   ``We are working on it. We haven't formulated our final legal
opinion on it,'' Ryland said Monday. ``It struck me when it was
called to my attention that it could possibly violate the privacy
of individuals.''
   Chief Deputy Tommy Hollingsworth said his office is ``simply
trying to get some intelligence'' on serious followers of satanic
beliefs because ``a lot of times it is connected with narcotics.''
   Lynn Dunn, who works in the sheriff's narcotics office, said the
names and addresses were subpoenaed ``to weed out the curious from
the serious'' followers of satanism.
   It is not an invasion of the readers' privacy ``because no one
is going to be contacted or anything like that,'' she said.
   Hollingsworth said his office is not investigating any specific
incidents involving devil worshippers. The sheriff's office is
simply updating files it has kept for the last 15 years, he said.
   Library Director Stephen Rogge said it is his policy not to
release such information simply on a request, but he could be
forced to comply because of the court order.
   Rogge said he would consider the sheriff's request an invasion
of privacy ``unless there is a good reason for it.'' If the
district attorney's office determines there are not sufficient
grounds to turn over the list, Rogge said he won't do it.
   Rapides Chief of Detectives William Earl Hilton said there may
be some satanic activity in the parish, but so far it has not been
linked to any crime.
</TEXT>
