<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DiplomatArrest     03-08 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diplomat Arrest,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Charged With Simple Assault For Hitting Protester
With Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African diplomat has been
charged with assault after his car hit a protester and a police
officer outside a radio station where he had been interviewed.
   South Burlington Police Chief John Race said South African Vice
Consul Duke Kent Brown was arrested by South Burlington police
Monday about a quarter-mile from the scene of the incident.
   Brown was charged with simple assault, released on his own
recognizance and ordered to appear in court in April. Race said the
charge carries up to a year in prison and a fine of $1,000.
   Police said Brown left the Burlington area following his release
and failed to make three other scheduled appearances.
   Jim Condon, news director at radio station WJOY-WQCR and a
witness to the incident, said the protester who was struck, Laurie
Larson of Richmond, suffered minor bruises.
   Race identified the injured officer as Todd Shepard and said he
had suffered bruises on his leg.
   Race said police had called the State Department in Washington
to ask if Brown was covered by diplomatic immunity and were told
``to treat this case like any other.''
   A spokesman in the South African embassy in Washington, Third
Secretary Heyn Van Rooyen, said Brown is connected with the South
African consulate in New York.
   Van Rooyen said, ``There are different degrees of diplomatic
immunity,'' and he was not sure that consular officials are given
the same degree of protection as those connected with embassies.
   Race said he hoped police could proceed with the case.
``Politics don't enter into the justice system, as far as I'm
concerned.''
   Condon said about 30 members of the Vermont Committee on
Southern Africa had gathered outside the station to protest Brown's
participation in a talk show, ``Viewpoint,'' which was broadcast
beginning at 9 a.m.
   He said Brown left the station under police escort and made his
way to a car in a nearby parking lot. Brown got into the car and a
few of the protesters sat on the hood, Condon said.
   Protesters were climbing off the hood of the car without any
resistance, Condon said, when Brown ``hit the accelerator'' and the
incident occurred.
   Philip Fiermonte, one of the leaders of the protest, said Brown
``shows disregard for humanity, as (South Africa's) apartheid
policies have.''
</TEXT>
