<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Williams,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Stanford Indian Mascot Harry Williams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRESCENT CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry D. Williams, a Yurok Indian
who served as Stanford University's mascot for 21 years until
protests arose against the school's Indian symbol, died on Sunday.
He was 64.
   Williams, who was ``Prince Lighfoot'' from 1951 to 1972, died of
injuries suffered in an automobile accident.
   Williams, a graduate of the University of San Francisco, first
performed an Indian dance at a Stanford rally when he was 27.
   He was such a favorite he was asked to lead the university band
onto the football field, which he did until 1972. In that year, the
school dropped the nickname Indians after complaints of racism,
changing it to Cardinal.
   Williams was active in Indian affairs and served as chairman of
the California Rural Indian Health Board.
</TEXT>
