<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0518 03-08 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Reports Hit On Iranian Tanker; Sides Trade Missile Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Iraqi naval attack, latest missile
exchanges, Soviet call for U.N. comdemnation; edits throughout; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMIR F. GHATTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes hit a ``very big
naval target'' in the Persian Gulf today, breaking a three-week
lull in attacks on Iran's oil shipping.
   The two nations also kept up their brutal barrage of missile
attacks, firing surface-to-surface rockets into each other's
capital cities. Iran accused the United States and France of
helping Iraq refit Soviet-designed missiles to give them enough
range to reach Tehran.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said Iraqi jets struck
``accurately and effectively'' at the naval target off the Iran
coast and returned safely to base.
   It was the first raid on a ``large naval target'' _ Iraq's term
for an Iranian tanker _ since Feb. 16. The last independently
confirmed attack by Iranian warplanes was on Feb. 12.
   The last time that Iran is known to have attacked a ship, in
retaliation for Iraq's air raids on its own shipping, was on Feb.
11.
   Since then, the two belligerents, at war for 7{ years, have
battered each other's capitals with long-range missiles and struck
other population centers with artillery and bombs.
   Hundreds of civilian casualties are believed to have resulted
from the bombardments.
   Also today, Iranian Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani
accused the United States and France of helping Iraq modify
Soviet-made missiles to reach longer-range targets in Iran. Tehran
is 290 miles from the Iraqi border.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported that an
Iraqi missile crashed into a residential neighborhood of Tehran
about midnight, killing or wounding several civilians.
   State-run Baghdad Radio reported that Iraqi gunners fired the
missile into Tehran, a city of 6 million, early today less than an
hour after Iran claimed it lobbed a projectile into Baghdad.
   Tehran Radio said President Ali Khamenei, who visited a bombed
Tehran neighborhood, said ``Our nation will never forget those who
have assisted the criminal in perpetrating its crime.'' Unlike
Rafsanjani, Khamenei did not refer to any specific country.
   Iraq's news agency confirmed the an Iranian missile strike on a
residential area in Baghdad, saying civilians, including women,
children and eldery people, were killed. No figures were given.
   Iran's news agency said Revolutionary Guards today shot a
missile at a ``military center'' at Amarah, an Iraqi town close to
the border and halfway between Baghdad and the southern port city
of Basra.
   The reports were monitored in Nicosia.
   Iraq said it fired three missiles into Tehran on Monday, and
Iran reported its Revolutionary Guards blasted Baghdad with four
missiles and launched a fifth at the northern city of Mosul for the
first time.
   Iraq confirmed only two missiles crashed Monday in Baghdad, a
city of 5 million, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including
women and children.''
   Iraq says it has fired 42 projectiles into Tehran since the
missile duel began.
   The Iranians have reported more than 30 missiles have hit
Tehran. They said Revolutionary Guards fired 25 long-range missiles
on Iraq during that period, 23 of them on Baghdad. The Iraqis have
only acknowledged 19 hits on the capital and one on Mosul.
   Both sides reported air raids on each other's cities and
artillery bombardment of border towns on Monday.
   IRNA said 30 civilians were killed and more than 100 people
wounded in Monday's Iraqi missile attacks on Tehran's residential
areas. It reported one missile demolished a clinic, a school and
several houses.
   Iran has listed at least 122 civilians killed and more than 300
wounded in the Iraqi missile blitz, with more than 100 killed and
more than 500 wounded in air raids over the last week. The Iraqis
have reported heavy civilian casualties, but gave no exact figures.
   Iran last week accused Moscow of supplying Iraq with the
missiles, triggering several violent protests outside the Soviet
Embassy in Tehran and the consulate-general in the central city of
Isfahan. The Soviet Union who, along with France, is main arms
supplier of Iraq, denied the charge.
   The Soviet Union, meanwhile, called for Security Council
condemnation Monday of the war.
   ``Under the circumstances, the Security Council has to do
something in order to eliminate the damage of the further
escalation of the military conflict between Iran and Iraq,'' Soviet
Ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov told reporters.
</TEXT>
