<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0467 03-08 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Concerned About Negative Ads on Super Tuesday Eve</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis voting in top 3 grafs, picking up in 2nd
graf pvs, ``They hurt; also subs 8th graf pvs, Dukakis plans</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis cast his
Democratic primary vote today at his hometown precinct in
Brookline, where he was greeted by neighbors who applauded his
arrival.
   ``It's good to be in this precinct where a great deal of my
political career and my life, really, has been shaped by a lot of
great friends who are here,'' said Dukakis, who was accompanied by
his wife, Kitty, and their daughter, Kara.
   Dukakis had closed his Super Tuesday campaign Monday night,
worrying about the last-minute impact of negative campaign ads
aired by Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore in Texas and North Carolina.
   ``They hurt, there's no question about it,'' Dukakis said as his
campaign plane headed for Boston on Monday night after a day of
campaigning in the South. ``By the time you find out what they're
doing it's too late.''
   Dukakis said of the latest Gore ad, ``It's a piece of garbage.''
   The comments were a final note of concern following an otherwise
upbeat weekend of campaigning that saw large crowds, extensive
media coverage and a few key endorsements.
   Dukakis planned to spend the day at his Statehouse office and
then fly to Chicago to begin campaigning in the next battleground _
Illinois, which holds its primary a week from today.
   In his final stop in the Raleigh-Durham area Monday night,
Dukakis once again rejected the notion that he is the most liberal
of the Democratic candidates, saying he preferred the label
``progressive.''
   Among the positions that have helped pin the label liberal on
Dukakis are his opposition to aid to Nicaraguan Contra rebels, his
opposition to any cuts in social spending, his opposition to a
space-based missile defense system and the Midgetman missile and
his support of closer relations with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   But Dukakis insisted that he has also cut taxes in Massachusetts
_ even though some of those tax cuts occurred over his initial
objections. He said he has balanced nine consecutive budgets and
has cut crime in Massachusetts. In his work with other governors,
he said the most consistently progressive are those from the
Southern states.
   In addition to stops in Miami, Plant City, Fla., and
Raleigh-Durham, Dukakis squeezed 21 television interviews into his
schedule Monday.
   Still, he said, ``Don't let them tell you this is a television
campaign. This is a grass-roots campaign and if we're successful,
it will be because of our organization.''
   The Dukakis organization is recognized as the best-funded and
most extensive in Texas, Florida and Washington state, among the 20
Super Tuesday states holding presidential primaries and caucuses
today. In North Carolina, though, campaign organizers predicted
Dukakis would finish third there behind Jesse Jackson and Gore.
   Dukakis kicked off the day of campaigning in perhaps his most
solid base of support in the South: Miami.
   At a senior citizens rally, Dukakis picked up the coveted
endorsement of 70-year-old Annie Ackerman, not a household name,
but someone with a reputation in Miami for being able to get out
the vote.
   The woman who was a ward organizer for Chicago Mayor Richard
Daley spurned other Democratic suitors and endorsed the
Massachusetts governor at a morning rally attended by about 500
senior citizens.
</TEXT>
