<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Murder-Sleep     03-08 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murder-Sleep,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Goes Without Sleep For Week, Shoots Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who went without sleep for a week
in order to watch over his wife, who reportedly suffered from
Alzheimer's disease, apparently shot her to death and then killed
himself, officials said.
   The bodies of Douglas and Clodene Schofield, both 67, were found
Monday morning at their home in a trailer park, said Butler County
Coroner Pete Tutchtone.
   ``She had gotten to where she was straying away from the
trailer,'' Tutchtone said. ``I guess she had Alzheimer's disease.''
   Tutchtone said Schofield realized he needed help in caring for
his wife, but he could not bear to part with her. ``He didn't want
to put her in a nursing home,'' he said.
   The coroner said neighbors contacted authorities last week after
Mrs. Schofield strayed. ``She walked out of the trailer and got
locked out and neighbors called the sheriff to get her back in,''
he said.
   Neighbors said Schofield had not slept for the week so he could
watch her and keep her from wandering again.
   Alzheimer's disease is a progressive, irreversible neurological
disorder that results in gradual memory loss, impairment of
judgment, disorientation and loss of language skills.
   Tutchtone said Schofield used a .38-caliber handgun to kill his
wife and then himself.
</TEXT>
