<HEAD>Pastor Says Swaggart Scandal Hurting Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PACE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Assemblies of God members have left the
fold or are seeking counseling because of the Rev. Jimmy Swaggart's
alleged sexual misconduct, says a minister who has talked to the
television evangelist.
   ``I hope to God there aren't any more'' sex scandals, added Glyn
Lowery, pastor of Pace Assembly of God in this Pensacola suburb.
``I don't know how we'll stand many more scandals in the Assemblies
of God. It has shaken our movement tremendously.''
   Another Assemblies of God television evanglist, Jim Bakker, was
the subject of earlier reports that he had sex with a church
secretary.
   Lowery was one of about a half-dozen ministers called to Baton
Rouge, La., to counsel Swaggart in the wake of reports he had been
photographed with a prostitute in New Orleans.
   ``He is a broken man,'' Lowery said Sunday. ``As he told me,
`Glyn, nobody could exact any punishment on me greater than that
which I put upon my own self for what I done.' ''
   Church officials have proposed to relieve Swaggart of his
ministry for three months.
   ``Some preachers feel like he needs a year out of the pulpit;
others don't,'' Lowery said. ``For him to stay out of the pulpit
for a year would be a death sentence to his ministry ... but that's
something he should have thought about when he went to New
Orleans.''

