<HEAD>Libya Says It Has Released 130 Foreign Prisoners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Belgian
ambassador. PICKS up 5th graf, `JANA said ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya's official news agency said today 130
foreigners, including one American, have been released from prison
in Libya.
   The JANA news agency report, monitored in Rome, carried
expressions of gratitude from prisoners from West Germany, Italy
and the United States.
   JANA mentioned a ``U.S. prisoner'' and quoted him as expressing
his happiness and gratitude.
   The Belgian ambassador, Camille Reynens, reached by telephone
from Rome, said the American was staying at his residence but
declined to give his name or any details about the case.
   Belgium represents U.S. interests in Libya.
   JANA said the prisoners were released Monday in a ceremony
attended by diplomats from embassies in Tripoli representing the
various prisoners.
   The report did not say what the freed prisoners had been charged
with, but the Italian Foreign Ministry in Rome said three Italians
released were businessmen accused by Libya of defaulting on
contracts.
   The JANA dispatch quoted a Libyan Foreign Ministry official as
telling the diplomats that the prisoner release was an expression
of the ``freedom and liberty'' brought by Libya's 1969 revolution
and evidence of its ``humanitarian aspect.''
   Last week, Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi, driving a
bulldozer, knocked down a wall of a Tripoli prison to release
prisoners as part of an amnesty he declared. JANA said 400
prisoners were freed.
   Gadhafi announced he was releasing all Libyan prisoners except
those accused of plotting with foreign countries.
</TEXT>
