<HEAD>Record Promoter Pleads Innocent to Payola Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former independent record promoter pleaded
innocent to charges he paid more than $200,000 to radio station
program directors to get his records on the air.
   William Craig, 42, of Scottsdale, Ariz., also is accused of
deducting the alleged payments from his corporate income taxes.
   Trial was set for May 3.
   Also Monday, Ralph and Valerie Tashjian were ordered to enter
pleas next week on similar payola charges.
   Ralph Tashjian is accused of giving cash and cocaine to radio
program directors in Fresno and El Paso, Texas. He and his wife are
charged with evading taxes on $300,000 in corporate income between
1983-85.
   Craig, who is free on $50,000 bail, the Tashjians and a former
Los Angeles radio station vice president and general manager,
George Wilson Crowell, also known as George Wilson, were named in a
Feb. 26 indictment that culminated a two-year grand jury probe into
payola allegations.
   Crowell faces arraignment next week.
