<HEAD>Man Holds Both Wives, 13 Sons At Gunpoint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kuwaiti held his two wives and 13 sons at
gunpoint for more than two days and fired randomly at police,
injuring one man, before surrendering, the Interior Ministry said
today.
   Nasser Farraj al-Rukeibi released his family members unharmed
and gave up late Monday, a ministry spokesman said. One of the
women was eight months pregnant and the eldest of the sons was less
than 7 years old.
   Police were interrogating al-Rukeibi to determine his motives
but they did not think the 58-hour standoff was related to his
polygamous marriage, sources said. Al-Rukeibi, a Moslem, is
permittted by Islamic law to have up to four wives.
   One neighbor was slightly injured by a stray bullet when
al-Rukeibi began firing in response to police attempts to talk him
into releasing the hostages.
   Police and special forces staked out the family home and used
bullhorns to negotiate with al-Rukeibi. Authorities said he
threatened to kill his wives and sons if the house was stormed.
   The sources, who could not be named under police regulations,
said the standoff began Saturday morning when al-Rukeibi clashed
with his personnel manager at the Ministry of Communications where
he is employed.
   Al-Rukeibi pulled out a revolver and opened fire, but no
injuries were reported. He then rushed to his car and drove to his
home at Firdous, a suburb 10 miles north of the city center, where
took his wives and sons hostage.
</TEXT>
