<1ST_LINE>r w PM-USHostages     03-08 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Hostages,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother of Hostage Says Hostages Should Be Campaign Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother of an American being held hostage
in Lebanon said today he thinks the hostages should be an issue
discussed by the U.S. presidential candidates.
   ``They have never mentioned a word,'' said Anthony Cicippio,
whose brother, Joseph, has been held for 18 months.
   ``I think they're treating it like a hot potato. They're just
laying off of it,'' he said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.''
   He also chided members of Congress for what he said was a lack
of concern for the hostages.
   ``We sent 300 letters to the congressmen and senators over the
last six months and, through that time, we've only received 13
replies,'' he said. One of them, whom he did not identify, asked
for a campaign contribution, said Cicippio, of Norristown, Pa.
   ``I live on hope,'' said Peggy Say, who joined Cicippio on the
program. Her brother, Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, was abducted March 16, 1985.
He has been held longer than any of the nine Americans in captivity.
   Mrs. Say said increased activity involving the search for Lt.
Col. William Higgins, who was kidnapped three weeks ago, gives her
some hope. But she said the hostage families should not ``have to
wait for a time when we could attach ourselves to a larger issue.''
   ``I think the (Reagan) administration is consistently saying
this is too complicated and that quiet diplomacy is the answer.
None of these things are acceptable any more,'' said Mrs. Say, of
Batavia, N.Y.
   She noted that a ceremony will be held in Washington March 16 to
mark the third anniversary of her brother's abduction. The event,
sponsored by No Greater Love, a humanitarian organization, and the
Journalists' Committee to Free Terry Anderson, is to be duplicated
in other areas across the country and is indicative of a growing
grass-roots movement to gain the hostages' freedom, she said.
   ``It's a human rights violation and I think Americans are
unwilling to be silent any more about it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
