<1ST_LINE>r n PM-KlanVisit     03-08 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Klan Visit,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest Visit to KU By Klan Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appearance by two members of the Ku
Klux Klan at a free speech forum turned into a massive
demonstration at the University of Kansas as protesters waved signs
and shouted slogans.
   An estimated 3,000 people, some shouting ``KKK not today'' and
``Don't go in,'' protested outside Monday night as about 2,000
people gathered inside Hoch Auditorium.
   No serious violence was reported, but several windows were
broken as protesters tried to push their way into the auditorium.
Police wearing riot gear guarded the entrances to the building,
breaking up one shouting match and ejecting another person.
   The forum was delayed for about 20 minutes when eight black
ministers from Lawrence and Kansas City stood up and began singing
spirituals. The audience joined in and gave the ministers two
standing ovations before the forum began.
   The ministers continued singing throughout most of the evening
before marching out a side door in protest.
   One of the Klan members, Thom Robb, of Harrison, Ark., accused
the ministers of stifling free speech.
   ``These people are so filled with hatred and bigotry they refuse
to let you hear us,'' said Robb, national chaplain of the Knights
of the Ku Klux Klan. He was accompanied by J. Allen Moran, Exalted
Cyclops of the Missouri Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.
   Allan Hanson, a professor of anthropology participating in the
forum, told the students to listen to the Klan members and make up
their own minds.
   ``If you find the ideas here are ugly or twisted, use your own
judgment and freedom of expression to tell other people that,''
Hanson said.
   Another participant, journalism professor Ted Frederickson, said
he wanted to stand up for free speech, even though the Klan had
denied that right to people working for civil rights in the South.
   ``Those people were met with bombs and guns and fists and
violence,'' he said. ``But I believe in free expression, even for
the Klan.''
   Michael Foubert, a graduate student and head of the group that
sponsored the forum, said he invited the KKK members to the campus
as a way of examining whether a university should support free
speech for all viewpoints.
   Foubert, director of ``Slightly Older Americans for Freedom,''
organized the forum after faculty members last month canceled a
planned visit to campus by two Klan members. The two had been
scheduled to speak to a journalism class for an exercise on
reporting on extremist groups and participate in a student radio
talk show.
   Black ministers in the Lawrence area and the Black Student Union
had opposed the visit.
   David Ambler, KU vice chancellor for student affairs, said the
university did not interfere with the forum because it was
sponsored by a student organization.
   ``Students have a right to explore ideas. We're obligated to
protect that right,'' Ambler said. ``I hope a lot of learning goes
on tonight.''
   Mia Crawford, a black student from Kansas City, Kan., said she
wasn't concerned that the Klan would recruit any students.
   ``I'm against the KKK but they do have a right to speak,'' she
said. ``I think a lot of people are here just out of curiosity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
