<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolIrritant     03-08 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Irritant,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>91 Students Treated for Mysterious Rash-Like Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST COVINA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ninety-one junior high school
students were sent to hospitals after a mysterious irritant caused
rashes, blisters and breathing difficulties during physical
education classes, authorities said today.
   Chemicals were ruled out after a grounds check at Rincon Junior
High School on Monday and experts were concentrating on water
contamination as a possible cause, said Diane Ho, a spokeswoman for
the Rowland Unified School District.
   ``It is a mystery,'' said Anastacio Medina, chief of the county
health department's hazardous materials control program.
   All but one of the seventh- and eighth-grade students were
treated and released from hospitals by mid-afternoon, authorities
said. One student, who was not identified, was kept overnight for
observation of an asthmatic condition at Inter-Community Medical
Center in Covina, a nursing supervisor said today.
   Paramedics accompanied students in ambulances and school buses
to the hospitals after the first symptoms were reported Monday
morning, said West Covina police Lt. Clint Collins.
   The 700-student campus is part of the Rowland Unified School
District in West Covina, about 30 miles east of Los Angeles.
   Experts from the San Gabriel Valley Fire Authority, the public
health department, the Department of Agriculture and the Walnut
Water District were called in to find the problem after the
students started reporting swollen eyes, rashes, blisters or
stomach cramps, Ms. Ho said.
   All of the youths had participated in one of three periods of
physical education classes.
   ``We found no chemicals on the playgrounds,'' Ms. Ho said,
adding that a couple of fleas were found in a grassy field area but
none was known to cause such an intense reaction.
   None of the school's teachers or other adult employees
experienced any symptoms, she said.
   The playgrounds were closed to all students after the outbreak
was initially reported, but the rest of the school remained open.
</TEXT>
