<HEAD>CBS Head `Remarkably Improved,' Released from Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. Chairman William Paley, who underwent
emergency gall bladder surgery last month, was released from a
hospital today after making a remarkable recovery, a spokeswoman
said.
   Paley, 86, was in critical condition following his Feb. 11
surgery at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center.
   Hospital spokeswoman Myrna Manners said Paley had ``remarkably
improved after one month in the hospital,'' and the network's
founder was sent home this morning.
   Paley bought the Columbia Broadcasting System, a fledgling radio
network, in 1928. He controlled it for more than half a century,
turning over the reins in 1983.
   When CBS's biggest stockholder, Loew's Corp., became unhappy
with his successor's policies, Paley teamed with Loew's chairman
Lawrence Tisch to retake control in 1986.
  
