<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MayorResigns     03-08 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayor Resigns,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danville Mayor Quits Amid Criminal Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor has announced his resignation
amid a criminal probe into the handling of client funds in his
private law practice.
   The town council will decide on March 21 whether to appoint a
replacement for Richard Kennett or call a special election. Kennett
also resigned his position as a council member.
   ``Please accept my deepest and most sincere apology for any
embarrassment and adverse publicity which in any way reflects
poorly on our town, its staff or council,'' Kennett said in a
resignation letter dated Friday.
   The letter did not mention a Contra Costa County District
Attorney's investigation into Kennett's practice, officials said.
Kennett has said his attorney has advised him not to comment on the
probe.
   District Attorney Gary Yancey also refused comment because the
case involved an ``ongoing investigation.''
   Kennett's attorney, William Gagen, said at least part of the
investigation stems from checks sent to Debbie Peterson of Spokane,
Wash.
   Peterson had hired Kennett to settle her deceased mother's
estate; the investigation involves checks that allegedly bounced.
   The State Bar of California has ruled in a separate case that
Kennett failed to represent a client in divorce proceedings in a
timely manner, had neglected the case of another client, and had
failed to respond to inquiries from the State Bar about these
complaints.
   That ruling is going to the State Bar's review panel for a
recommendation on disciplinary action.
   Kennett, 49, was elected to the Danville Town Council in
November 1985 and was named by fellow council members to a one-year
mayor's term last December. Danville is a suburban town of 7,000
about 20 miles east of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
