<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DiabetesBoy     03-08 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diabetes Boy,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Charged In Death of Diabetic Boy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAITH CONROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former leaders of a strict religious
group have surrendered their passports and agreed to stay in the
United States pending trial on charges involving the death of a
10-year-old diabetic boy.
   Doug Kleber and Jeffrey Siegel, both of Champaign, Ill., posted
$2,500 bond after being charged with second-degree criminal
mistreatment and were released from the Spokane County Jail Monday,
officials said.
   Kleber, former national leader of the so-called ``No Name
Fellowship,'' and Siegel, former head elder of the Spokane branch,
are among seven people being investigated in the Dec. 20 death of
Aaron Norman. An autopsy determined the boy died from untreated
juvenile diabetes.
   At issue is whether the Normans and church leaders knew the boy
was seriously ill but withheld medical care because of their
religious beliefs. Leaders have said the church believes in the
power of prayer, and former members say the church distrusts
doctors and institutionalized medicine.
   The boy's parents, Bob and Judith Norman, are being investigated
for homicide by abuse, said county Deputy Prosecutor Clark Colwell.
   The Normans did not seek medical help prior to the child's
death, but contacted church leaders after trying unsuccessfully to
revive the boy using cardiopulmonary resuscitation, according to
sheriff's deputies.
   The boy was disciplined by spanking on the advice of church
leaders the day before he died, authorities say. A pathologist
determined the spanking did not contribute to the boy's death but
said bruises were found on his buttocks and legs.
   Kleber has said that neither he nor the Normans knew the boy was
seriously ill and that they would have taken him to a doctor if
they had known.
   The Normans have been members of the Spokane fellowship since it
started in in 1981, but the branch announced last weekend it had
disbanded.
   Since the boy's death, the Normans' youngest son, 8-year-old
David, has been put in foster care by state officials.
   Three others charged with criminal mistreatment are Mark Roloff,
33, the head elder of the former Spokane branch, and church members
John Johnson, 37, and Steve Arden of Spokane, Colwell said.
   Arraignment for all defendants will be scheduled in the next
several weeks in Superior Court, officials said.
   The church said it has about 200 members in Spokane; Champaign;
Plano, Texas; and Passaic, N.J. It was formed in the 1970s in
Illinois primarily as a Bible-study group for athletes.
</TEXT>
