<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Students     03-08 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Students,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Demonstrate For Rights On Anniversary Of '68 Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition spokesman said riot police
clashed today with hundreds of student protesters in Krakow, while
at Warsaw University thousands of students demonstrated peacefully
to demand greater academic freedom.
   About 70 to 100 people were detained in Krakow, but police began
releasing them by early afternoon, opposition activist Zygmunt
Lenyk said. He said at least three people were severely beaten by
police.
   The demonstrations coincided with the anniversary of March 8,
1968, student protests at Warsaw University against censorship and
political repression, which were brutally broken up by police and
Communist Party worker activists.
   This year's protests reflected a renewed campaign by student
activists urging Communist authorities to legalize the Independent
Students Union, known as NZS, which was outlawed following the
December 1981 martial law crackdown on the independent labor
federation Solidarity.
   At Krakow's Jagiellonian University, about 700 students tried to
march to the main square in the city's Old Town following a noon
campus rally organized by the NZS, but found the street cordoned
off by police, Lenyk said.
   Lenyk, quoting eyewitness accounts, said police attacked the
crowd with clubs, but some demonstrators pushed their way through
police lines to reach the square, where they were detained.
   He said most of the students returned to campus and tried twice
more to march to the square, about 500 yards away, but each time
were attacked by police.
   A government spokesman, asked about the reported clash and
violence, said he had no information and promised to look into the
matter.
   At Warsaw University, police did not intervene as more than
2,000 students peacefully demonstrated without leaving campus.
   Students and university workers, carrying dozens of banners
demanding legalization of the NZS and Solidarity free trade union,
marched to a campus carrying a plaque commemorating the 1968
protests.
   The plaque was put up in March 1981 when both Solidarity and the
NZS functioned legally.
   University authorities allowed the rally, but the campus' main
gates were locked and security guards kept non-university personnel
from entering.
   After students and faculty members laid wreaths under the
plaque, campus NZS leaders stood on top of a wall to take turns
speaking to the crowd through a bullhorn.
</TEXT>
