<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Hermit 1stLd-Writethru a0523 03-08 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Hermit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hermit of Chestnut Hill Found Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 3 grafs, autopsy results</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The hermit of Chestnut Hill,'' who lived in
makeshift huts on government land for nearly two decades and
resisted well-publicized efforts to relocate him, died the way he
would have wanted, says a friend.
   ``He died free, so to speak,'' said Clyde Raymond. ``He had his
own drummer and stuck with it.''
   Bill Britt, 52, had been dead for several months when he was
found Monday by two of his three childen, Ingrid Boughner of
Belmont and Britton Steven Boughner of Medford, Boston police
spokesman Scott Gillis.
   His body, dressed in multiple layers of clothing, was almost
skeletal because of decomposition and animals, Gillis said.
   Dr. Stanton Kessler of the Suffolk County Medical Examiner's
office said today that autopsy results showed Britt died of
hypothermia. He said identification of the body was
``presumptive,'' because rats had eaten away most of Britt's face
and other exposed areas.
   Kessler said Britt's feet were found dug into the ground, as if
to gain some warmth.
   Born Britton William Boughner in wealthy Chestnut Hill, Britt
had lived on nearby land controlled by the Metropolitan District
Commission since 1969. His hut was about 30 feet inside the fence
surrounding Evergreen Cemetery, in the area of a large reservoir on
the Boston-Brookline border.
   ``In his case, he felt that this was where he wanted to live,
this was his estate,'' said Raymond.
   In 1985, officials started trying to move Britt, who was legally
blind and lived on money from collecting cans and bottles for the
deposits. When he refused welfare and several attempts to relocate
him to public or subsidized housing, the news media dubbed him
``the hermit on Chestnut Hill.''
   In May, Britt's plastic and wood wigwam was destroyed in a fire.
He was in New York City at the time appearing on the ``Late Night
with David Letterman'' television show because of the publicity his
case attracted.
   State Appeals Court Judge Edith Fine issued a stay preventing
authorities from removing Britt from the property. But when the
appeals court order expired in July, officials removed his rebuilt
wigwam and his belongings.
   Britt rebuilt it again despite deteriorating health. An
opthalmologist testified at a Housing Court hearing a year ago that
Britt had ulcers and he needed a corneal transplant. Also, Britt
was nearly toothless.
   Last year, he said he was writing a ``Hermit's Cookbook,'' but
the manuscript and other papers relating to his legal battles were
lost in the May fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
