<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0569,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briton, Syrian Aide Freed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs with quotes from Coleridge. Picks up 11th
graf pvs ``Today's release.. ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British relief worker and his Syrian
aide were freed today, five days after being taken captive in south
Lebanon, a Sunni Moslem leader said.
   The Briton, Peter Coleridge, told reporters in the southern port
city of Sidon that there had been ``no kidnapping'' and that he and
Omar Traboulsi were detained because they took photographs without
authorization.
   Mustafa Saad, the Sunni leader whose militia controls Sidon,
said Palestinian guerrillas freed Coleridge, the 44-year-old Middle
East coordinator of the British Oxfam relief agency, and Traboulsi,
a 31-year-old Syrian who is the agency's representative in Lebanon.
They were taken captive Thursday at Sidon's Ein el-Hilweh
Palestinian refugee camp.
   Saad said by telephone that representatives of
Fatah-Revolutionary Council, the radical faction headed by Abu
Nidal, turned the two captives over to him at his house in Sidon at
3:50 p.m.
   The release of Coleridge and Traboulsi leaves 22 foreigners
missing and presumed kidnapped in Lebanon. They are nine Americans,
four Frenchmen, three Britons, one Irishman, one Italian, one West
German, one Indian, and two unidentified men. The longest held is
Terry A. Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Lebanese security sources have said Abu Nidal's guerrillas
seized Coleride and Traboulsi when they saw Coleridge taking
pictures of parts of Ein el-Hilweh.
   ``I made a mistake by not asking for a permission (to shoot
pictures) from the authority in Ein el-Hilweh,'' Coleridge told
reporters at Saad's home.
   ``I know and respect the people who took us. There has been no
kidnapping. It was clear from the beginning that I made a mistake.
They were only applying security procedures,'' he said.
   Coleridge, clean-shaven and dressed in dark blue trousers and a
beige jacket, said he ``didn't lose hope'' during his captivity.
   ``We were well treated. We were held at around 4 p.m. Thursday
near the place we photographed in Ein el-Hilweh. Three hours later
they moved us blindfolded to another place. Omar and I were in
separate rooms all the time,'' he added.
   Traboulsi did not talk to reporters.
   Today's release came one week after two U.N. relief workers were
freed in southern Lebanon.
   Jan Stening of Sweden and William Jorgensen of Norway had been
abducted near the south Lebanon's provincial capital of Sidon Feb.
5. They were freed March 1.
   Their employer, the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, said today it
would consider resuming some of its activities in the war-torn
country.
   But UNRWA, in a statement released in Vienna, Austria, said it
would not resume full operations in Lebanon without minimum
guarantees of security for its foreign workers there.
   UNRWA cares for Palestinian refugees in the Middle East.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
