<HEAD>Trophy Hunters Kill Rare Indian Antelope at Animal Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trophy hunters killed a rare Indian
antelope at an animal park with a crossbow, then beheaded it,
police said.
   It was the second such incident since 1983 at the Symbio Animal
Gardens at Stanwell Park south of Sydney, police said Monday.
   ``I suppose they will stick the head on a wall and boast about
it,'' said park owner Bob Grover. ``They probably wanted it because
of its long, spiraling horns.''
   The antelope, named Rajah, was beloved by the thousands of
children who visited each year. The park staff said its mate,
Rajeesh, was pining for its companion.
   Police said the poachers also skinned the animal after shooting
it at close range.
</TEXT>
