<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Satellite     03-08 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Satellite,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Successfully Launches 22nd Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has successfully launched into orbit its
22nd satellite, a synchronous communications satellite, it was
reported Tuesday.
   The nationally televised evening news showed a Long March 3
rocket blasting off Monday night from a launch site in Xichuang,
Sichuan province.
   Acting Premier Li Peng, who was shown with military leaders
watching the launch of the telecommunications satellite, later
congratulated scientists and technicians on its success.
   The Long March 3 is China's most sophisticated rocket.
   Reports have said the three-stage rocket's launch capabilities
were nearly doubled last year, and it can now put a payload of 2{
tons into geosynchronous orbit 22,320 miles above Earth.
   China launched its first satellite in 1970 and has recovered all
10 of the retrievable satellites it put into space.
   It began offering launch services for foreign countries last
year. Two U.S. companies have contracted with China to launch
communications satellites this year. China also is to put a
Norwegian satellite into orbit in 1991.
</TEXT>
