<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-People-Chou-Widow     03-08 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Chou-Widow,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chou En-lai's Widow Resigns as Head of Advisory Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deng Yingchao, widow of Premier Chou En-lai and
one of China's most respected women, will resign as head of a
prestigious advisory body, it was reported Tuesday.
   Deng, 84, will be among 600 people who will give up their seats
on the national committee of the China People's Political
Consultative Conference, which will hold its annual session from
March 24, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   She told a meeting of the conference's Standing Committee the
resignations will revitalize the advisory body, which is made up of
prominent members from the Communist Party, non-Communist groups
and mass organizations.
   The Standing Committee approved a list of 2,081 for the new
national committee, Xinhua said.
   At the age of 21, Deng joined the party and married Chou. She
was one of only about 50 women to complete the 7,750-mile Long
March in 1934-35.
   After Chou's death in 1976, she began to play a more prominent
role in politics, gaining a seat on the policy-making Politburo in
1978.
   Often referred to as China's ``elder sister,'' she and Chou
adopted about 10 war orphans, including acting Premier Li Peng.
   The report did not say who would succeed her.
</TEXT>
