<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1235EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--NaziHunt     03-08 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nazi Hunt,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 1,100 Ongoing Investigations For Nazi War Crimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUDWIGSBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German prosecutors are
investigating more than 1,100 cases of suspected Nazi war crimes,
the country's chief Nazi hunter said Tuesday.
   ``There are still formal investigations of 1,164 persons,'' said
prosecutor Alfred Streim, chief of West Germany's office for Nazi
war crimes investigations.
   Streim's office in the southern city of Ludwigsburg also has
checked out 18,000 names on a list of possible war crimes suspects
received from the United Nations War Crimes Commission archives in
1986, the statement said.
   In January, Streim said he had added 10 prosecutors to his staff
to help with the increased workload in investigating 4,500 war
crimes suspects from the U.N. list. The rest of the suspects had
either died, or had been cleared or convicted in previous trials.
   According to federal statistics, 91,481 people have been
investigated by West German officials since the end of World War
II, with 6,482 ending in convictions. Of those, 12 were sentenced
to death, 160 to life imprisonment, and the rest to lesser
punishment, the statement said.
</TEXT>
