<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Feinstein-CalPoll     03-08 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Feinstein-Cal Poll,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cal Poll Shows Feinstein Stands Good Chance for Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Dianne Feinstein would stand a
good chance of winning the Democratic nomination for governor in
1990, according to a California Poll released Tuesday.
   The poll showed Feinstein leading Attorney General John Van de
Kamp, state schools Superintendent Bill Honig and Controller Gary
Davis among registered Democrats questioned.
   None of the Democrats has announced plans for 1990, and Gov.
George Deukmejian, a Republican, has not said if he will seek a
third term.
   Feinstein had the support of 47 percent of Democrats in Northern
California and 25 percent in Southern California. She was the first
pick of 34 percent statewide.
   Van de Kamp was the favorite of 34 percent of Southern
California Democrats, 13 percent in the north and 26 percent
statewide. Honig was picked by 12 percent statewide and Davis by 10
percent.
   The poll found that Feinstein was the choice of 42 percent of
all registered voters while Deukmejian was favored by 48 percent.
Ten percent of those questioned were undecided.
   The survey of 769 registered voters was conducted Feb. 17-21 and
has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.6 percent. The Democratic
gubernatorial preference of 356 registered Democrats had an error
margin of plus or minus 5.2 percent.
</TEXT>
