<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     03-08 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Rams New Elections Laws Through Legislature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo's ruling party
rammed its version of a new election law through the National
Assembly on Tuesday with an impromptu voice vote, clearing the way
for crucial legislative elections.
   After the law was passed during an unruly assembly session that
drew shouts of outrage from opposition lawmakers, officials of the
ruling Democratic Justice Party said National Assembly elections
would be held about April 20.
   The two sides squabbled over the legislation for hours when Vice
National Assembly Speaker Chang Sung-man, protected by guards, went
to the podium, called for a voice vote and quickly declared the
bill passed.
   Opposition lawmakers tried to block the move but were caught off
guard. Some rushed the podium but were stopped by guards. A brief
scuffle broke out between ruling and opposition lawmakers, but
nobody was hurt.
   ``It is regrettable that the assembly could not proceed
smoothly, although we made concessions up until the last minute,''
said Democratic Justice Party spokesman You Kyung-hyun.
   You said his party had to pass the bill before the current
assembly session ended Tuesday in order to hold the general
elections by April 28, the legal deadline. He said at least 35 days
are needed to prepare.
   But Kim Tae-ryong, spokesman for tMinister Wu Xueqian, said the United
States and China
``have a very cordial relationship between ... and we want to
continue it.''
   As the two leaders posed for pictures in the Oval Office, a
reporter asked Reagan if he would urge China to stop selling
Silkworm missiles to Iran. ``We're going to be talking about a
great many things,'' Reagan replied.
   When the reporter asked if their talks would involve the
Silkworms, Reagan replied, ``You know the rules,'' apparently
suggesting that reporters should not ask questions.
   Wu met Monday with Secretary of State George P. Shultz and with
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci.
   During toasts following a State Department luncheon on Monday,
Shultz and Wu hailed the progress in bilateal relations and made
almost no reference to issues dividing them.
   Chief among those issues is China's reported sales of military
weaponry to Iran in defiance of U.S. efforts at the United Nations
to win support for a worldwide arms embargo against Iran.
   The administration has been seeking assurances from China that
it will not veto an embargo resolution.
   Last October, the United States retaliated against China for
selling Silkworm anti-ship missiles to Iran by suspending the
process under which China had been given increasing access to U.S.
products with advanced technology.
   Since then, China has said it has stopped selling Silkworms to
Iran.
   Shultz made no reference in his remarks to recent anti-Chinese
rioting in Tibet. State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
between three and nine people are believed to have been killed, and
he expressed deep concern over the human rights situation in Tibet.
</TEXT>
