<HEAD>Church Sued Over Spider Bite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claims he was bitten by a
black widow spider during a church bingo game has sued the church.
   Kevin W. Leonard is suing Holy Spirit Catholic Church for
$1,004.91 in medical bills, $67 in lost wages and an unspecified
amount for physical pain and mental anguish.
   Leonard said he was bitten on the lower leg as he sat at a bingo
table last June. A doctor later diagnosed the bite as having come
from a black widow spider, according to Matt Parmenter, Leonard's
attorney.
   The spider's venom can affect the central nervous system,
although it is generally not fatal to adults.
   The suit claims negligence on the part of the church and the
diocese.
   The Rev. Patrick Foster, pastor of Holy Spirit, declined to
comment on the suit, filed Friday in Vanderburgh Superior Court.
