<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FieryCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 03-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiery Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0557,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Die in Four-Vehicle Collision in Arizona</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with new police report, correcting driver to
man, sted woman, that mother was riding in motor home and not in
lead car, deleting reference to motor home impaled on pipe, adding
ID</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WIKIEUP, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man driving his four grandchildren to a
family reunion hit a tractor-trailer rig, causing a four-vehicle
pileup and fire that killed him, the children and his wife,
officials said.
   The death toll of seven also included another woman who was
driving a pilot truck behind the tractor-trailer on the narrow,
twisting section of U.S. 93 near this remote western Arizona
community on Monday, authorities said.
   The children's mother, Susan E. Stone, 24, of Las Vegas, was the
only occupant of the motor home to survive the crash. She was taken
to a hospital in nearby Kingman for treatment of shock.
   Stone's husband was driving ahead of the motor home and was not
injured, officials said.
   Investigators at the scene found the dead burned beyond
recognition, said Sgt. Allan Schmidt of the state Department of
Public Safety.
   Jim Bell, an engineer for the Hualapai Fire District, said the
Glovers and Stones were en route from Nevada to a family reunion in
Phoenix.
   Schmidt said investigators determined that the motor home was
southbound on U.S. 93 when it apparently swerved off the right side
of the highway, over-corrected and came back onto the roadway and
struck the trailer portion of the northbound semi-truck.
   The motor home then hit the pilot pickup truck, pushing the
pickup back into a fourth vehicle that was following behind it,
said Schmidt. The motor home, pickup and the fourth vehicle then
burst into flames.
   Schmidt said the driver of the fourth vehicle escaped injury, as
did the driver of the tractor-trailer rig.
   U.S. 93, part of the most direct route between Phoenix and Las
Vegas, Nev., was not completely reopened to traffic until early
today.
   The six occupants of the motor home who were killed have been
identified as Omer L. Glover, 63; his wife, Hazel F. Glover, 62;
and their grandchildren, Elizabeth A. Stone, 8; Justin M. Stone, 5;
Trevor J. Stone, 2; and Kyle A. Stone, 1 month, all of Las Vegas,
Nevada, authorities said.
   Also killed was Verda Noble, 57, of Phoenix, the driver of the
pilot truck.
</TEXT>
