<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     03-08 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenians at Moscow Meeting Exchange Grim Accounts of Ethnic
Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weeping Armenians gathered in a snowy cemetery in
Moscow on Tuesday to exchange tales of brutal beatings and deaths
in a southern city torn by ethnic mob violence.
   Their accounts, which often elicited cries of anger from the 300
listeners, could not be verified independently, but were typical of
stories that have been circulating in Armenian communities since
the Feb. 28 rioting in the city of Sumgait in the republic of
Azerbaijan.
   The unrest in Sumgait was triggered by protests in the republic
of Armenia demanding that a region given to neighboring Azerbaijan
in 1923 be shifted to Armenian control. The population of the
Nagorno-Karabakh district is more than three-quarters Armenian.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, has said that 31 people
were killed in Sumgait, which has an Armenian minority. Soviet
officials have refused to elaborate on what happened and
Moscow-based journalists have been barred from traveling to the
Caucasus region.
   There have been many reports by Armenian activists of high death
tolls and brutality against Armenians by Azeris, members of the
dominant ethnic group in Azerbaijan. The Azeris are predominantly
Shiite Moslem, while the Armenians are predominantly Christian.
   The tearful crowd gathered in front of a brick church in the
Armenian section of Moscow's Vagankovskoye Cemetery. Plainclothes
police watched but did not try to break up the meeting, which
lasted two hours.
   One distraught man said he saw a pregnant woman and her unborn
baby slain and mutilated in Sumgait. At the local Communist Party
headquarters, he said, he saw people who were covered with knife
wounds and who had their ears cut off.
   The gray-haired man left without giving his name.
   The meeting began with a moment of silence for women slain in
Sumgait. A priest clad in black asked members of the crowd who had
witnessed anti-Armenian violence to come forward to speak.
   A resident of a village near Sumgait said bands of Azeris had
roved through his settlement, looking under beds for Armenian
children and raping Armenian women. Another Armenian said young
children had been thrown from windows.
   Ambartsum Galestyan, deputy chairman of the committee that
organized last month's protests in Yerevan, Armenia's capital, said
33 people had been killed in the Sumgait rioting.
   They included two Azeris, Galestyan said. He said the Azeris had
been killed by military units brought in to restore order, and that
eight soldiers had been killed. He said 100 to 150 people were
seriously injured.
   Galestyan said 4- and 5-year-old children had been thrown out of
fifth-floor windows by mobs in Sumgait, an industrial city of more
than 160,000 people. The Yerevan resident did not say how he had
learned of the attacks on the children or whether they had been
killed, and it was not clear whether he had been in Sumgait.
   A villager who lives near Sumgait said four people in his
settlement were slain. The villager, who did not give his name,
said he did not know where his family or sister were. ``I fear for
their safety,'' he told the meeting.
   Some speakers were angry at Soviet state-run press and
television, which blamed ``extremists'' for the dispute over
Nagorno-Karabakh and never clearly linked the violence in Sumgait
to antagonisms between Armenians and Azeris.
   ``How can the Soviet media today be silent, under conditions of
openness and restructuring?'' asked Robert Aryanpetyan, a
specialist in history who lives in Moscow. ``Shame on the central
television.''
</TEXT>
