<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NavySubs     03-08 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Subs,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Upgrades on Navy's Attack Submarines Leads to $1.3 Billion Overrun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy effort to upgrade future Los
Angeles-class attack submarines has generated delays at production
shipyards and contract overruns totaling $1.3 billion, the service
said Tuesday.
   The estimated $1.3 billion overrun covers 23 of the attack subs
scheduled for delivery into the 1990s and amounts to roughly a 5.9
percent increase over the negotiated target price for each
submarine, the Navy said.
   The Navy's target price for each of the attack submarines
currently is between $750 million and $760 million. Of the 23
submarines covered by the latest overrun estimate, 11 are being
built by General Dynamics Corp. and 12 by Newport News Shipbuilding
& Drydock Co.
   Under the production contracts covering the vessels, the overrun
will be split 50-50 with each of two shipyards building the subs,
meaning the Navy will have to pay out roughly $650 million beyond
the target price of the 23 submarines.
   The Navy said it already had the funds on hand to pay the
overrun, however, because it had anticipated there might be some
delays associated with improving the Los Angeles-class of subs.
   ``The Navy has retained funds to cover all improvements, and
there are no plans to seek additional funds from Congress to cover
these improvements,'' the service added.
   The delivery delays vary by shipyard, but range from seven
months to 18 months, the Navy said.
   The Los Angeles class, also known as the 688 class, is the
Navy's primary attack sub. The nuclear-powered vessel is designed
to hunt and destroy Soviet submarines and is built at General
Dynamics' Electric Boat Division in Groton, Conn., and at the
Newport News shipyard in Newport News, Va.
   The Navy is now in the midst of research and development work on
a new attack submarine, designated the SSN-21 Seawolf, but doesn't
anticipate that vessel materializing before 1994 at the earliest.
   In the interim, the Navy set out to improve the 688-class
submarine with such things as a stronger hull to allow Arctic
operations; better electronic and sensor systems; a series of
noise-reduction modifications; and installation of launching boxes
for Tomahawk cruise missiles.
   The service said Tuesday some of the improvements had required
extensive modification of the original design, leading to delays
that were not totally unexpected.
   In this case, the Navy and contractors have at least agreed up
front on how cost overruns will be handled and thus should avoid
the type of legal wrangling that erupted after cost overruns
skyrocketed on the same submarine in the 1970s, said Assistant Navy
Secretary Everett Pyatt.
   ``I'm not going through that again,'' Pyatt added.
   Four Newport News boats are now expected to be delivered from 14
months to 18 months late, while seven General Dynamics' submarines
will be delivered from seven months to nine months late.
   ``We want the deliveries on as timely a basis as possible, but
we have to acknowledge the fact that the modifications which we
asked for were a contributing factor,'' Dan Howard, the Pentagon's
chief spokesman, said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChistensenLeaving     03-08 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chistensen Leaving,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director of Mining Office Will Leave Job March 20.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jed Christensen, director of the Office of
Surface Mining, will leave the job March 20 for a county job in
California, the office said today.
   Chistensen, who worked in local government in Utah, Nevada,
California and Arizona before joining the Interior Department in
1981, will become deputy chief executive of Fresno County.
   He has been director or acting director of the federal
government's chief regulatory body for strip mines since April
1985, longer than anyone else in the history of the 10-year-old
agency.
   During his tenure, the office returned to state jurisdiction
parts of the Oklahoma regulatory program it had taken over in 1984,
installed a computer system to match applicants for mining permits
against operators with outstanding violations and won congressional
abolition of an exemption from regulation of mines covering less
than two acres.
</TEXT>
