<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GagOrder 1stLd-Writethru   03-08 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gag Order, 1st Ld-Writethru,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Challenges Navy Order That Workers Can't Take Part In
Caucuses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with judge denying restraining order; new throughout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today refused to issue a
restraining order that would have allowed civilian workers at a
Navy shipyard to participate in Washington's presidential precinct
caucuses tonight.
   The Navy earlier had said that the federal Hatch Act prevented
11,600 workers at the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard in Bremerton from
speaking out on which candidates they preferred.
   U.S. District Judge Jack Tanner's brief order said the state of
Washington, which had asked for the restraining order, failed to
show irreparable injury would result if the Navy's position were
allowed to stand and ``failed to establish the balance of hardships
tip in their favor.''
   Tanner's ruling came in a hastily filed state suit, which
contended that prohibiting federal workers from speaking at the
party caucuses unconstitutionally violated their right to free
speech.
   The suit, filed Monday, asked Tanner to clarify the intent of
the Hatch Act by interpreting ``conflicting sections'' of the
regulations, said David Bryant, a spokesman for the Washington
secretary of state's office.
   Secretary of State Ralph Munro was miffed at the ruling and said
the state may pursue the case for future years.
   ``I'm disappointed he didn't provide federal workers more
protection,'' he said. ``I can't believe in the long run that this
is constitutional.''
   He said the state's abortive attempt at gaining an injunction
did succeed in clarifying that federal workers may attend their
caucuses and participate in most respects.
   ``It sends a clear signal they can go to the caucuses and do
everything but speak out on the canidates,'' Munro said. ``It's
absurd. A guy can say `What America needs is a senator from Kansas
who was wounded and was a war hero,' but he can't say, `What
America needs is Bob Dole.'''
   A bill to revise the Hatch Act and allow workers to participate
in partisan political activities on their own time overwhelmingly
passed the U.S. House last year. It is pending in the Senate.
   Officials at the Bremerton shipyard had told workers they could
attend the political caucuses scheduled in 12,000 Washington
neighborhoods, but could not discuss candidates.
   The caucuses are the first step in the months-long process
leading up to a selection of delegates from Washington to the
national presidential nominating conventions this summer. At stake
ultimately are 73 Democratic national convention delegates and 41
Republican delegates.
   The Hatch Act states that federal employees may not use their
official authority or influence to interfere with an election.
   ``Obviously, addressing the caucus is part of the activity,''
said James Sommerhauser, representing Professional and Technical
Engineers Local 12 in Bremerton, but ``most federal employees are
so intimidated by the Hatch Act they're afraid to participate.''
   Sommerhauser said his union represents 1,800 federal workers at
the yard and elsewhere in the county.
</TEXT>
