<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lisbon Radio Reports 2 Killed in Failed Coup Attempt in Sao Tome
e
Principe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lisbon radio station said today
authorities in the West African island nation of Sao Tome e
Principe crushed a coup attempt, killing two people.
   A correspondent reporting from the former Portuguese colony for
Lisbon's Radio Commercial said 40 armed men landed by canoe before
dawn today and tried to seize the police headquarters near the
capital of Sao Tome.
   The report said forces loyal to the government of President
Manuel Pinto da Costa killed two of the attackers and captured the
others.
   The radio correspondent, Jaime Marques de Almeida, said the
government blamed the coup attempt on the National Resistence Front
of Sao Tome e Principe that has its headquarters in Libreville,
Gabon. He said the government was expected to make an official
statement on the reported coup attempt later.
   The Lisbon-based secretary-general of the National Resistence
Front, Quintiliano Loures Amado, denied the group was responsible.
