<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MoslemArrests     03-08 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moslem Arrests,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fundamentalist Moslems Attack Explorer Scouts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fundamentalist Moslem students attacked a
group of scouts with knives, stones and bicycle chains, then opened
fire on security forces as they came to the scouts' aid,
authorities said Tuesday.
   Two policemen and two extremists were wounded slightly, said a
police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said officers arrested about 50 students after the Monday
night incident and another 20 on Tuesday. Many had been arrested
after a demonstration late last year.
   The fundamentalists apparently attacked the male and female
scouts because of their belief that the sexes should not mix.
   Police said the fundamentalist students were found with two
empty pistols, iron rods, knives and daggers. About 25 shell
casings from rounds used against security forces were found at the
stadium on the Assiut University campus where the violence occurred.
   On Tuesday, police clamped tight security on the downtown
courthouse where the suspects were housed. On campus, about 500
fundamentalists tried to demonstrate for the release of their
classmates but were stopped by university guards, security
officials said.
   Street demonstrations are banned in Egypt under an emergency law
enacted after Moslem extremists assassinated President Anwar Sadat
in October 1981.
   For several years, the university campus has been a hotbed of
Moslem fundamentalist agitation in Assiut, a southern Nile town 235
miles south of Cairo.
   Monday night's trouble began during a meeting and parade of the
Rovers, the equivalent of the Explorers in the American Boy Scout
program.
   University officials said militants attacked the parade.
   University guards were unable to contain the fight and called
for help from outside security police, normally banned from the
campus.
   Four people were hurt in the melee that followed, but the Rovers
escaped unhurt by climbing out stadium windows and clambering down
fire escapes, security officials said.
   In a telephone call to The Associated Press in Cairo, a man
claiming to speak for Assiut's fundamentalists blamed security
police for the trouble. He said his group demonstrated because the
university administration had ``organized a dancing and singing
party,'' and security police broke up the demonstration with tear
gas and batons.
   Security officials said the suspects were charged with firearms
and other weapons offenses and destroying musical instruments.
   The fundamentalists appear to have been angered because they
believe the sexes should be forbidden from mixing in parties,
picnics or other social events.
</TEXT>
