<DOCNO> AP880308-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Democrats     03-08 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Democrats,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Native Sons Hoping Super Tuesday Shows Broader Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s Southern strategy faced a do-or-die test
on Super Tuesday. Democratic rivals Michael Dukakis and Jesse
Jackson were favored overall in the battle for 1,307 party
delegates and Richard Gephardt fought for survival.
   Jackson, a black man born and educated in the South, relied on
his wide support among that region's large black population and
figured to be among the delegate leaders in the Super Tuesday
voting.
   Gov. Dukakis of Massachusetts was virtually conceded the support
of his home state, and he sought to win on both sides of Dixie with
strong bids in Texas and Florida.
   Gore of Tennessee and Gephardt of Missouri were heavily favored
to win their home states. They battled among themselves for what
was left of the white vote. Theirs was a struggle for survival,
with each reduced to a strategy aimed at emerging as the white
alternative to Dukakis when the campaign moves elsewhere.
   Two other candidates were on the ballot but weren't factors:
Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois and Gary Hart, the former senator from
Colorado.
   Twenty states and American Samoa were holding Democratic
contests in what was the closest thing to a national primary ever
held.
   Most were in the South, where every state save South Carolina
had a primary. South Carolina Democrats select delegates Saturday.
   Outside the South, there were primaries in Massachusetts, Rhode
Island, Washington state, Idaho and Nevada.
   At stake were 1,307 delegates _ more than half the number needed
to win the nomination. A candidate had to receive at least 15
percent of the vote in a congressional district or statewide to win
delegates.
   Jackson is from the only Southern state not voting, South
Carolina. But he had a strong appeal to blacks, who make up a
quarter of the Democratic vote in the South _ and as much as half
in Alabama and Mississippi.
   With so many white candidates fragmenting the vote, Jackson
hoped to score well in other Southern states, too.
   After wins in New Hampshire, Maine and Vermont, Dukakis hoped to
demonstrate an appeal to Democrats outside New England, and he
concentrated heavily on Texas and Florida. He had wide appeal among
Jewish voters in south Florida and Hispanics in Texas.
   Gore followed a Southern strategy that ignored the earliest
contests, even while insisting he was a national candidate. But he
faced a severe battle even to emerge as his own region's candidate.
   Gephardt entered the Southern campaign with little money to
mount the heavy television campaign that succeeded for him in the
earlier states. He and Gore sought the moderate and conservative
vote.
   Simon, running as the clear liberal, was reeling and broke from
third-place finishes in Iowa and New Hampshire. He sat out the
Super Tuesday campaign and awaited the next stop, his home state of
Illinois where he planned a low-budget campaign to get back in the
race.
   Hart, a year ago the odds-on favorite, acknowledged before Super
Tuesday that he didn't expect to be the nominee but was pressing
his candidacy in an effort to steer the campaign debate.
   Hart had re-entered the race in December but couldn't regain the
support he had before dropping out seven months earlier amid
disclosures about his relationship with model Donna Rice.
</TEXT>
