<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--South Africa-Journalist,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Release of Journalist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Tuesday joined a
group of senators in urging the South African government to release
Zwalakhe Sisulu, a prominent black journalist detained for the past
14 months without trial.
   ``We see no justification for Mr. Sisulu's detention,'' State
Department spokesman Charles Redman said. ``He has been a leader in
efforts to resolve South Africa's political problems peacefully.''
   ``He's the type of black leader the South African government
should be talking to, not repressing,'' Redman added.
   Redman said U.S. Ambassador Edward J. Perkins made a personal
appeal to the South African authorities for Sisulu's release and
``we will continue to urge'' his freedom.
   A group of 52 senators has written South African President P.W.
Botha on Sisulu's behalf. The letter was made public Monday.
