<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TouristBus     03-08 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tourist Bus,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>55 American Tourists Hurt in Bus Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus carrying American tourists on a trip
through the Holy Land skidded on a rain-slick highway east of the
occupied Gaza Strip and flipped over Tuesday, injuring all 56
people on board, officials said.
   Three of the 55 Americans were in serious condition and the bus
driver also was hurt. The passengers, en route from Israel to
Egypt, crawled from the overturned bus through shattered windows.
   ``I was climbing over bodies. Blood was just running all over,''
said Dora Bowling, a retired secretary from Fairmont, W.Va.
   The Americans were participating in an extensive tour of the
Holy Land sponsored by the United Methodist Church's West Virginia
Conference.
   Tour coordinator Wendall Eskew identified the three seriously
injured passengers as Margaret Glass of Dunbar, W.Va.; Mary Lou
Moore, of Charleston, W.Va.; and Donna Light of Wheeling, W.Va.
   He said Glass and Moore are in their 70s and Light is in her 50s.
   Five other people were in moderate condition at Barzilai
Hospital in Ashkelon, 15 suffered minor injuries and the others
were treated and released, said Ilana Zeev, a spokeswoman for the
facility, 40 miles southeast of Jerusalem.
   ``We were going around a curve and it was raining and slick and
the bus seemed to hydroplane,'' said Bonny Eskew, a piano and organ
teacher from Charleston, W.Va.
   ``We were heading for a ditch, then we swerved back to the
right, lost control and turned over,'' said Mrs. Eskew, 59, who had
a badly bruised right eye. ``It happened so fast we didn't have
time to do anything.''
   Passengers spoke at Jerusalem's Hyatt Hotel, where they returned
after being treated at the Ashkelon hospital.
   Many of the Americans suffered fractured limbs, including broken
hands, wrists and shoulder bones, or cuts requiring stitches, said
an emergency room surgeon who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Police commander Ezra Menashe told Israel army radio the
accident involved a bus from the East Jerusalem Tourism Co. and
occurred on the road between Miflasim and Kfar Azza, two collective
farms located about three miles east of the Gaza Strip.
   The tourists were headed from Jerusalem to Cairo via the
Egyptian border crossing at Rafah on the southern tip of the Gaza
Strip. The bus departed from the northern city of Tiberias.
   Debbie McGraw, a church secretary in Charleston, said the bus
was carrying lay people and clergy from various parts of the state,
as well as relatives from Virginia and possibly other states,
McGraw said.
   She said the bus passengers were part of a larger tour and had
opted to extend the tour and visit Egypt. She said tour members on
the bus were scheduled to return Friday and Saturday.
   Those on the bus had ``successfully completed a Holy Land
pilgrimage and were on the way to Egypt for a three-day tour
extension,'' said Richard Ridgeway, vice president of Educational
Opportunities Inc. of Lakeland, Fla., the tour operator.
</TEXT>
