<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-China 3rdLd-Wriutethru a0628 03-08 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-China, 3rd Ld-Wriutethru, a0628,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 9 grafs new, picking up 5th graf pvs, During toasts</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's foreign minister told President Reagan
today his government is very concerned about the Iran-Iraq war and
supports an arms embargo against the Tehran regime, a White House
spokesman said.
   President spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the administration
also accepts China's declaration that it no longer is selling
Silkworm missiles to Iran, although it remains a supplier of
conventional arms.
   Reagan met for nearly 40 minutes in the Oval Office with Wu
Xueqian, who was making his first visit to the United States in
four years. Posing for photographers, Reagan said, ``We have a very
cordial relationship between our two countries and we want to
continue it.''
   Briefing reporters on the meeting, Fitzwater said Wu offered
support for a U.N. cease-fire resolution in the Iran-Iraq war, and
also endorsed an arms embargo to back it up ``if the overwhelming
majority of the (U.N.) Security Council believed it should be
adopted.''
   Fitzwater said the administration did not believe that Wu was
trying to qualify or limit his endorsement.
   ``It was our reaction, the president's reaction, that this was a
very positive sign, a very strong expression of support and one,
frankly, one we hope the Soviet Union would emulate,'' Fitzwater
said.
   In the talks, Reagan did not bring up the subject of the
Silkworm missiles, although it was discussed in Wu's earlier
meetings with Secretary of State George P. Shultz, Fitzwater said.
   The United States protested to China last fall about its sale of
Silkworms to Iran. ``To the best of our information, they have not
delivered any missiles since then,'' Fitzwater said.
   While noting that China still remains a major supplier of
conventional arms, he said, ``We think the fact that we have not
detected any new missile shipments and their general attitude
toward the Iran-Iraq war and the U.N. resolution _ that those are
very hopeful signs.''
   Wu met Monday with Shultz and with Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci.
   During toasts following a State Department luncheon on Monday,
Shultz and Wu hailed the progress in bilateal relations and made
almost no reference to issues dividing them.
   Chief among those issues is China's reported sales of military
weaponry to Iran in defiance of U.S. efforts at the United Nations
to win support for a worldwide arms embargo against Iran.
   The administration has been seeking assurances from China that
it will not veto an embargo resolution.
   Last October, the United States retaliated against China for
selling Silkworm anti-ship missiles to Iran by suspending the
process under which China had been given increasing access to U.S.
products with advanced technology.
   Since then, China has said it has stopped selling Silkworms to
Iran.
   Shultz made no reference in his remarks to recent anti-Chinese
rioting in Tibet. State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
between three and nine people are believed to have been killed, and
he expressed deep concern over the human rights situation in Tibet.
</TEXT>
