<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MechamImpeachment 3rdLd-Writethru a0597 03-08 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham Impeachment, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0597,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Lawman Says Governor Obstructed Justice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to add new testimony; pick up 6th graf:
``Milstead, 49 ...''
^LaserPhoto PN1</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona's ranking lawman said today he
decided to cooperate in an investigation of an alleged death threat
but didn't tell Evan Mecham because the governor was so angry about
the probe he ``was not to be reasoned with.''
   Department of Public Safety director Ralph Milstead, in his
second day of testimony at Mecham's impeachment trial, continued to
insist that Mecham had obstructed justice by ordering Milstead not
to cooperate.
   During his five hours of testimony Monday, Milstead had
portrayed Mecham as a frightened, angry leader who told him: ``I
don't want you to help the attorney general hang me. Don't tell him
anything.''
   The first-term Republican governor is accused of trying to
thwart an investigation into whether an associate, Lee Watkins,
threatened last Nov. 12 to send former top Mecham aide Donna
Carlson on ``a long boat ride'' if she testified before a grand
jury investigating Mecham's campaign finances. Watkins has denied
threatening Ms. Carlson.
   During continued cross-examination today by defense attorney
Fred Craft, Milstead testified that Mecham was fully informed about
the alleged threat and the involvement of the attorney general's
office when he told Mecham the attorney general wanted information
from DPS officers about the matter.
   Milstead said today he did not tell Mecham during their
telephone conversation that he intended to cooperate with the
attorney general despite the governor's order not to.
   ``I was in shock from his anger that was directed toward the
attorney general,'' Milstead said. ``He was not to be reasoned
with.''
   Milstead testified Monday that he considered the alleged threat
serious because Watkins had a criminal record. Watkins resigned as
state prison construction chief after a past assault conviction was
disclosed.
   Milstead, 49, said he phoned Mecham on Nov. 15 to alert him to
the possible death threat. ``I think my words to the governor were,
`I don't want you to be blindsided,'' said Milstead.
   Milstead said when Mecham told him not to cooperate with the
attorney general, ``I was in shock over what he was saying, taken
aback, speechless.''
   Craft asked Milstead why he had not included his own part of the
conversation in a report he wrote on his talk with Mecham.
   ``Because I'm not committing a crime,'' said Milstead. ``I'm not
obstructing justice.''
   ``When did you conclude that the governor's words constituted a
crime?'' asked Craft.
   ``As I'm hearing them and reflecting on them,'' said Milstead,
adding it took him ``about two seconds'' after hanging up the phone.
   Craft asked if Milstead was surprised that his staff didn't tell
him the governor had assigned cabinet member Max Hawkins, then-head
of the department of administration, to investigate the death
threat allegation.
   ``No, it didn't surprise me,'' said Milstead. ``Max Hawkins is
not a law enforcement officer. He's not competent to investigate
it. Lee Watkins works for him, and Max Hawkins wouldn't be taken
seriously anywhere on Earth that I know of.''
   The senators decided Monday to forego hearing from Watkins
because it meant granting him immunity from prosecution. Watkins
invoked Fifth Amendment protection against self incrimination.
   Senators also expressed impatience with Craft's long
interrogation, which Minority Leader Alan Stephens, a Democrat,
called wearing and repetitious.
   ``If that's what they do in a court of law,'' said Stephens,
``I'm glad I'm not a lawyer.''
   Mecham, 63, the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six
decades, is not attending his trial and did not comment on
Milstead's testimony. In January, he testified before a House
impeachment committee that he may have told Milstead not to
cooperate with the attorney general's investigation but that he was
not fully informed about the seriousness of the situation.
   Mecham also is charged with concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
and misusing $80,000 in a state funds by loaning it to his car
dealership.
   He faces a a May 17 recall election and a March 22 criminal
trial on the campaign loan disclosure allegation. A prosecutor in
that case, however, sought Monday to have it delayed until April 21
on the ground that pretrial defense maneuvers have left the
prosecution too little time to prepare.
   Defense lawyers Monday filed a series of motions, including one
asking for a dismissal of the charges.
   Judge Michael Ryan of Maricopa County Superior Court said he
would rule Wednesday or Thursday on the prosecution request but did
not indicate when he would rule on the defense motions.
</TEXT>
