<HEAD>Robertson Supporters Hope for Triumph; Dukakis Favored Among
Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ed: Caucuses begin at 11 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson's fervent band of supporters waged
political warfare against Republican regulars in presidential
caucuses Tuesday, while Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was
favored over his Democratic rivals.
   None of the state's 41 GOP delegates were directly at stake in
the caucus voting, but the former television evangelist hoped to
embarrass Vice President George Bush and Kansas Sen. Bob Dole.
   Robertson was given a good shot at winning the state where
evangelicals have controlled the party for most of a decade,
ramming through anti-abortion, ultraconservative platforms at
carefully orchestrated conventions.
   ``We're stomping the daylights out of them!'' Robertson's state
organizer, Bruce Hawkins, said with a delighted chuckle a few days
ago.
   Bush and Dole forces, waging conventional campaigns, admitted to
high anxiety over the Robertson Factor, but held out hope the party
regulars would get worried enough to go to their neighborhood
caucuses.
   The caucus voting was basically a straw poll, since delegates
elected to go on to district-level caucuses are not bound to any
candidate.
   On the Democratic side, with 65 delegates at stake, Dukakis
benefited from endorsements by Gov. Booth Gardner, Sen. Brock
Adams, Seattle Mayor Charles Royer and other party leaders.
   Jesse Jackson and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon were fighting it out
for second- and third-place finishes and a sizable number of
caucus-goers were expected to vote for uncommitted delegates, said
state Democratic Chairwoman Karen Marchioro.
</TEXT>
