<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HostageStandoff     03-08 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage Standoff,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helena Man Arrested After Five-Hour Standoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 48-year-old man who held his 11-month-old
daughter at gunpoint for more than five hours was arrested today
when police officers crept into his apartment and found him asleep,
police said.
   Warren Dean Brown was arrested without incident after the
five-hour standoff, during which police evacuated other residents
of Brown's apartment building, some of them going down ladders from
second-floor windows, said Helena Police Chief Bill Ware.
   Brown is charged with felony assault and was scheduled for
arraignment later today in Helena Justice Court, Ware said.
   Brown was arrested about 1 a.m. when police entered the family's
apartment. They found Brown asleep in the master bedroom with his
young daughter, Crystal, and a loaded .22-caliber pistol, Ware said.
   The incident began at Monday night when police received a call
from another resident of the building.
   Ware said Brown's wife, 26-year-old Kathy Brown, had escaped
with another daughter, 3-year-old Amber, after Brown pistol-whipped
his wife with the handgun, striking her on the face.
   ``The area was secured and the wife ... indicated Mr. Brown
stated he was going to kill the family,'' Ware said.
   Mrs. Brown was taken by ambulance to St. Peter's Community
Hospital, where she was treated and released.
   Police evacuated seven people from two other apartments in the
building.
   Of the 35 officers in the Helena Police Department, 20 were at
the apartment complex while Lewis and Clark County sheriff's
deputies assisted with other calls in the city.
   There was no phone in the Brown apartment and Brown did not
respond to a hostage negotiator who spoke through a bullhorn, Ware
said.
   Police aimed a directional microphone at the apartment, heard no
movement inside, and at 1 a.m. sent in three members of the
department's ``quick response team,'' who found Brown and the child
in a bedroom, along with the loaded pistol, the chief said.
   No shots were fired during the incident and Brown offered no
resistance when arrested, Ware said.
   He said Crystal was returned to her mother, who along with her
two daughters is now staying with friends.
</TEXT>
