<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1349EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet     03-08 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tibetan Communist Leader Criticizes Countrymen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Tibetan Communist Party official Tuesday
condemned the ``savage actions'' of his Tibetan countrymen who
sparked two days of anti-Chinese riots in the capital of Lhasa last
week.
   ``Sabotage'' of the monk-led rioters ``went completely against
the people's wish for a normal democratic life.'' Tibet's party
Deputy Secretary Raidi was quoted as saying by the official Xinhua
News Agency.
   Xinhua also claimed in a report from Lhasa that no policemen
carried arms while on duty Saturday. Western sources have said that
five Tibetans and three policemen were killed in the rioting, while
Chinese officials say the only death was that of a policeman.
   Another Chinese official report said the riots, which started
Saturday, stretched into Sunday. Previous reports said there was no
unrest Sunday.
   That report, by the China News Agency, also said Tibetan monks
tried to poison the tea of Chinese officials and journalists
attending ceremonies to mark the end of a major Buddhist festival.
   Xinhua said 309 policemen were injured, 29 seriously, by
Tibetans attacking with stones, clubs and iron bars. The China News
Service, monitored in Hong Kong, put the number of hospitalized
police officers at more than 30.
   There have been unconfirmed reports that some rioters were shot,
and Western travelers in Lhasa, contacted by telephone, have
reported seeing large contingents of armed police.
   Travelers said police on Tuesday withdrew their blockade from
around the Jokhang Temple, Lhasa's main temple and the scene of the
violent protest against Chinese rule.
   William Tang, assistant foreign manager at the Lhasa Hotel, said
guests were told they could go to the temple's market square but
``at their own risk.''
   ``Most Tibetans detest and oppose the savage actions of the
handful of splittists,'' Raidi, a Tibetan, told Xinhua.
   Splittists is a termed coined by the Chinese to describe those
who seek independence for regions in China.
   The weekend violence followed a similar outbreak of
pro-independence unrest in early October during which at least 14
people died.
   Chinese troops entered Tibet in 1950 after beating Nationalist
Chinese forces in a civil war. Nine years later, Tibet's spiritual
and temporal leader, the Dalai Lama, fled into exile after an
abortive uprising.
   Many Tibetans continue to be bitter about China's suppression of
local customs and religion and its destruction of temples.
   China News Service accused the monks of being the ringleaders
Saturday, the final day of a major 10-day festival known as the
Great Prayer Festival.
   The report said monks Saturday attacked the vans of Chinese TV
crews photographing the 500-year-old prayer festival and dropped a
22-pound boulder from a rooftop.
   Seven cars from Tibet's local TV station and a camera were
smashed, the report said. Two cars were turned over and another set
afire as the rampaging monks shouted, ``Smash anything that is
communist!''
   A Western traveler said Tibetans told him police beat two monks
to death inside the Jokhang Temple.
   Several Tibetans later carried the monks' bodies around the
square, he said, triggering further clashes.
   The Dalai Lama, in a statement from his office in New Delhi,
Monday said the violence clearly revealed the ``desperation'' of
the Tibetan people. He called on Tibetans to ``restrain from
violence in spite of repressive measures that the Chinese may
take.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     03-08 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Progress Reported On Fine Print</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators on Tuesday reported progress in their
work on the fine print of an emerging Afghan settlement in talks to
end nine years of fighting.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez told reporters that negotiations
were focusing on ``sensitive technicalities'' of the four documents
that are to make up the peace package and govern the withdrawal of
an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops backing Kabul's communist
government.
   Asked if there was substantive progress, he said ``yes'' but did
not elaborate. ``Even if the two sides wanted to sign the accords
now they cannot do so before the agreements are ready,'' he said.
   Cordovez's optimistic comments came as an Afghan resistance
group quit the seven member anti-Soviet alliance because it said
the interim government in Afghanistan could be dominated by Moslem
extremists.
   The abrupt departure of the Afghan National Liberation Front
reduces to two the number of moderate parties in the alliance.
   ``Pakistan is going to bring in a fundamentalist government. It
is not good for Afghanistan. It will destroy Afghanistan,'' said
the front's leader, Sibghatullah Mojaddedi.
   It was not clear how Mojaddedi's move might affect negotiations.
   Cordovez and other sources close to the talks made it clear that
nothing spectacular was likely to emerge in the next few days from
the indirect negotiations between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
   ``You should go sightseeing for three days,'' he counseled
journalists.
   Still, there was considerable behind-the-scenes activity.
   Cordovez and delegates reportedly kept close touch with deputy
U.S. Secretary of State Robert Peck and another visitor, Ambassador
Nicolai Kozyrev, described as a Soviet specialist on Afghan affairs.
   Pakistan's chief representative, acting Foreign Minister Zain
Noorani, was eager to dispel any notions of a standstill.
   ``Things are moving forward,'' he said. ``Don't you see that I
am coming here every day?''
   A diplomatic source who insisted on anonymity said prospects for
a settlement continued to look good in the current round, which
started March 2. The source said that no substantive discussions
had taken place on the question of an interim government. Pakistan
wants the formation of a broad-based transitional Kabul government
to move on a ``second track'' parallel to the implementation of
troop withdrawal.
   It argues that only a generally acceptable government can ensure
the safe return of more than five million refugees and prevent more
bloodshed in the country already mourning more than one million
dead.
   The Kabul delegation has publicly rejected Pakistan's request as
an attempt to introduce an extraneous issue that could undermine
the talks. But Pakistan is reported to be still hoping for a
compromise, perhaps by agreeing to sign the settlement with the
present leadership _ which it does not recognize _ in return for
assurances that an interim government will be formed soon afterward.
   Pakistani president Muhammad Zia ul-Haq, in Dubai for
inauguration of the Emirates Golf Club, said Tuesday an interim
government was a necessary ingredient in any settlement.
   ``We do not want to go over just pages of an agreement. Out of
the Geneva process we want to take a comprehensive settlement. And
for that settlement, an interim government is one of the most
essential instruments,'' Zia said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
