<DOCNO> AP880308-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1358EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan-Guerrillas     03-08 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Guerrillas,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Resistance Splits Over Proposed Interim Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan resistance group on Tuesday
quit an anti-Soviet alliance because of fears that the interim
government in Afghanistan will be dominated by Moslem extremists.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddedi, leader of the moderate Afghan National
Liberation Front, also resigned as party chief.
   The front's abrupt departure reduces to two the number of
moderate parties in the alliance.
   Hamed Karzai, the party's information director, said Mojaddedi's
move was to protest plans for a future Afghan government worked out
by the alliance's Moslem extremist members.
   ``For us it's is finished,'' Karzai said of the alliance.
   At a news conference, Mojaddedi said the ``most important
decision about Afghanistan'' had been made by seven people _ the
leaders of the seven-party alliance.
   ``Nobody has looked to the 15 million people of Afghanistan,''
he said, adding that the three million Shiite moslems had
particularly been ignored.
   Mojaddedi said the proposal for an interim government announced
late last month was too hardline.
   ``Pakistan is going to bring in a fundamentalist government. It
is not good for Afghanistan. It will destroy Afghanistan,''
Mojaddedi said.
   He said the best alternative was to convene a grand national
council, whose membership of about 1,000 would include commanders,
scholars, tribal and religious leaders, refugees and Afghans living
abroad.
   The council, he said, would decide the future government.
   Moslem extremists in the alliance apparently oppose that plan.
   The alliance, under pressure from Pakistan, announced in late
February plans to form a future Afghan government headed by an
all-guerrilla executive council and 28 ministers, possibly
including non-communist officials from the communist government in
Kabul.
   While Pakistan cautiously endorsed the plan, rumors soon
circulated in Peshawar that the alliance leaders were split over
which parties should wield the most power.
   Pakistan, which is negotating with the Kabul government over a
withdrawal of Soviet forces from Afghanistan, has insisted that the
formation of a broad-based interim Afghan government is crucial for
the safe return of about 5 million Afghan refugees from Pakistan
and Iran.
   Meanwhile, the remaining six guerrilla leaders called an
emergency meeting to discuss the development. None of them would
comment on Mojaddedi's move.
   Although Mojaddedi personally has considerable political
influence, his party, comprised of traditional Pathan tribal
militias with few outside sources of military or financial support,
is not strong.
   The split comes at a sensitive time for Pakistan, which speaks
for the guerrillas at U.N.-sponsored peace talks in Geneva.
</TEXT>
