<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ToyGuns     03-08 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Guns,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Only Outlaws Will Sell Toy Guns Under SF Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City supervisors have agreed to ban the
sale of realistic toy guns following the recent fatal shooting of a
retarded boy who drew a toy pistol on police officers.
   The measure was proposed by Supervisor Wendy Nelder, daughter of
a former police chief, who said some toy stores already have
removed toy weapons from their shelves.
   ``Nobody wants to be responsible for a little kid's death, or a
police officer's death, or anybody else's,'' she said in an
interview.
   On Feb. 17, two police officers killed Silivelio ``Tony''
Grohse, 13, when he pointed a toy gun, which the officers thought
was real, at them during a confrontation.
   The district attorney's office cleared the officers of
wrongdoing, saying they had a ``well-founded fear for their lives.''
   In another incident on Dec. 21, 1986, a police officer shot a
15-year-old burglary suspect to death after the youth held up a toy
gun.
   Toy guns already are banned in Los Angeles and neighboring
Burbank and Santa Monica.
   Nelder's plan won unanimous tentative approval late Monday
night. Final adoption usually is a rubber-stamping procedure taking
place within 30 days.
   Under the plan, possession of a toy gun would still be legal.
Otherwise, she notes, it would be possible for a police officer to
arrest people in one house for having toy guns, but impossible to
arrest a neighbor with real weapons that were otherwise legal.
   It also will be legal to sell toy guns that were obviously toys.
But, Nelder said, ``They'd have to be about four feet long and made
of pink plastic, because that's about all nowadays that makes
something a toy gun.''
   Many toymakers already are changing designs as the result of
pressure from retailers like Toys R Us, which has urged
manufacturers to come up with ways to keep toy guns from being
mistaken for authentic guns, said Douglas Thomsom, president of the
New York-based trade group Toys Manufacturers of America.
</TEXT>
