<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To celebrate his 50th birthday March 17, Rudolf
Nureyev will dance the romantic role of Albert in the classic
ballet ``Giselle.''
   The Paris Opera Ballet said Tuesday that Nureyev, director of
the Paris company, was invited to dance in three performances with
the American Ballet Theatre during its tour to Los Angeles. The
invitation was made by ABT director and ballet star Mikhail
Baryshnikov, who, like Nureyev, defected from the Soviet Union.
   Most dancers in Nureyev's troupe retire at age 45, but while he
makes only rare stage appearances, the elder statesman of classical
dance has yet to hang up his slippers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Bernie Simon said he was delighted with
a caricature of himself that is the new ``Face on the Barroom
Floor'' at the Omaha Press Club.
   ``I'm flabbergasted. I thought I'd look like hell,'' said Simon,
who has been undergoing radiation therapy for brain tumors. About
125 people attended the unveiling of his portrait Monday.
   The drawing by Jim Horan shows Simon placing toy building blocks
along the city's riverfront, where ConAgra Inc. is planning to
build a multimillion-dollar headquarters and research center.
   Simon's picture will be displayed in a frame on Press Club floor
for about three months and then will hang in the club's gallery of
more than 30 politicians, athletes and business people.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. founder and Chairman William Paley made
a remarkable recovery from emergency gall bladder surgery and went
home Tuesday, a spokeswoman said.
   Paley, 86, was in critical condition following his Feb. 11
surgery at New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center.
   Hospital spokeswoman Myrna Manners said Paley had ``remarkably
improved after one month in the hospital.''
   Paley bought the Columbia Broadcasting System, a fledgling radio
network, in 1928. He turned over the reins in 1983. But when CBS's
biggest stockholder, Loew's Corp., became unhappy with his
successor's policies, Paley teamed with Loew Chairman Lawrence
Tisch to retake control in 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tami Erin, the 13-year-old star of ``Pippi
Longstocking,'' says she was very excited to see the premiere of
her movie accompanied by a Japanese princess.
   ``It was so weird seeing myself on the big screen,'' Miss Erin
said Tuesday after the world premiere of the film based on the
popular tomboy of Astrid Lindgren's novels. ``It was great and I
was very excited.''
   Japan's Princess Nori, the 18-year-old granddaughter of Emperor
Hirohito, joined Miss Erin for the first showing of the film,
directed by Ken Annakin.
   The princess ``was a very sweet girl and very friendly,'' Miss
Erin said. ``She loved it (the movie) a lot.''
   The eighth-grader from Shark River Island, N.J., who began
performing in commercials in 1983, was chosen from 9,000 aspirants
to play Pippi, whose stories have been translated into 44 languages.
   The movie will be released in the United States in July.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British weeklies have accused Prince Andrew's
wife, the former Sarah Ferguson, of brash and vulgar behavior
during the couple's recent visit to California.
   London's Sunday Times said that after seeing the Duke and
Duchess of York, Americans will likely ``retreat to their more
refined dinner parties, there to cap each other with anecdotes
about the awful vulgarities of the British.''
   The Observer, a liberal weekly, in a profile of the 28-year-old
duchess, said: ``Something appears to have gone awry with the royal
fairy story.''
   The newspapers were particularly critical of the duchess' quip,
``I'll see you later,'' to a man who yelled out, ``I love you,''
breaking a fake bottle over her husband's head and what they saw as
generally failed attempts at humor.
   The Sunday Times, in an article by sketch writer Craig Brown,
criticized British daily newspapers for using headlines such as
``Hollywood Bows to a Touch of British Class'' and ``Royal
One-Liners Woo U.S. Hosts.''
   Of a black-tie dinner at which the duchess wore a red-and-black
gown, Brown wrote:
   ``While the stars of Hollywood dressed in discreet black and
stayed in the shadows, down the stairs walloped someone who looked
as if she'd just won third prize for her Carmen Miranda
impersonation in an end of pier show at some forgotten resort.''
   The Observer asked, ``Has the Duchess of York gone too far?''
and added, ``Even in this day and age it is easily possible for
noblesse to be too obliging.''
