<1ST_LINE>u a PM-StolenMonet     03-08 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stolen Monet,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Painting Believed to Be Stolen Monet Recovered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today found what appears to be
the painting by French impressionist Claude Monet that was stolen
from the Fisher Community Center nearly a year ago.
   ``We're extremely pleased,'' said Rex Ryden, head of the Fisher
Foundation. ``Obviously, it's going to be something that will be of
value as far as the entire art world is concerned.''
   Lt. Darrell Templeton said the department recovered the painting
in a mail drop box in LeGrand, about nine miles east of
Marshalltown.
   The painting, ``The Fishing Boats in Front of the Cliffs at
D'Etretat,'' is to be examined to see if it is the original. Ryden
said the painting was rolled up when found and that Templeton
unrolled it just far enough to determine that it may be the Monet.
   Ryden said officials will not bend nor otherwise tamper with the
painting for fear that it might be damaged in the process.
   The painting, valued at up to $300,000, was stolen March 19,
1987. Authorities soon after called in the FBI and the
international police agency Interpol to help locate it.
   The painting was stolen by a man who rushed into the center at
night, carved the 23-by-32 inch canvas from its frame and vanished
on foot.
   Ryden said the foundation's insurance carrier paid $175,000 for
its loss. ``I'm not sure who owns that painting now, since the
insurance company paid us for it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
