<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1419EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0613 03-08 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0613,600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new with Fitzwater statements; picks up 3rd graf
pvs, Rep. Stephen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said today it
intends to keep holding the threat of sanctions over Panama's Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, but said no decisions have been made on
possible actions.
   ``The threat's still out there. We're still considering it. The
situation is changing rapidly and we're still monitoring it. But we
don't want to act precipitously,'' White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater told reporters.
   He made the comments to clarify statements he'd made earlier
indicating the administration might be withholding a decision on
possible economic and trade sanctions.
   Earlier in the day, the House Foreign Affairs Committee voted
unanimously to endorse Reagan's course of action against the
military regime and to urge him to consider further economic
sanctions.
   The administration has called for Noriega's removal since he was
indicted on federal drug trafficking charges in Florida last month.
   The sanctions are being considered as a means of bringing
pressure against Noriega's military regime and to promote a return
to civilian rule under President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   ``Let me back you away from the inevitability of these kinds of
decisions,'' the spokesman had said initially, adding, ``It's been
our feeling from the very beginning that change should come from
within in Panama and we should watch it carefully and if that is
the process, that is preferable to our taking actions.''
   But Fitzwater later returned to the briefing room to say, ``We
want to keep the threat of sanctions still out there.''
   He said the options were still before the administration, but
that no decisions had yet been made. He said such decisions
depended upon ``a very complicated set of criteria.''
   He cited the impact the sanctions might have on the status of
the Noriega government, U.S. interests in terms of the canal, the
Panamanian military and U.S. investment in that country.
   Fitzwater also offered support for statements issued by Delvalle
and opposition parties that have called for the establishment of a
``government of national reconciliation.''
   ``We welcome those statements,'' the spokesman said. He also
issued a statement saying the U.S. government supports the goal of
``restoring democratic government and civilian constitutional
order. Once this goal has been achieved, we will work cooperatively
with the government of Panama toward the recovery of Panama's
financial and economic health.''
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee resolution, which will be
voted on by the House later this week, also reaffirmed
congressional support for the full implementation of the Panama
Canal treaties which require the United States to hand the canal
over to Panama at the end of the century.
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., noted that Panama's military
ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, has said that the criticism
from the United States aimed at his alleged involvement in drug
trafficking and other acts of corruption is actually a smoke screen.
   ``Noriega is contending the real reason is to create the
groundwork for an ultimate American decision to renege on the
commitment to turn over the Panama Canal'' in the year 2000, Solarz
said.
   ``This resolution shows that we fully intend to live up to our
commitments under the Panama Canal treaties,'' Solarz said.
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee already has adopted a
resolution calling for a total trade embargo against Panama, but
several members of the House panel said they thought that approach
was premature.
   Several members said their resolution is more in tune with
Reagan administration measured strategy and is essentially an
endorsement of a targeted approach designed to put pressure on
Noriega while not harming the Panamanian people as a whole.
</TEXT>
