<DOCNO> AP880308-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1425EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Taxes     03-08 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taxes,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Less Tax Cheating Because of Law Changes, Tougher Policing, IRS
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheating on federal income taxes has declined
by as much as 20 percent, mainly because of tax law changes and
tougher federal policing, Internal Revenue Service Commissioner
Lawrence B. Gibbs said Tuesday.
   Gibbs told a House Appropriations subcommittee an IRS study
indicates the much-publicized ``tax gap'' _ the difference between
taxes owed and taxes paid _ has dropped to between $80 billion and
$90 billion in 1987. The agency's last report on the annual gap
estimated it would rise to more than $100 billion in 1987.
   Gibbs attributed the decline to campaigns by Congress and the
IRS to force stricter compliance, through tougher penalties and the
computer-matching of tax returns with income reports, and to the
numerous changes brought about by the 1986 tax law revision.
   The commissioner announced also that the IRS has temporarily
suspended efforts to collect back taxes from students who were paid
stipends for teaching or research work at their universities.
   ``We've put the word out (to IRS offices) to hold up on any'' of
the students' cases that are pending until the agency adopts a
consistent policy on how such income should be treated, Gibbs said.
   He said cases affecting students who receive stipends developed
from a computer matching of employer reports with students' tax
returns _ not from any IRS initiative to ``go after the graduate
students.''
   In dispute are stipends paid in 1984, 1985 and 1986. The 1986
tax revision declared all such stipends to be taxable income.
   IRS officials said they had no estimate how many students are
involved in the controversy, although The Washington Post on
Tuesday quoted unofficial estimates of up to 17,000 cases.
   ``Apparently there are some inconsistencies in the way the
examination of students' returns are being conducted,'' IRS
spokesman Steve Pyrek said. There is a wide variety of stipends
paid by colleges and universities, he noted, and some IRS field
offices are following court decisions on the issue while others
abide by a 1975 ruling by the agency itself.
   ``In looking at the cases, case law is a lot harsher (toward
students) than our rules,'' Gibbs told the subcommittee.
   The students' troubles began when their colleges sent the IRS
copies of W-2 wage statements indicating they were paid taxable
wages. When the students filed their tax returns, the computer
indicated those wages were not reported as income.
   Gibbs said the IRS hopes to announce within a month new
guidelines on treatment of such stipends from the three earlier tax
years.
   Also within a short time, the commissioner said, he hopes to be
able to report on the new estimate of the tax gap. He declined to
provide any details of the new findings but told the subcommittee:
``The amount of the tax gap has diminished since the last time we
did a study.''
   The last IRS study of the tax gap was published in 1983 and was
based on 1981 information. It estimated that individuals and
corporations dodged $81.5 billion in taxes on legal income that
year, by understating income and overstating deductions.
   The agency estimated that another $9 billion in taxes was lost
on three types of illegal income: drugs, prostitution and gambling.
The new report will not even attempt to estimate the tax loss from
illegal income that is never reporte.
   Since the last tax-gap study was published, IRS researchers have
reported evidence that taxpayers may be cheating less. In May 1986,
the agency released a report indicating that a 20-year trend of
declining compliance with the tax laws might have been reversed.
   That study estimated that voluntary compliance rose to 91.8
percent in 1982, from 91.0 percent in 1979. Compliance had declined
steadily from 94.3 percent in 1965.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
