<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Madonna,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Madonna Play To Bypass Lincoln Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Speed-The-Plow,'' the new David Mamet play
starring Madonna and produced by the Lincoln Center Theater, will
bypass that cultural complex altogether and open directly on
Broadway, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   The play was to have been performed at the small, 299-seat Mitzi
Newhouse Theater in Lincoln Center before moving to Broadway's
Royale Theater in late April, said Merle Debuskey.
   Now it will begin preview performances April 9 at the Royale for
a May opening, possibly May 3, Debuskey said. He said ``Boys'
Life,'' the current tenant at the Newhouse, will extend its run
there until June 5. The play, written by Howard Korder, was to have
closed March 13.
   The Lincoln Center Theater, run by Gregory Mosher and Bernard
Gersten, has has experienced a booking jam at its two theaters.
``Anything Goes'' has been a solid hit at the larger Vivian
Beaumont Theater where it opened in October. Debuskey said the
vintage Cole Porter musical would remain until July 31 and then
transfer to Broadway.
   The Lincoln Center Theater opened its fall season at the Mitzi
Newhouse with ``Sarafina!'', a South African musical which has
moved to Broadway. Following ``Boys' Life'' at the Newhouse will be
``Road,'' by English playwright Jim Cartwright. It will open June
29.
   Debuskey also confirmed that ``Waiting for Godot,'' starring
Steve Martin, Robin Williams, F. Murray Abraham and Bill Irwin,
would be on the company's fall schedule. It will begin performances
Oct. 25 at the Newhouse, he said.
</TEXT>
