<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Fashion     03-08 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fashion,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fendi's Fake Furs Win Bravos In Milan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MIL6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEONORA DODSWORTH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Italian sisters showed their latest
furry creations at fall-winter shows Tuesday alongside the real
skins, and they dared the audience to guess which was which.
   Women who still yearn to wear the big cats can now choose the
Fendi sisters' version consisting of ocelot markings printed on
synthetic fur fabric coats with the added bonus of cuffs in real
sable.
   Karl Lagerfeld, who designs the Fendi collection, is never short
on witty ideas and when he wasn't making fabric look like fur, he
was reversing the process to make furs imitate fabrics. His long
winter coats in shaved weasel worked to look like corduroy velvet
were a case in point.
   There were plenty of other surprises, such as the big muffs in
chinchilla or sable which, at a flick of the models' wrists, became
complete fur coats.
   But although Lagerfeld had his fun with the fakes, he also
indulged in the real thing, showing styles in sumptuous mink,
sable, ermine and Mongolian lamb so lavish that that they could
retail for as much as $100,000.
   Favored shapes included high-waisted, oval-skirted coats that
harked back to the fashions in vogue in the early 1920s. Shoulders
were soft and natural with padding sent into retirement.
   There were spectacular capes such as the circular version in
black-dyed mole threaded intricately into lace, and shapely coats
in black ermine worked to look like shiny and matte-striped silk
velvet.
   A princess-line coat, fitted and flared, came in woven gray wool
and had an extra layer of warmth in its luxury lining of sumptuous
chinchilla.
</TEXT>
