<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Haitians Intercepted,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Intercepts Second Haitian Boat in Two Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Haitian sailing vessel with 60 people aboard was
intercepted Monday about 300 miles southeast of Miami, a U.S. Coast
Guard spokesman said.
   A ship holding 190 Haitians without legal entry papers was found
Saturday by the Coast Guard, and passengers were being sent back to
Port-au-Prince.
   Monday's interception was made by the cutter Vigorous near
Crooked Island in the Bahamas chain, said Coast Guard spokesman
Luis Diaz.
   The 45 men, 12 women and three children will be taken back to
Haiti by the Vigorous, he said.
   Coast Guard vessels were also searching Monday for another ship
reportedly in the area, said Diaz.
   Diaz said there had been a lull in Haitian interceptions in
recent months, and that the two seizures could signal renewed
efforts to enter the country illegally.
