<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--7-UpRuling     03-08 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--7-Up Ruling,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Reinstate Damages After Reducing Them</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has denied a motion to reconsider
his reduction of a $10.5 million jury award to an 83-year-old woman
who was struck in the eye by a 7-Up bottle cap.
   Third District Court Judge Kenneth Rigtrup on Monday let stand
his Feb. 17 reduction to $375,000 the damages due Mae Roberts of
Holladay.
   Rigtrup said the jurors were ``inflamed with passion'' and had
awarded damages that were ``disproportionate and unreasonable.''
   Rigtrup awarded $75,000 in compensatory and $300,000 in punitive
damages. The jury had awarded $500,000 in compensatory damages and
$10 million in punitive damages.
   Colin King, the plaintiff's attorney, has said the judge's
action would nullify the jury's attempt to punish 7-Up and to send
a message to bottlers that negligence would not be tolerated.
   Roberts was struck in the eye when an aluminum twist-off cap
blew off a soda bottle she was opening with a pair of pliers. As a
result, the sight in her left eye was impaired.
   King said Roberts is unlikely to seek another trial because of
her age.
</TEXT>
