<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dominican-Unrest     03-08 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-Unrest,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Coalition Rejects Concessions; Strike Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,000 supporters
of President Joaquin Balaguer marched through the capital Tuesday
on the eve of a 48-hour general strike called by the opposition.
   ``To the conspirators, we're going to give hell,'' shouted the
Balaguer supporters, who ended their afternoon rally at the
National Palace.
   A tense calm prevailed in the rest of the city of 1.5 million.
Police and soldiers were out in force, but the barricades, burning
tires and stone-throwing mobs of last week were absent.
   Wednesday's strike was called by the National Conference of
Popular Organizations, which claims to represent about 200 groups.
The issue is the soaring cost of living in this Caribbean nation of
6 million.
   Inflation last year rose 30 percent, according to private
economists, who predict that this year it will top 50 percent. The
Central Bank estimates inflation hit 16 percent in 1987.
   Coalition spokesman Fabio Ruiz said Balaguer's pledge to
implement price controls on bananas, onions, potatoes, rice and
beans, ``don't satisfy our demands.''
   The coalition also rejected Balaguer's pledge, made last month,
to increase the minimum wage by 33 percent to about $75 a month.
   Rising prices for gasoline, meat and other basic commodities
have touched off protests in several of the Dominican Republic's 26
provinces. In the past two weeks, six people have been killed and
about 20 injured by gunshots, tear gas or stones. Several hundred
people have been detained.
   Leftist groups and unions claimed Tuesday that police arrested
some of their leaders _ including Diaz Jaquez of the Dominican
Workers Party and Rafael Abreu of the General Workers Central _
without warrant, and interrogated others.
   Armed Forces Minister Lt. Gen. Antonio Imbert Barrera said
soldiers will patrol city streets and give ``full support'' to the
national police.
   The strike Wednesday is opposed by the main labor unions, the
Dominican Revolutionary Party, which is the main opposition party,
and the influential Roman Catholic Church. Those groups and others
have urged that compromises be negotiated to resolve the economic
problems.
</TEXT>
