<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Falklands     03-08 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Falklands,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says Falklands Exercise `No One Else's Business'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Tuesday that
Britain's current military exercise to reinforce the Falkland
Islands against possible attack by Argentina was ``no one else's
business.''
   Flatly rejecting protests by Argentina and other Latin American
countries, Mrs. Thatcher told the House of Commons that Britain had
a right and also ``a duty to see that reinforcement proposals could
in fact be carried out.''
   ``It is no one else's business except the defense of people's
rights in the Falkland Islands,'' said Mrs. Thatcher.
   About 900 troops will travel 8,000 miles next week to the
Falkland Islands from Brize Norton air base, north of London, as
part of the exercise, called Fire Focus.
   The exercise began this week with mythical ``intelligence
reports'' warning that Argentina was preparing again to invade the
south Atlantic archipelago which it has long claimed. The 1,800
British-descended islanders fiercely reject Argentine rule.
   Fire Focus is the first major maneuver announced by Britain
since it recaptured the islands from invading Argentine troops in a
74-day war in 1982.
   Britain has said it gave notice last month to Argentina of the
intended exercise and has since announced that Fire Focus will
involve fewer than 1,000 men.
   Britain maintains a garrison, reportedly of about 2,000 men, on
the islands and says it must practice sending in reinforcements in
order to avoid keeping more troops there permanently.
   Briefing reporters at Brize Norton on Tuesday, Foreign Office
Assistant Under Secretary Robin Fearn said Fire Focus ``threatens
no one. It is entirely defensive.''
   ``Far from being a cause for concern, it is an integral part of
our policy of reducing tension,'' he added.
   He said the initial post-war garrison had been halved in recent
years after the completion of a new runway at the Falklands
capital, Port Stanley, which can take wide-bodied jets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
