<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CulturalExchange     03-08 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cultural Exchange,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organizers Say Soviet-U.S. Cultural Exchange Still On, Despite
Cash Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $350,000 shortfall is casting a shadow on the
largest-ever Soviet-U.S. cultural exchange, a three-week festival
viewed by the State Department as an important symbol of improved
relations with Moscow, fund-raisers said Tuesday.
   With three days to go before its scheduled opening, ``Making
Music Together'' is heavily in the red because of unexpected costs,
said Harold Hestes, president of the Greater Boston Chamber of
Commerce.
   Hestes declined to detail what drove costs above the estimated
budget of $2.4 million, but said revised figures put the price tag
for the 80-event festival at about $3.3 million.
   Festival Operating Co. which is managing the American part of
the exchange, last month seriously considered the idea of declaring
bankruptcy and canceling the event, said lawyer Gabor Garai.
   Instead, company directors agreed to try and raise additional
funds ``in light of the national and international importance of
the event,'' said Garai, whose firm, Hale and Dorr, is providing
free legal counsel to organizers.
   Billed by U.S. organizers as the largest cultural exchange ever
with the Soviet Union, the festival, which runs though April 2,
will feature 285 Soviet musicians, dancers, composers and other
artists performing in the Boston area.
   It will continue in Moscow in the fall of 1989, where the
festival will concentrate on contemporary American music.
   Organizers originally had hoped to cover most costs through
ticket sales, a state contribution of $450,000 and private sector
pledges of $350,000.
   The state has promised to provide more grants and loans
amounting to $400,000, and businessess and charitable organizations
have pledged an additional $150,000, Hestes said.
   Of the outstanding $350,000, Hestes said, ``We're doing our best
to raise it (but) the cash flow situation is extremely tight.''
   ``It would be my hope that that the festival goes on no matter
what, as it would be tragedy for the state and the nations if it
would fail,'' he said.
   Hestes said he contacted the State Department about possible
cancellation recently, and ``the clear inference ... (was) that it
would be bad for our relations with the Soviet Union.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz expressed his personal
support and that of President Ronald Reagan last year, in a letter
to Sarah Caldwell, a key organizer of the exchange and artistic
director of the Opera Company of Boston.
   ``I want you to know that both the president and I personally
support these exchanges ....,'' he wrote to Ms. Caldwell. ``These
exchanges will continue to be an important element in the
U.S.-Soviet relationship.''
   Ms. Caldwell provided a copy of the Sept. 8 letter to The
Associated Press.
   In Washington, Greg Guroff, of the government-run U.S.
Information Agency, said he believes the Soviet Union ``has made a
tremendous commitment to this festival.''
   Guroff, head of the agency's office of U.S.-Soviet exchanges and
a former cultural attache to the U.S. Embassy in Moscow, said the
Soviets would interpret cancellation as a rebuff.
   Because of guaranteed state funding of such events in the Soviet
Union, ``the American concept of fund-raising for most Soviets
...(is) not only incomprehensible, but it's not their problem,''
said Guroff. ``We have had two or three performing arts exchanges
that have fallen through from lack of funding: The fallout was
quite considerable in the Soviets' minds.''
</TEXT>
