<HEAD>Justice O'Connor Doing Fine Following Appendix Surgery, Court Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor was
reported ``in good spirits'' and feeling well Tuesday after having
her appendix removed.
   O'Connor, 57, underwent the surgery Monday night at Bethesda
Naval Hospital.
   Court spokeswoman Toni House said O'Connor was feeling
``exceedingly well'' but gave few other details.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, asked about O'Connor after he testified
before a House subcommittee on the Supreme Court's budget request
for next fiscal year, said he had spoken to her by telephone
Tuesday morning.
   ``She sounded in good spirits,'' he said. ``I think she'll be
back to work shortly.''
   O'Connor had been scheduled to testify with Scalia but she was
taken to the hospital in midafternoon Monday, and was operated on
about 8 p.m.
   Scalia explained O'Connor's absence to the subcommittee members
by saying, ``She had a supervening appointment with an
appendectomy.''
