<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Chistensen-SurfaceMining     03-08 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chistensen-Surface Mining,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strip Mining Chief Leaving Post March 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jed Christensen, director of the Office of
Surface Mining for the past three years, is leaving his job March
20, the Interior Department announced Tuesday.
   Christensen, who served as the government's chief regulator of
strip mining longer than anyone else, will become assistant chief
administrative officer of Fresno County, Calif.
   His boss will be Dan Fitzpatrick, with whom he worked previously
when Chistensen was a budget officer for Clark County, Nev. ``He
called me (just after taking office) and asked if I would be
interested ... I will be getting back to my roots.''
   He said he was ``not in the least'' pushed out.
   Christensen also has worked in local government in Provo, Utah;
Phoenix, Ariz and Santa Anna, Calif.
   He came to the Interior Department in 1981 and was appointed
acting director of the Office of Surface Mining in April 1985,
winning nomination as director in December 1985 and confirmation in
May 1986.
   Robert H. Gentile, an aide to Steven Griles, assistant secretary
for land and minerals management, has been appointed deputy to
Chistensen for operations, the department said.
   Christensen said it was ``up to the secretary'' to decide on a
successor, but other officials, speaking on condition they not be
identified, said they expected Gentile to be named acting director,
perhaps for the remainder of the Reagan administration.
   The office, formed by Congress in 1977 after a decade of bitter
debate, was subjected to a wrenching reorganization by
then-Secretary James Watt in 1981. When Christensen took over, some
violation records were still stored in shoeboxes.
   Christensen said most of the $150 million in penalties
represented by those boxes would be written off by the end of this
fiscal year, with about 15 percent of the amount finally collected,
and the records now kept on a computer.
   His tenure also has seen installation of another computer system
to match applicants for mining permits in the states against the
list of outstanding violations, and the abolition by Congress of
the exemption from most regulation for mines under two acres. That
exemption had enabled some big companies in Virginia and Kentucky
to break their operations into a ``string of pearls'' _ mines of
less than two acres operated by subcontractors.
   ``I'm amazed at the things we've accomplished,'' he said,
listing among other things better relations with the states and
forthcoming proposals for criminal penalties for mining without a
permit and for incentives for miners to take coal from and reclaim
abandoned mines.
   Thomas Galloway, a Washington lawyer who has represented
environmental groups in several lawsuits against the agency, said
Christensen's departure was ``not a major move,'' since ``he was
not involved in major issues over the past year ... we have been
dealing with the assistant secretary's office.''
   Galloway said he believed the office was ``probably in the worst
shape it's been since 1977'' in terms of competence and
effectiveness, which he said was ``not entirely the Reagan
administration's fault.''
   ``I believe abuse is continuing unchecked'' in parts of
Kentucky, West Virginia, Virginia and Tennessee, largely at the
hands of miners operating on a shoestring, Galloway said.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., who as chairman of the environment
subcommittee of the House Government Operations Committee has
produced several reports critical of the office, said a change in
directors ``will be meaningless, just like all the others have
been.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
