<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DallasPolice     03-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dallas Police,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Withdraw from One Polling Place After Conflict With Drive
Opponent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Off-duty police gathered signatures at polling
places Tuesday in a drive to abolish a citizens review board, but
said they abandoned their efforts at one site after being
confronted by a City Council member.
   ``In at least one of the polling places, we had to leave because
(Mayor Pro Tem) Diane Ragsdale and some of her cohorts started to
create problems, so we just decided to leave because it was not
worth it,'' said Dallas Police Association President Monica Smith.
   ``Ms. Ragsdale started an argument, trying to convince people
not to sign the petitions, and rather than getting it to escalate,
we pulled out,'' said Ms. Smith.
   Ms. Ragsdale, a vocal critic of the police, said there was no
confrontation.
   ``This gentleman wanted to know from me what to do. He wanted to
know about the issue because, you know, many of them _ actually,
some of our citizens, seniors _ really don't know,'' she said.
   ``They do not realize what they are doing,'' she said. ``They
attempted to circumvent their policy makers.''
   But one DPA spokesman, Larry McGowan, said Ms. Ragsdale grabbed
one man trying to sign a petition.
   Ms. Smith said signatures were being collected citywide by about
1,400 off-duty officers, 200 to 300 firefighters and their
families. The campaign to abolish the Dallas Citizens Police Review
Board has drawn opposition from a coalition of black business,
community, church and elected leaders.
   The DPA wants the city to hire more officers and abolish the
board, which hears complaints against police. The board was formed
in January and has met twice.
   Twenty thousand signatures are needed to force a City Charter
amendment election.
   The Texas secretary of state had poll monitors at voting places,
also observing the police effort.
   Three Dallas officers have been shot and killed this year,
including John Chase, who was shot by a deranged transient as a
bus-stop crowd watched the homeless man ignore the officer's pleas
to spare his life.
   Four men have also been killed by officers this year, including
the transient who killed Chase.
   Opponents of the citizens review board, which has limited
subpoena powers, say it duplicates existing panels or agencies,
including the police internal affairs department and the Dallas
County grand jury, and calls into question the department's ability
to police itself.
</TEXT>
