<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Plywood-Canada     03-08 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Plywood-Canada,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Defend Plywood Provisions In US-Canada Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest lawmakers and representatives of the
timber industry said Tuesday the new U.S.-Canada free trade treaty
will do little to open Canadian markets to American-manufactured
plywood, but Reagan administration officials said it was a step in
the right direction.
   ``It's one-way free trade,'' Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., said
during a House subcommittee hearing. ``The U.S. is being snookered
again.''
   Both DeFazio and Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said the treaty will
allow Canadian plywood manufacturers unrestricted access to
American markets but only 10 percent of the Canadian market, at
best, will be opened to U.S. producers.
   ``I think a provision like this provides red meat to the
protectionists,'' said Wyden, adding that Congress should draft
strong language covering plywood trade when it consider
implementing language for the treaty later this year.
   Oregon is the top plywood producing state in the nation and
Washington state ranks No. 4. Other states in the top five include
Louisiana, Texas and Arkansas.
</TEXT>
