<HEAD>Sales Increase For Sixth Consecutive Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. savings bonds increased for the
sixth consecutive month in February, rising 2 percent to $658
million, the government reported Tuesday.
   The Treasury Department said that February sales were $13
million higher than January and were 2 percent above the level of a
year ago, when sales were $646 million.
   With the inclusion of interest earnings, the value of
outstanding bonds rose by $1 billion to total $103.24 billion, 10
percent higher than a year ago.
   Since November 1982, savings bonds held five years or longer
have earned market-based interest rates. The current rate, in
effect until May 1, is 7.17 percent.
</TEXT>
