<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ScotusBudget     03-08 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus Budget,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scalia Warns That Budget Cut Would Hurt Court's Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia told a
House subcommittee Tuesday that trimming the high court's $16.4
budget request could ``cut not fat, not muscle but bone.''
   Scalia, submitting a budget request for the fiscal year that
begins next October, warned that the court cannot withstand an
appropriations reduction similar to one imposed for its current
budget.
   ``We come close to becoming the proverbial turnip'' from which
no more blood can be squeezed, Scalia said.
   The court last year requested $16 million for its current,
fiscal year 1988 budget but only $15.2 million was appropriated.
   ``This has put a very serious strain on the operations of the
court during the current fiscal year,'' Scalia said.
   The fiscal year 1989 request includes:
   _$100,000 for increased library shelving capacity.
   _$40,000 to upgrade into legal research databases the word
processors the justices and their law clerks use.
   _$50,000 to celebrate the 200th anniversary of the federal law
that created the federal court system.
   The Supreme Court's budget is handled separately from the
billion-dollar budget of the federal court system but most of the
subcommittee's questions, focused on problems facing the federal
judiciary generally.
   Rep. Joseph D. Early, D-Mass., asked several questions about
what he apparently views as dwindling judicial efficiency.
   Noting that ``there are a lot more laws out there,'' Scalia
said, ``You simply cannot lay too much additional responsibility
upon this institution (the federal courts) without fundamentally
changing'' it.
   Responding to a similar question by Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz.,
Scalia said the caseload problem facing federal courts ``originates
right here (in Congress) and I don't see an answer to it.''
</TEXT>
