<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-SouthAfrica     03-08 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-South Africa,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Vetoes Resolution To Impose Sanctions On South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Britain on Tuesday
vetoed a Security Council resolution to impose economic sanctions
on South Africa in an effort to end apartheid.
   The measure failed by a vote of 10-2, with France, West Germany
and Japan abstaining.
   The resolution would have imposed mandatory worldwide sanctions,
including an oil embargo, for a year.
   All the speakers deplored South Africa's state of emergency and
recent restrictions on anti-apartheid groups.
   In their speeches, the representatives of France and Italy
condemned Pretoria's ban on activities by major anti-apartheid
groups and urged dialogue between the white-led government and the
black majority. However, the representatives did not endorse
mandatory sanctions.
   The United States and some other Western nations have opposed
similar measures in the past. The five permanent members of the
Security Council _ the United States, Britain, China, France and
the Soviet Union _ have veto power.
   The resolution proposed a ban on export and sale of oil to South
Africa, the discontinuation of iron and steel imports from South
Africa, an end to loans to South Africa, a ban on sale of coins
minted in South Africa and a halt to all military, police or
intelligence cooperation with South Africa.
   In Johannesburg, Foreign Minister Pik Botha said on national
television that ``I wrote the words'' used by South Africa's U.N.
ambassador, Leslie Manley, last Thursday when he told the council,
``Do your damnedest.''
   ``Either we're strong enough to withstand and resist the
onslaught against us or we're not,'' Botha said.
   The draft resolution invoked Chapter 7 of the U.N. Charter,
which provides for economic sanctions and other measures when
international peace and security are threatened.
   Last Thursday the council opened a debate to condemn South
Africa's ban Feb. 24 on activities by major anti-apartheid groups.
It is expected to pass a resolution expressing outrage and
condemnation.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
