<HEAD>Four Indicted in Police Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four suspects in the killing of a rookie police
officer as he sat in a patrol car were indicted Tuesday,
authorities said.
   Todd Scott, 19, Scott Cobb, 24, Philip Copeland, 22; and David
McClary, 22, were indicted on charges of second-degree murder and
criminal possession of a weapon, said Richard Piperno, spokesman
for the district attorney's office.
   Edward Byrne, 22, was shot in the head Feb. 26 as he sat in his
car guarding the home of a man who had complained about crack
dealing in the borough of Queens.
   All four suspects have been held without bail since pleading
innocent at arraignments Friday and Saturday.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said police believe a major
drug dealer ordered the hit. The arrests followed a week-long
investigation that included a roundup of 294 suspected dealers in
Queens.
   Ward said the suspects met in a Queens apartment Feb. 25 to plan
the murder of a police officer. Police alleged that Copeland was at
the planning session, but not the slaying.
   It was not known who pulled the trigger. McClary and Scott have
pointed the finger at each other, police said.
