<HEAD>Sheriff's Department Tries Tracing Mystery Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He calls himself Dee Jay, says he is 17 and
ran away from New York City. But beyond that, sheriff's deputies
say they have no idea who he is or how to help him.
   ``This kid has been in limbo for 17 years _ or more. He doesn't
know who he is or anything,'' Montgomery County Chief Deputy Gary
Haines said Monday.
   Haines appealed for public help to identify Dee Jay, saying
routine missing-person checks and other leads have turned up
nothing since the man was arrested outside a bar March 2.
   Dee Jay appears to have a severe learning disability, Haines
said. He also told investigators he may have been involved in
pornography films and other abuse, Haines said.
   Dee Jay was picked up after deputies were called to investigate
a car burglar alarm outside a bar, Haines said.
   ``His explanation is that he heard the alarm go off while he was
in the lounge,'' said Claudia Marlin, the department's victim
advocate. She said he was in the lounge because, ``they have free
hors d'oeuvres and he was hungry.''
   Dee Jay was not charged and is in the custody of the Montgomery
County Children Services Board, Haines said. He cannot read or use
a telephone and can barely write, Haines said.
   He is described as black, 6-foot-2, weighing about 150 pounds,
with black hair and brown eyes. He was wearing a black-and-silver
sweater and washed jeans, Haines said.
   Dee Jay told Ms. Marlin he lived with a man named Rick in a
three-bedroom apartment in the New York City borough of the Bronx.
He said he got occasional tutoring and once was treated by a doctor
for the flu, she said.
   He said he hitchhiked from the Bronx on a truck, ended up in
Dayton around Christmas and slept in trucks and in doorways, Ms.
Marlin said.
