<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-US,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency Criticizes U.S. Queries About Conflict Of Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization
criticized the United States Tuesday for its questions about how
the agency handles its money and hires employees.
   Fred J. Eckert, U.S. ambassador to the agency, sent a letter to
FAO Director-General Edouard Saouma seeking details of agency
spending, hiring practices and Saouma's compensation package.
   ``These are serious and important questions,'' Eckert said
Tuesday.
   Agency spokesman Richard Lydiker said: ``The director-general
regrets that requests for information have been presented as
aspersions on the management and reputation of the FAO. As requests
for information they are legitimate. But as aspersions they are
groundless.''
   ``Throughout his entire term of office the director-general has
scrupulously observed (the agency's) rules and regulations and this
will be demonstrated in his reply to the permanent representative
of the United States,'' Lydiker said, reading from a statement.
   He also noted that the United States has not paid its
contribution to the agency. Lydiker said earlier this year that the
United States owes $68 million from its 1986-87 assessment, which
amounts to a quarter of the agency's budget.
   Saouma, a Lebanese, was elected to a third six-year term in
November, defeating an African challenger supported by the United
States and other major donor nations.
   The United States and other nations have called for reforms at
the organization, which coordinates agricultural projects in
developing countries and is the largest specialized agency in the
United Nations.
   Last November, a 1988-89 FAO budget of $492 million was approved
over objections from the United States, Britain, Australia and
Canada.
   ``In the course of our review, we have become increasingly
concerned about reports portraying FAO in an extremely unfavorable
light. The questions that we shall be putting to you are for the
purpose of getting at the truth of these matters,'' Eckert said in
his letter, dated March 3.
   The letter also asked for an explanation about travel expenses
for delegates to a recent agency conference, the agency's purchase
of cars and details of entertainment allowances.
   It asked how many former ambassadors were on the agency's
payroll and whether relatives of current or former ambassadors work
for the agency.
</TEXT>
