<HEAD>Congress Urged To Step Up Pressure On Haiti</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf bgng ``Michael S. Hooper'' to CORRECT name of
organization to National Coalition For Haitian Refugees.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress was urged by a trio of witnesses
Tuesday to increase economic and diplomatic pressure on Haiti to
spur a return to democratic rule.
   But the Latin American director of the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, a Washington-based conservative think tank,
called on the United States to restore aid to Haiti.
   The witness, Georges Fauriol, said the new government of Haitian
President Leslie Manigat ``deserves encouragement and resources _
rather than further sanctions and further hardship for the Haitian
people.''
   ``Barring gross misjudgment and behavior on the part of the new
government, the United States, at a minimum, should reinstate the
aid package cut off last November,'' Fauriol said.
   But other witnesses disagreed.
   Rep. George W. Crockett Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the House
Foreign Affairs subcommittee on Western Hemisphere affairs, said
Washington needs to make clear ``that the United States government
will use every diplomatic, political and economic means at our
disposal to help accomplish a free and fair election in Haiti.''
   A Haitian journalist, Raymond A. Joseph, urged Manigat to call
new elections and order the investigation of politically inspired
killings.
   Michael S. Hooper, executive director of the National Coalition
for Haitian Refugees, said the Reagan administration would end the
hope for free and fair elections in Haiti if it moves to embrace
the Manigat government, which was installed after Haiti's military
forces broke up earlier presidential elections.
   ``The United States should immediately institute and recommend a
complete (international) arms embargo and an end to all assistance
that frees up domestic resources allowing the government to sustain
the growing army,'' Hooper said.
   Patrick Bellegarde-Smith, an author specializing in Haiti and
its problems, called on the United States to continue the aid
cutoff, to oppose all loans to Haiti by international lending
institutions, to withdraw Haiti's privileges under the Caribbean
Basin Initiative, and to insist Haiti restore democratic government
and end the use of the country as a haven for narcotics trafficking.
</TEXT>
