<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SuperCollider     03-08 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Collider,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE Won't Get Extra Funds for Super-Collider Site Evaluation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The congressional appropriations committees
have denied a request by the Energy Department to shift $8 million
to pay for evaluation of possible sites for the $4.4 billion
super-collider atom smasher, the department said Tuesday.
   ``We are looking at our options,'' department spokesman Jeff
Sherwood said.
   The department is seeking $363 million in the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1 to begin construction of the collider, a
53-miles-around tunnel that would smash beams of protons into each
other.
   Last year it requested $25 million for design and $10 million
for early construction work that was not tied to a site, but
Congress approved only the $25 million.
   Sherwood said the department had not sought site evaluation
funds until it knew how many sites it would have to deal with.
Twenty-five states submitted proposals for 35 sites, a list that
was narrowed to seven finalists in December.
   Until recently the department had planned to write an
environmental impact statement only for its final choice, expected
to be made tentatively in July, but last month Secretary John
Herrington told Congress that choice would be delayed until
November, and the department said it would assess environmental
impacts for all seven sites.
   There is substantial congressional opposition to the heavy
spending required for the project. Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La.,
chairman of the Energy and Natural Resources Committee and also of
the energy and water development subcommittee of the Appropriations
Committee, warned Herrington that the department might not get all
the money it was seeking in the new fiscal year.
   The $8 million would have been shifted from general
administrative funds of the department for the current fiscal year.
   Sherwood said the department could take evaluation funds from
the $25 million, at the cost of slowing down design of the magnets
that guide the proton beams, or could delay the evaluations,
perhaps at the cost of pushing the site selection decision into the
next administration.
   ``We would very much like to keep to our planned schedule,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
