<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OperaTickets     03-08 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Opera Tickets,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Opera Raises Ticket Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising production costs and a weakening dollar
overseas are forcing the Washington Opera to raise ticket prices
and reduce the number of performances next season, officials said
Tuesday. The best orchestra seats will sell for $60, up from $49.50
this year.
   Despite the first major boost in ticket prices since 1981,
general director Martin Feinstein said the opera still must raise
$300,000 privately to stage a new production of Giacomo Puccini's
``Tosca'' for its season opener in the Kennedy Center Opera House
on Nov. 5.
   Tenor Placido Domingo will star in that production, which will
be directed by Gian Carlo Menotti and conducted by Rafael Fruhbeck
de Burgos.
   Other season highlights will include Peter Tchaikovsky's ``Pique
Dame'' (The Queen of Spades), conducted by Mstislav Rostropovich
and directed by his wife, Galina Vishnevskaya, and Stephen Paulus'
``The Postman Always Rings Twice,'' a 1982 musical adaptation of
James M. Cain's Depression-era novel.
   The cheapest seats in Washington will sell for $20 in the
Kennedy Center's Eisenhower Theater, where smaller operas are
staged, and standing room remains $10. Students and senior citizens
can still buy half-price tickets.
   Feinstein blamed the increase on mounting production costs and a
50 percent decline in the value of the dollar abroad in the past
three years, which makes it more expensive to hire Domingo and
other foreign singers.
   The budget squeeze also forced Feinstein to reduce the number of
performances from 66 to 48 next season and to present seven instead
of the current eight operas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
