<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0721,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Missiles Fired; Iraq Reports Raid on Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf bgng: Iraq said... with 1 graf to update with
two missiles fired at Isfahan. Pick up 5th graf: Tehran radio...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq fired missiles at each
other's cities Tuesday and the Iraqis said their warplanes raided
an Iranian oil tanker. It was the first reported attack on Persian
Gulf shipping in weeks.
   Iran claimed either the United States or France had helped Iraq
modify Soviet-built missiles so they could reach Tehran for the
first time since the war began in September 1980.
   The United States greeted with skepticism a surprise call by the
Soviet Union for the U.N. Security Council to condemn the ``war of
the cities.''
   Iraq said it fired two surface-to-surface rockets at Isfahan in
central Iran in the first missile attack on that city in the
nine-day-old missile duel. It said three missiles were fired into
Tehran and one at the holy city of Qom.
   Tehran radio said 12 civilians were killed when the missiles
struck residential areas in the three cities, damaging houses,
shops and a medical center.
   Iraq has reported hitting Tehran with 43 missiles since Feb. 29
and Iran says it has fired 23 into Baghdad.
   Iran said it fired a missile Tuesday into Amarah, an Iraqi town
halfway between Baghdad and the southern port of Basra, and two at
Mosul, an important northern oil center. Iraq reported casualties
but did not specify how many.
   Iran has said 134 people have been killed and more than 300
wounded in the latest round of the ``war of the cities.'' Iraq says
there have been many civilian casualties, but has not mentioned
figures.
   A dispatch from the official Iraqi News Agency said warplanes
raided a ``very large naval target'' off Iran. The phrase usually
means an Iranian supertanker.
   Maritime sources said they had no information about the raid,
which would be the first confirmed attack on a commercial ship in
the gulf since Feb. 12. More than 400 have been hit in the 7{ years
of war.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of Iran's Parliament, said the
missiles being fired by Iraq are Soviet-made Scud-Bs, which
previously have been used against Iranian border cities.
   ``In order to increase the range of the missiles, they have been
clumsily tampered with,'' he said. ``There is no doubt that the
major powers did this, such as America or France.''
   Rafsanjani said Iranian military experts had examined several
unexploded missiles and concluded ``that although such missiles
were originally made in Russia, most of the Eastern Bloc countries
manufacture or assemble this missile today, and Iraq can obtain it
from other sources.''
   Western military experts have said the missiles are Scud-Bs
fitted with strap-on boosters enabling them to reach Tehran and
Qom, which are nearly 300 miles from the border.
   The missile normally carries a 1,000-pound warhead and has a
range of 190 miles. Western experts say Iran also uses Scud-Bs,
supplied by its Arab allies Syria and Libya, but it does not need
boosters because Baghdad is only 80 miles from the frontier.
   At the United Nations in New York, Soviet Ambassador Alexander
M. Belonogov told reporters Monday the Security Council must act to
prevent ``further escalation of the military conflict,'' but evaded
a question about whether the Kremlin would approve an arms embargo.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert Okun said a Soviet resolution on the
``war of the cities'' should not ``undercut or erode'' council
Resolution 598 of July 20, which demanded an immediate cease-fire.
</TEXT>
