<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DeafPresident 1stLd-Writethru a0760 03-08 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaf President, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gallaudet University Students Boycott Classes in Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES with faculty support of students, mew material
throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gallaudet University students on Tuesday
boycotted classes to protest the hiring of a hearing woman as the
school for the deaf's next president, while a faculty leader said a
growing number of instructors favor a deaf leader.
   The boycott of classes highlighted a second consecutive day of
stormy protest over the hiring of Elisabeth Ann Zinser, an
administrator with the University of North Carolina at Greensboro
who prevailed over two deaf finalists.
   At an afternoon rally at the school's football field, students
burned effigies of Zinser and board of trustees chairwoman Jane
Bassett Spilman. More than 1,500 students roared their approval in
strong voices and flashing fingers.
   The rally highlighted a day in which most of the school's 1,800
undergraduate and graduate students skipped classes, and nearly a
third of the school's 274 full-time professors did not show up to
teach.
   ``I'm missing an art history test today, and my grades will
probably be hurt,'' said 26-year-old Eric Spanbauer, a sophomore
government major from Decatur, Ill. ``I'm not going to let my deaf
rights get hurt. I've been waiting too long. This is our time.''
   Psychology professor Neil Reynolds, who chairs the school's
21-member faculty senate and a larger group that includes all the
university's faculty, said a growing number of instructors are
advocating a deaf president.
   ``There has been in the past week an escalation of overt support
from faculty members for a deaf president,'' said Reynolds. ``That
is definitely a change.''
   Both the faculty senate and the larger group of instructors will
meet Wednesday to discuss the ongoing controversy, said Reynolds.
   About 30 percent of Gallaudet's professors are deaf, while
nearly 22 percent of the school's support staff is deaf, according
to university publicist Barbara Dennis.
   Students took heart from the support from their mentors, and
were cheered to know that alumni of the nation's only liberal arts
college for the deaf were standing by them.
   ``The alumni sympathize with and support the students,'' Gerald
Burstein, president of the school's alumni association, said at an
afternoon rally. ``We _ unlike hearing members on the board _ know
fully what it is like to be deaf. Those members of the board who
lack confidence in the abilities of deaf persons ... should
resign.''
   Off-campus groups have also rallied behind the students.
   Fred Weiner, a Washington spokesman for the National Association
of the Deaf, said state leaders from his 20,000 member organization
were planning to meet in Washington on Friday to discuss ways of
helping students gain a deaf president.
   Students say they will not stop their protest until Zinser is
replaced with a deaf president, Spilman is replaced, and the
university agrees to make deaf persons a majority on the school's
20-member board of trustees. The board now has just four deaf
members.
   Spilman said Tuesday that the board will stand by its decision
to hire Zinser, vice chancellor of academic affairs at Greensboro.
   ``It was not the intention of the board of trustees to create
turmoil on campus,'' Spilman said in a telephone interview. ``It
was a vote cast in the best interests of the university, and
Elisabeth Ann Zinser was selected for one and only one reason _ she
was the most qualified person.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
