<HEAD>Judge Temporarily Freezes Panamanian Assets In Miami</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with judge temporarily freezing
assets, suit also filed in Boston. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The
suit...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge temporarily froze Panamanian assets
in banks here after a suit was filed Tuesday to prevent the
government of strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega from
withdrawing any funds.
   A similar order was issued last week in New York City, and a
suit was filed Tuesday in Boston as well. A hearing in the Boston
suit was set for Friday.
   The Miami suit lists the Republic of Panama as the plaintiff and
was set in motion by Panama's U.S. Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, who has
refused to recognize the Noriega government.
   The money at issue is ``a substantial amount,'' said Sosa's
attorney, Mark A. Cohen. But he refused to give a figure.
   U.S. District Judge Sidney Arononvitz issued a temporary
restraining issue late Tuesday afternoon preventing the defendant
banks from turning over any funds to Noriega or his government's
agencies. The judge scheduled a hearing on the order for 1:30 p.m.
Wednesday.
   Defendants in the Miami suit were the Citizens and Southern
International Bank, Republic National Bank of Miami, Barnett Bank
of Florida and the Boston-based Bank of New England's international
branch in Miami.
   The suit says Noriega, under indictment for drug smuggling in
Miami and Tampa, illegally dismissed Panama's legal President Eric
Arturo Delvalle on Feb. 25.
   The suit states that Delvalle consitutes the ``only lawful
government of the Republic of Panama and that Gen. Noriega's regime
is illegal.''
   It said only Sosa is authorized to withdraw money from the bank
accounts, and seeks an injunction preventing the banks from making
payments without his approval.
</TEXT>
