<2ND_LINE>AM-Island Coup, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canoe Invasion, Attempted Coup Crushed in Sao Tome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with government
confirmation, new details. CORRECTS spelling of Resistance. No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces crushed an attempted
coup Tuesday on Sao Tome and Principe and killed two of the 40
armed raiders who landed in canoes in the Marxist-ruled West
African nation, a government official said.
   Information Ministry official Joao Carlos said most of the
attackers were captured as they tried to seize National Police
headquarters on the coast of the former Portuguese colony.
   One policeman was wounded and security forces were combing
coastal areas for attackers still on the loose, Portuguese radio
reported from Sao Tome.
   Carlos, speaking in a telephone interview with Portuguese
television, said forces loyal to the Marxist government of
President Manuel Pinto da Costa were securing key facilities,
including broadcasting stations and the airport.
   Sao Tome and Principe lies about 125 miles off the west coast of
Gabon in the Gulf of Guinea. The two-island country, with a
population of 110,000, has one political party, the Sao Tome e
Principe Liberation Movement.
   The Portuguese radio report said the raiders boarded canoes from
a larger craft that anchored offshore.
   President da Costa appealed Tuesday night for vigilance against
attacks in a two-minute broadcast on national radio after an
emergency Cabinet meeting, reports said. He said calm was restored
within hours of the landings on two beaches between 3 and 4 a.m.
   Da Costa blamed the attack on government foes linked to the
National Resistance Front of Sao Tome and Principe. Portuguese TV
said the raiders were suspected of launching the attack from Gabon,
where the Front is based.
   The Front's Lisbon-based secretary-general, Quintiliano Loures
Amadao, denied it was responsible.
   He said the attack may have been carried out by dissidents
within the Front, or members of the Sao Tome and Pricipe armed
forces unhappy over the presence there of Angolan troops.
   The two islands lie on strategic Atlantic shipping lanes. News
reports in 1984 said about 2,000 Soviet and Cuban troops ran two
radio stations and a submarine facility in the area.
   Rumors of an imminent invasion swept Sao Tome and Principe in
1978 and Cuba, Angola and Guinea-Bissau sent troops to help defend
the islands.
   The invasion never materialized, but the country has since
strengthened its ties with Angola, Cuba and the Soviet Union. An
estimated 1,000 Angolan troops are stationed in Sao Tome and
Principe to support the regular army.
   The force supposed to be behind the invasion never was clear.
   The ruling party has not previously faced armed opposition.
Loures Amadao said the Resistance Front supported peaceful dialogue
with the government because it was in no position to engage in an
armed struggle for power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
