<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Urges Israeli Envoy to Convey to Shamir Urgency on Peace
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz told a senior
Israeli envoy Tuesday that he would reject any attempt by Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir to postpone a response to his Mideast peace
plan, an Israeli source said.
   Shultz met for an hour with Israel's former ambassador to
Washington, Moshe Arens, a close Shamir confidante, said the
source, who spoke on condition he not be identified by name. The
State Department confirmed the meeting took place but declined to
comment further.
   Arens asked for the meeting following a letter sent last week by
30 senators to Shultz urging that Shamir cede Israeli-occupied
lands in return for peace with the Arabs.
   The letter by some of Israel's staunchest supporters on Capitol
Hill caused consternation in Jerusalem, which is unused to such
censure from Congress. Shamir is expected to face heavy pressure
from Congress when he comes here for a four-day visit next week.
   Shultz told Arens that ``he sees no good reason why Shamir
cannot come here with an answer'' to the U.S. proposal which calls
for negotiations on a three-year period of Palestinian self-rule to
be followed by talks on a permanent solution for the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip, said the source.
   Shamir on Sunday blocked a Cabinet debate on the proposal, which
Shultz presented during a shuttle diplomacy swing through the
region last week, but said he would bring the subject up for a
decision after he returns from Washington. Shultz asked both Israel
and Jordan for an answer within 10 days.
   Israeli news reports say Shamir will make Shultz a
counterproposal which will include self-rule for the 1.5 million
Palestinians under Israeli control but will not address the
question of the future of the territories.
   Shamir and his right-wing Likud bloc are opposed to a
land-for-peace formula.
   The White House on Monday welcomed the senators' call for Shamir
to give up Arab lands, but the State Department has not responded
publicly. Shultz is expected to answer the senators, possibly later
this week.
   Shultz told Arens that ``Israel can't afford to delay,''
especially in view of the growing congressional and public pressure
for negotiations to resolve the Israeli-Palestinian violence which
has resulted in the killing of some 80 Arabs by Israeli troops over
the past three months.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Chic Hecht of Nevada and several of his fellow
Republicans were working on a letter or statement in response to
last week's letter to Shultz. Hecht, as well as Sens. Jesse Helms
of North Carolina and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, are opposed to
what they view as internal interference in Israeli politics.
</TEXT>
