<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--ShuttleLandings     03-08 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Shuttle Landings,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Shuttle Landing Site Under Construction in Morocco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction has begun at an abandoned
Strategic Air Command base near Ben Guerir, Morocco, to create an
emergency landing site for space shuttles when they begin flying
again, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration said
Tuesday.
   The former SAC base has a 14,000 foot runway, but its surface
must be rejuvenated to make it usable by shuttles that for some
reason they fail to reach the speeds necessary to get into orbit.
   The Ben Guerir base, 40 miles north of Marrakech will be the
fourth emergency site. NASA announced earlier in the week that
another airport site in northwest Africa, in the tiny country of
The Gambia, will be upgraded to accommodate shuttles. The space
agency intends to continue using runways at Zaragoza Air Base and
Moron Air Base in Spain.
   Foundations for shuttle approach and landing aids are being laid
at the new sites and other equipment, including 10 personnel
vehicles, will be shipped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
