<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-08 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain, Thunderstorms from Michigan to Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold air mass moving across the nation's midsection produced
rain and thunderstorms from Michigan to Texas on Tuesday, while
most of the East enjoyed springlike weather.
   Up to an inch of rain was reported across parts of northeast
Texas, northwestern Louisiana and southwestern Arkansas. Half-inch
hail fell at Killeen, Texas. Lake Charles, La., got three-quarters
of an inch of rain in an hour early Tuesday morning.
   High wind buffeted the high Plains and northern Rockies, with
gusts of 61 mph at Brookings, S.D., 53 mph at Mitchell, S.D., and
50 mph at Cheyenne, Wyo.
   Falling snow reduced visibility to a mile or less from northeast
Minnesota into eastern South Dakota.
   Up to four inches of snow was reported across southern and
eastern South Dakota. Huron, S.D., received an inch of new snow the
6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST.
   Rainshowers were scattered across the Pacific Northwest.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 1.38 inches at Lake Charles, La.; 0.97 inch at Jonesboro,
Ark.; 0.96 inch at Leesville, La.; 0.94 inch at Hot Springs, Ark.;
0.70 inch at Little Rock, Ark.; 0.61 inch at Killeen, Texas; 0.51
inch at Lafayette, La.; 0.45 inch at Alexandria, La.; and 0.41 inch
at Marquette, Mich.
   Springlike weather ruled much of the eastern third of the
nation. Skies were mostly sunny across the Ohio Valley and
middle-Atlantic region into New England.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 21 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 89 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The morning low was 15
degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   Wednesday's forecast called for rain showers from central and
southern New England through the lower Great Lakes, the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys into the Atlantic Coast and in the northern
Plateau, western Washington and northwestern Oregon; showers and
thunderstorms across much of the South from the lower Mississippi
Valley into the southern Atlantic; rain and snow showers across
eastern upper Michigan, turning to snow late in the day; and gusty
winds across the northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 30s across the
northern Great Lakes; the upper 20s and 30s across northern Maine;
the 40s from northern Washington into western Montana and from the
eastern Dakotas into southern New England; the 70s across southern
California and Arizona, the central Gulf Coast and the southern
Atlantic Coast; the low 80s across much of Florida and the desert
Southwest; and the 50s and 60s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
