<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Corruption     03-08 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Corruption,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Withdraws Candidacy of Member Accused of Corruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Christian
Democratic Party on Tuesday withdrew the candidacy for the national
legislature of a member under investigation for alleged misuse of
U.S. aid funds.
   Rodolfo Castillo Claramount, vice president of the party,
appeared before the Central Elections Council to remove Luis Mejia
Miranda as a candidate for the National Assembly in elections March
20.
   ``Mejia is going to have support in order to clear up his
personal situation, but we don't want the application of justice to
be blurred if he is elected and possesses (legislative) immunity,''
Castillo told reporters.
   Assembly members have a degree of immunity from prosecution
under Salvadoran law.
   Castillo called on the public prosecutor's office to conduct a
thorough investigation of the allegations against Mejia, which were
reported Sunday by The New York Times.
   The newspaper said Mejia is being investigated for allegedly
misusing up to $2 million of U.S. aid.
   It quoted unidentified Salvadoran and U.S. officials as saying
it could be the largest case of theft of American aid money during
the administration of President Jose Napoleon Duarte, who was
elected for a five-year term in May 1984.
   Mejia on Monday denied the allegations and said, ``Can you
imagine that if I had ($2 million) I would still be in this
country?''
   The New York Times also said Duarte's son Alejandro, who is
running for mayor of San Salvador, was trying to protect Mejia.
   Alejandro Duarte on Monday denied having ties to Mejia.
   According to The New York Times, the money allegedly stolen was
part of a $10 million program to assist war-ravaged areas and help
win the support of Salvadorans in the war against leftist rebels.
   It said Mejia resigned three months ago as director of the
National Commission for the Restoration of Areas, but President
Duarte agreed to allow him to become a party candidate for the
National Assembly on the recommendation of Alejandro Duarte.
</TEXT>
