<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0719,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian Ambassador Asked To Explain Embassy Seizure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with police saying seven, sted six men
involved in consulate assault, none of them embassy workers,
Britons charged.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Foreign Office summoned Panama's
ambassador Tuesday after he hired a British security firm to seize
the Panamanian consulate from diplomats opposed to Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   The assault, in which seven men from the security firm used a
Land Rover to smash through the glass doors of the consulate Monday
night, was condemned by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   ``Differences of opinion should not be fought out on London
streets,'' she told Parliament.
   The Foreign Office said Undersecretary Tim Eggar and Panamanian
Ambassador Guillermo Vega ``had a full discussion of the incident
and the background to it.'' It said Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey
Howe ``is now considering what the ambassador said.'' It did not
elaborate.
   Police announced Tuesday night that the seven security men, all
Britons, had been charged with offenses against public order.
   Consul Eduardo Arango and his staff had remained loyal to
deposed Panamanian President Eric Delvalle, who was ousted Feb. 26
after he tried to fire Noriega, the military chief and power behind
Panama's government.
   Arango, who was not in the consulate at the time of the
takeover, had been fired by Panama's new government but refused to
leave his post, saying Delvalle was the legitimate president.
   It was ``a thuggish way of behaving and an unbelievable way of
doing things in a civilized country,'' Arango told a British
Broadcasting Corp. television interviewer.
   Vega, loyal to Noriega, told reporters that the assailants had
his authority and were ordered into the consulate ``because this
place was full of outsiders to the Panama government.''
   Police said seven men forced their way into the consulate and
that six remained to occupy the offices. They said no one was
injured.
   The seven security employees were questioned by police and after
being charged they were released on an undisclosed amount of bail
for an April 6 court hearing.
   Police identified them as Michael Lord, 35, a security officer;
James Brown, 30, a company executive; Robert Green, 34, a security
consultant; electricians Thomas Anderson, 34, Joseph Anderson, 39,
and Kenneth Ford, 38, and construction worker Kevin Noble, 26. They
worked for GB Security.
   Noriega was indicted in Florida last month on drug trafficking
charges and the Reagan administration is pressing for his
resignation.
</TEXT>
