<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Kentucky 1stLd-Writethru a0658 03-08 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Kentucky, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0658,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gore, Bush Win Kentucky</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Gore, Bush declared winners. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK R. CHELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. and Vice
President George Bush cashed in on endorsements from Kentucky
politicians to easily win the state's Democratic and Republican
primaries Tuesday.
   Gore, running in his neighboring state, defeated Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis in the Democratic race by 45,593 votes or 39
percent to Dukakis' 26,902 votes or 23 percent, with 1,151 of 3,243
precincts or 35 percent reporting.
   Jesse Jackson was third with 20,509 votes or 18 percent;
Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 10,628 votes or 9 percent;
former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 4,363 votes or 4 percent; and
Illinois Sen. Paul Simon finished with 2,734 votes or 2 percent.
   In the Republican primary, with 1,384 of 3,237 precincts or 43
percent reporting, Bush soundly defeated Kansas Sen. Bob Dole by
36,887 votes or 58 percent to Dole's 14,731 votes or 23 percent.
   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson was next with 7,287
votes or 11 percent; New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 2,278 votes or 4
percent; and former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont finished with 339
votes or 1 percent.
   At stake were 55 Democratic and 38 GOP delegates.
   Gore won a battle with Dukakis for the support of Gov. Wallace
Wilkinson, who decided to go with a neighboring son of the South.
   ``He's one of us,'' Wilkinson said.
   But Dukakis wasn't giving up. He began running TV ads on Friday
and paid his first visit of the year to the state _ in Louisville
on Sunday _ wooing undecided voters.
   Bush had the support of Sen. Mitch McConnell, a national
campaign co-chairman, and the two GOP representatives who endorsed.
   In a late February poll conducted by the Louisville
Courier-Journal, Gore was the choice of 28 percent of Democrats
while Dukakis was the favorite of 20 percent. Hart was third with
10 percent while Gephardt, Jackson and Simon were all in single
digits. Undecided voters accounted for 23 percent.
   The poll found Bush preferred by 51 percent of likely GOP
voters. Dole was the choice of 28 percent. Undecided voters made up
the third largest segment at 11 percent. Robertson and Kemp split
the rest.
</TEXT>
