<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MillionaireGunman 1stLd-Writethru a0697 03-08 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Millionaire Gunman, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0697,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banker Pleads Guilty in Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT age to 53, sted 43, and ADDS 5 grafs
with Cotugno's version of incident, civil suit.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired investment banker Arthur K.
Salomon admitted Tuesday that he shot a college student after a
traffic dispute, saying he was afraid the young man was going to
attack him.
   Salomon, 53, pleaded guilty to first-degree assault. He had been
indicted on a charge of attempted murder.
   In return for the plea, state Supreme Court Justice Nicholas
Colabella indicated he would sentence Salomon to two to six years
in prison on April 27. Salomon, grandson of one of the founders of
the Salomon Brothers investment firm, could have received a maximum
of five to 15 years in prison.
   Salomon read a brief statement describing what happened June 19
when he shot Gianluca Cotugno, 19, of Larchmont off the Hutchinson
River Parkway in Scarsdale, north of New York City.
   Cotugno, who was hospitalized several weeks with a gunshot wound
to the stomach, was not in court.
   Salomon said he was heading south on the parkway from his Pound
Ridge home to his Manhattan apartment when a white Honda began to
tailgate him. The driver flashed his lights and ``attempted to run
my car off the road,'' Salomon said.
   Salomon pulled off at an exit, and stopped his 1977
Mercedes-Benz. The Honda also pulled off, Salomon said, and the
driver got out of the car.
   ``A tall, slim white male was moving rapidly toward my car,
waving his arms in a threatening manner and shouting,'' Salomon
said. ``I believed at that time that this individual was going to
attack me.''
   The other man was unarmed, Salomon said.
   Salomon said he reached for a loaded .38-caliber Colt revolver
in the car.
   By then, the man was ``standing adjacent to the passenger door
of my car. He was leaning over my car, making threatening motions
with his hands. I believe he was going to attack me,'' Salomon
said. ``Knowing that the revolver was loaded, I discharged it in
the direction of the individual.''
   Salomon said that when he realized he had hit the man, ``I
panicked and drove away.''
   Salomon, who had licenses for the Colt and another gun,
surrendered to authorities several hours later.
   Cotugno told authorities that Salomon was traveling slowly in
the left lane and, despite his flashing his lights, Salomon would
not move to the right lane so that he could pass.
   Salomon pulled over, waving for Cotugno to do the same, Cotugno
said.
   Cotugno said that when he approached Salomon's car, he spotted
the gun and told Salomon he was going to get the car's license
plate and call police. The shooting occurred after Cotugno had
started to walk back to his car.
   A $15 million civil suit Cotungo filed against Salomon is
pending.
</TEXT>
