<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1959EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Divine     03-08 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Divine,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director John Waters Calls Actor `Kind and Gentle Man'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divine, the bizarre female impersonator who
starred in such films as ``Pink Flamingos'' and ``Hairspray,'' was
remembered Tuesday by John Waters, director of the two movies, as
``a kind and gentle man.''
   ``Divine is as irreplaceable to me as a member of my own
family,'' Waters said, reading haltingly from a statment at a
Baltimore hotel. ``I'll miss him incredibly.''
   ``Not only did I respect him as the best actor I've ever worked
with, I knew him personally as a kind and gentle man,'' Waters said.
   The 42-year-old actor, whose real name was Harris Glenn
Milstead, was found dead in his bed Monday at the Hollywood Regency
Plaza Hotel. Waters said he was told Divine was found under the
covers ``with a smile on his face.''
   A preliminary coroner's autopsy failed to pinpoint a cause of
death, and a microscopic examination of tissue samples was ordered.
Preliminary tests showed no signs of trauma or any other factor
that would have contributed to the actor's death, Los Angeles
County coroner's spokesman Steve Stewart said Tuesday.
   Publicist John West of PMK said the actor apparently died of
asphyxiation during the night. He was in town to appear in an
episode of ``Married ... With Children,'' a Fox Television Network
series.
   Divine normally slept upright, propped up because of his weight,
said Peter Haas, a publicist for ``Hairspray.''
   Divine had a long-term weight problem but was found at a medical
checkup Friday to be otherwise in excellent health, his manager,
Bernard Jay, said Tuesday.
   ``He was not on drugs at all, and he never drank alcohol,'' Jay
said. ``I suppose it all comes down to his weight. He was
constantly trying to diet, but as soon as he'd take the pounds off,
they'd come right back on again.''
   Waters was one of the actor's few friends in school in
Lutherville, a Baltimore suburb, where Milstead said he grew up fat
and taunted by classmates.
   Waters' obsession with trashy movies nearly matched Milstead's
fantasies of celebrity, and Waters began casting his friend in
bizarre roles.
   The most famous would be the cult film classics ``Pink
Flamingos,'' ``Lust in the Dust,'' ``Polyester'' and ``Female
Trouble.''
   He had been pleased over his role in ``Hairspray'' as Edna
Turnblad, the fat mother of a fat teen-age girl.
   ``He'd call me in the middle of the night to read me some
newspaper interview and say, `Isn't it wonderful! They called me
Divine, the 300-pound actor, not Divine, the 300-pound
transvestite,''' Jay said.
   As Divine, he wore garish makeup and was loud and foul-mouthed.
``She's her own person and a lot of people like that,'' he once
said. ``The camp element is something out of the ordinary, this big
man playing a sexy woman.''
   Milstead played a non-transvestite role, that of a Sydney
Greenstreet-type character, in the 1985 film ``Trouble In Mind.''
   Besides film roles, Milstead used the Divine persona in a
nightclub act.
   Waters said that the last time he had spoken to Divine was two
days ago and that he had last seen him at the premiere of
``Hairspray'' in New York City.
   In their last conversations, Waters said, ``he was just so
happy. He said `Can you believe we came this far?'''
</TEXT>
