<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-JapanConstruction     03-08 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Construction,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Fail on US Participation in Japanese Contruction Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press Writer=
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ A week of talks between U.S. and Japanese
officials over participation by U.S. firms in billions of dollars
worth of Japanese building projects ended in failure Tuesday.
   And, a U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
President Reagan under the law could retaliate against Japan for
what are considered unfair trade practices.
   ``That is one of the options,'' the official said, adding that
the Reagan administration will decide probably by the end of next
week what its next step will be.
   The official said the U.S. side had exhausted its capacity to
resolve the issues and was not ready to go on talking, given the
differences between the two sides.
   He said the Japanese, who had offered measures to allow U.S.
construction firms to gain experience in Japan on seven projects,
wanted discussions to continue.
   The U.S. delegation was led by J. Michael Farren, deputy
undersecretary of Commerce for international trade. The Japanese
group was headed by Peter Sato, director general of economic
affairs in the Japanese Foreign Ministry.
   Farren has criticized previous Japanese proposals as offering
American companies only limited experience, not enough to enable
them to take part in normal Japanese bidding on public projects.
   The U.S. official, as an example, cited the extension of the
Tokyo International Airport at Haneda, where he said the only
opportunity offered to Americans would be in ``compacting earth and
laying concrete,'' and in building a monorail.
   The Americans would not be competitive in the labor-intensive
construction, he added. He said that under the Japanese proposals
they would not be allowed to participate in the design or
engineering, nor in the building of a $900 million airport terminal.
   The official said the U.S. delegation also wanted the
arrangements on participation by U.S. construction firms written
into a formal agreement, while the Japanese did not want to be
bound and sought only a joint statement that unspecified
arrangements were satisfactory.
</TEXT>
