<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Protests     03-08 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Protests,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scores Detained in Women's Day Demonstrations in Chile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas and water cannons on
Tuesday to scatter hundreds of demonstrators who turned an
International Women's Day march into a protest against the military
government.
   At dusk, police reported around 100 demonstrators detained, but
reporters in Santiago and other witnesses called that figure too
low.
   Demonstrators were also arrested in similar protests in
Valparaiso, 75 miles northwest of Santiago on the Pacific coast.
   The street protests were the first this year against the
14-year-old regime of Gen. Augusto Pinochet.
   Helmeted riot police in downtown Santiago fought running battles
for hours with protesters, most of them women.
   Scattered repeatedly by police, the demonstrators would quickly
regroup at a different intersection and renew their chanting of
anti-government slogans.
   Police used water cannons to put out flaming barricades erected
by protesters.
   Reporters saw a public bus set afire with gasoline bombs thrown
by three people. The bus was destroyed, but all passengers fled
without injury.
   The United Nations declared March 8 as International Women's
Day, but Chile's government said leftist groups turned the day into
a ``Marxist event.''
   Tuesday's march was called by women's organizations and
dissident groups.
</TEXT>
