<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 2032EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Press     03-08 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Press,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Rejects Newspaper's Challenge of Censorship Powers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court panel on
Tuesday rejected a challenge to censorship powers that allow a
Cabinet minister to close newspapers for publishing material he
considered objectionable.
   Earlier, police detained nine journalists during an
anti-apartheid demonstration by about 100 black women outside the
Chamber of Mines building.
   Police arrived about 10 minutes after the peaceful protest
began. The crowd dispersed and police began seizing journalists,
including crew members of CBS and London-based World Television
News.
   World Television soundman Prince Msuthu said police punched him.
   Police spokesman Col. Frans Malherbe said the nine were were
taken to police headquarters but were released without charge.
   Malherbe said emergency rules that have been in effect for
nearly two years prohibit members of the media from being at the
scene of unrest.
   The protesters, members of the Federation of Transvaal Women,
called on mining companies to oppose new government restrictions on
anti-apartheid organizations. The women's federation is an
affiliate of the United Democratic Front, one of 18 organizations
covered by the ban issued Feb. 24.
   Apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the
26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs and the 5
million whites control the economy and maintain separate services.
   The censorship ruling by the Rand Supreme Court could lead to
the closing of the weekly New Nation, a newspaper published for
black readers by the South African Catholic Bishops Conference.
   During the hearing, Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha said he
had been ready to shut down the New Nation in January. He said the
paper published material that he felt promoted outlawed
organizations, fanned revolt and incited hostility toward security
forces.
   Under a decree issued in August by President P.W. Botha, the
home affairs minister can install censors at newspapers or shut
down the publications.
   In its challenge, the New Nation said the decree was
unenforceable because editors could not anticipate what the
minister might consider objectionable.
   Gabu Tugwana, acting New Nation editor, said in a telephone
interview, ``The paper we are putting out for tomorrow could be the
one before the last issue.'' He said the publishers intended to
appeal the decision.
   New Nation editor Zwelakhe Sisulu has been in detention without
charge for more than a year.
   Under the emergency decrees, the home minister is not required
to give detailed reasons for his objections to published material.
   The head of the three-judge panel said in the ruling the
president was ``legally correct'' to give the minister such power.
</TEXT>
