<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireDeaths     03-08 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Deaths,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Infant's Death Brings Memphis Fire Toll To Seven Small Children
This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of a 3-month-old boy in a home
fire brought to seven the number of small children killed in
residential fires this year, authorities said.
   N.E. Wallace, an assistant city fire marshal, said the latest
victim, Christopher Bolden, died Monday in a fire apparently caused
by an electrical short circuit.
   The boy's 6-month-old cousin, Jessica Baker, suffered smoke
inhalation and was listed in critical condition Tuesday in Le
Bonheur Children's Medical Center.
   Wallace said three children from 1 to 3 years old died in
residential fires in Memphis last year. So far this year, seven
youngsters age 6 or less have died.
   When the latest fire broke out, Christopher was one of five
children being cared for at a house by one of his aunts. The woman
managed to escape from the house with three of the children, ages
21 months to 4 years, and firefighters saved Jessica.
   ``The family was out front screaming that there were kids
inside,'' said firefighter Ron Chastain. ``There was an awful lot
of smoke, and as soon as we got the door open, a lot of fire shot
out.''
</TEXT>
