<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP-FarRight     03-08 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP-Far Right,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lobby: Robertson's Poor Showing Means Split In `Traditional Value
Community'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson's poor showing in the Super
Tuesday voting in the South shows that ``the traditional value
community has been totally fractured,'' the chairman of Christian
Voice said Tuesday night.
   ``Frankly, I'm surprised that he did not do better,'' said
Robert Grant, who leads the largest conservative evangelical lobby
in the country.
   In early returns, Robertson did not come in better than third in
any state, behind Vice President George Bush and Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas. He bested another conservative, Rep. Jack Kemp of New York,
however.
   Grant said the opinion-makers on the far right of the Republican
Party must now try to come to some consensus on who they will back.
   ``Only as this community hangs together does it have any real
impact,'' Grant said. ``The traditional value community has been
totally fractured with Kemp taking a piece, Robertson taking the
charismatics to a degree and a large part going to Dole and Bush.''
   He said the vice president's showing in the South ``is an
indication that he may be a viable candidate for the Bible
Belt-type vote, but he is going to have to work for it.''
   However, said Grant, ``The image or perception conveyed by the
Bush campaign has been to savage and to turn away conservative
Christian activities. This has not necessarily been the sentiment
of the vice president but it has been the impression conveyed
within his campaign and among many established Republican types.
   ``If Bush wishes to woo that vote, he has a good shot at it.''
</TEXT>
