<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ThrillKilling     03-08 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thrill Killing,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Ends in Teen Killing Case; Closing Arguments Expected</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ritalin Irony, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who admitted plotting the fatal
beating of a classmate in 1986 has not suffered from severe
psychosis or hallucinations despite a history of behavioral
problems, medical experts said Tuesday.
   The Norfolk Superior Court jury is expected to hear closing
arguments then begin deliberations Wednesday, the seventh day of
the trial.
   Rod Matthews, 15, of Canton is being tried as an adult for
murder in the Nov. 20, 1986, slaying of 14-year-old Shaun
Ouillette, also of Canton, who allegedly was lured to a wooded area
by Matthews and beaten with a baseball bat.
   Matthews, who pleaded innocent by reason of insanity, said he
had plotted the slaying for a month to experience what killing
someone was like, according to testimony from two classmates to
whom Matthews showed the body.
   Dr. Michael Annunziata, a court-appointed psychiatrist, told a
Norfolk Superior Court jury that Matthews suffered from a ``conduct
disorder'' but that he had not experienced classic symptoms of
psychosis, such as hallucinations.
   Matthews, said Annunziata, had ``substantial capacity to conform
his conduct to the requirement of law.''
   Annuziata on Tuesday said the methodical planning of the killing
did not indicate psychotic tendencies but suggested Matthews was
``playing by different rules.''
   Earlier, Dr. Marcel Kinsbourne, director of behavioral neurology
at the Eunice Shriver Center in Waltham, testified that standard
doses of Ritalin, a drug Matthews had been taking, should not
trigger violent behavior.
   Ritalin, a stimulant primarily used to control hyperactivity in
children, has been a key aspect of the case.
   The defense had contended that Matthews was a mentally ill youth
from a troubled home and that his problems were exacerbated by the
use of Ritalin.
   Dr. Bernard Yudowitz of Belmont's McLean Hospital said on Monday
that Ritalin may have made it harder for Matthews to control his
behavior.
</TEXT>
