<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Tennessee, 2nd Ld _ Writethru,a0869,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gore, Bush Win Tennessee</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Bush winning.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush cruised to an
easy victory in Tuesday's presidential primary, while favorite son
Albert Gore Jr. blasted past other Democrats to win his home state.
   In the Republican race, with 195 of 2,391 precincts or 8 percent
reporting: Bush had 10,747 votes or 61 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole had 3,600 votes or 20 percent; former TV evangelist Pat
Robertson had 2,121 votes or 12 percent; and New York Rep. Jack
Kemp had 894 votes or 5 percent.
   In the Democratic race, with 202 of 2,391 precincts or 8 percent
reporting: Gore had 34,449 votes or 76 percent; Jesse Jackson had
7,345 votes or 16 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had
1,537 votes or 3 percent; and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had
761 votes or 2 percent.
   Gephardt was an early campaigner in Tennessee, but since Gore
announced his candidacy in June, Jackson has been the only other
Democrat to visit the state.
   Gov. Ned McWherter, Gore's Southern campaign chairman, conceded
that Jackson was supported by most blacks, who constitute about 18
percent of the state's voters.
   Dole and Robertson targeted Bush as the man to beat in
Tennessee. Robertson was in the state three times since Jan. 1 and
has been represented by his wife twice. Dole, who visited the state
six times since last year, spoke in Knoxville on March 1.
   Robertson and Bush visited upper East Tennessee, Republican
territory, in the 10 days before the election. Kemp was in
Knoxville on Sunday, where he said he would reassess his future in
the race after Tuesday.
</TEXT>
