<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Romp In Home States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Material below dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis and Vice President George
Bush romped to Super Tuesday victories in their home state of
Massachusetts, a delegate-rich field that was virtually abandoned
as the candidates rushed south.
   In the Democratic race, with 50 of 2,140 precincts or 2 percent
reporting, Dukakis had 6,594 votes or 60 percent; Jesse Jackson had
2,567 votes or 23 percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 776
votes or 7 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had 332 votes or
3 percent; Illinois Sen. Paul Simon had 277 votes or 3 percent.
   On the Republican side, with 49 of 2,140 precincts or 2 percent
reporting, Bush had 1,690 votes or 57 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob Dole
had 789 votes or 27 percent; New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 200 votes
or 7 percent; and Pat Robertson had 148 votes or 5 percent.
   Dukakis, the popular three-term governor of this liberal state,
was a prohibitive favorite in the Democratic primary, where 98
delegates were at stake, the party's third-biggest prize of the day.
   In the Republican primary, 52 delegates were at stake, the
fourth-biggest batch on Super Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush carried Massachusetts in the 1980 GOP primary _ over Ronald
Reagan _ and enjoys the support of many mainstream Republicans.
Bush, who held a rally at historic Faneuil Hall last week, is the
only Republican candidate to visit the state since the New
Hampshire primary, although Dole has sent his wife, Elizabeth, for
two campaign stops.
   In recent days, the Bush and Dole camps dueled with
endorsements. Bush was backed by former U.S. Attorney General
Elliot Richardson, Dole by former Sen. Edward Brooke.
</TEXT>
