<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Students 1stLd-Writethru a0640 03-08 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Students, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0640,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Clash With Police To Demand Academic Freedom</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with police breaking up Warsaw march</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police swinging clubs dispersed hundreds
of Warsaw University students who marched for more academic freedom
on Tuesday, the anniversary of 1968 student protests.
   In the southern city of Krakow earlier Tuesday, riot police
clashed repeatedly with student demonstrators and briefly detained
70-100 people, an opposition spokesman said.
   Twenty years ago, March 8, 1968, police and Communist Party
activists brutally attacked Warsaw University students who were
protesting censorship and political repression.
   This year's protests reflected a renewed campaign by student
activists for legalization of the Independent Students Union, or
NZS. It was outlawed after the independent labor federation
Solidarity was suppressed with the declaratrion of martial law in
December 1981.
   About 500 students chanting ``Register NZS!'' and
``Solidarity!'' and carrying banners began marching after an
evening Mass attended by about 2,000 people at St. Anne's, a Roman
Catholic church near Warsaw University.
   Riot police blocked the street 100 yards from the church,
keeping demonstrators away from a monument to Adam Mickiewicz, the
19th century Polish national poet.
   An NZS leader asked police to allow people to lay flowers at the
monument. After demonstrators refused an offer to let a
three-person delegation approach the monument, police charged the
crowd, flailing with clubs. Students fled.
   Hundreds of people lining the sidewalk chanted ``Gestapo!
Gestapo!'' Police pushed several students and at least one
middle-aged woman into vans, but how many people were detained
could not be determined.
   At Krakow's Jagiellonian University, about 700 students tried to
march to the main square in the city's Old Town and were blocked by
riot police, said Zygmunt Lenyk, a Krakow opposition activist.
   Quoting accounts from witnesses, he said police attacked the
crowd with clubs but about 50 demonstrators pushed through police
lines to the square, where they were detained.
   Lenyk said most of the students returned to campus and tried
twice more to march to the square, about 500 yards away, but police
attacked each time.
   Students erected a street barricade with park benches and
garbage cans but police vehicles drove through it, he reported.
   About 70 to 100 people were detained but police began releasing
them by early afternoon, he said. Lenyk reported at least three
people severely beaten by police.
   In 1968, police and party activists went onto the Warsaw
University campus to beat and arrest protesters, many of whom were
expelled, and a purge of reform-oriented intellectuals and Jews
followed. Last week, the Communist Party said the purge was
excessive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
