<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan-PLO     03-08 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-PLO,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Hussein Invites Arafat for Talks on U.S. Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein has invited Yasser Arafat,
chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, to Amman to
discuss the latest U.S. proposals on Middle East peace, a
government official said Tuesday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
invitation ``comes within a framework of a United Arab stand''
reached at the Arab summit in Amman last year.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz explained the proposals on
trips to the region before and after last week's NATO summit in
Brussels.
   In Tunis, the Central Committee of Arafat's Fatah guerrilla
group said Tuesday the Shultz plan was ``nothing but a desperate
attempt aimed at reviving the (1982) Reagan initiative and imposing
it on the region.''
   CBS News, in a report from Paris, said, ``CBS News has learned
that the American ambassador to the United Nations, Vernon Walters,
met secretly with a top-ranking PLO leader in Tunisia last weekend.
This according to senior PLO officials who say the meeting took
place at a private home at a seaside resort near Tunis.''
   ``PLO sources say it probably had to do with how Palestinians
can participate in any future peace talks,'' the report said, and
added Walters denied he had met with the PLO. ``In a statement read
by a spokesman, Walters said he had no authorization to meet with
them and had not done so,'' CBS News said.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
reports that Walters met with PLO representatives were ``absolutely
untrue.''
   The U.S proposals include limited self-rule for the 1.5 million
Palestinians living in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip and an international peace conference that could include the
five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, Israel,
Jordan, Syria and Palestinians, but not the PLO.
   Hussein and Arafat decided in 1985 to take a joint approach to
peace with Israel, but Hussein called it off in February 1986,
accusing Arafat of not keeping his promises.
   On Monday, Jordan's minister of information welcomed the U.S.
peace effort and said the Shultz proposals were being ``studied
thouroughly with Arab states.''
   ``We welcome the American moves, and we believe that the
American re-engagement in the peace process is positive,'' Hani
Khasawneh told reporters.
</TEXT>
