<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia     03-08 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Take Over Petroleum Plants in Response to Crippling Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops took over plants of the state
petroleum company Tuesday and arrested labor leaders in response to
a strike that threatens to paralyze transportation and the
industrial sector.
   The government began rationing gasoline and motorists waited
hours in line. Many buses and taxis in major cities stayed off the
streets for lack of gasoline, tranport unions said.
   Police in Santa Cruz and La Paz rounded up leaders of the
Petroleum Workers Union. The government declared the strike illegal
and said there would be more arrests if the walkout continues.
   The conservative government decided to take over petroleum
plants and gasoline distributorships after the petroleum workers
union rejected a 30 percent wage increase conditioned on their not
striking for a year.
   The Santa Cruz refinery, 350 miles east of La Paz, was
surrounded by army units after workers turned off the plant's
machinery following the breakdown of negotiations with the
government.
   The plant produces 70 percent of the gasoline and natural gas
used domestically. It also is responsible for much of the natural
gas exported to Argentina, the country's principal source of export
earnings.
   Saul Soliz, leader of the Petroleum Workers Union, said the
government's linking of a wage increase to a promise of no strikes
is ``a maneuver to divide the labor movement against the interests
of workers.''
   The union accused the government of planning to finance the 30
percent wage increase with the firing of 1,500 workers. Minister of
Energy Fernando Illanes denied the charge. The government-owned
petroleum company employs 7,000 workers.
   The Ministry of Information said the military intervened to
prevent the destruction of equipment and guarantee a supply of fuel.
   Many factories in La Paz and other cities said they had enough
fuel for only two more days and were cutting back on production.
   ``The government will not negotiate under pressure, more so
since 11 out of 21 unions agreed to the wage increase,'' said
Illanes.
</TEXT>
