<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP-Republicans 4thLd-Writethrua0857   03-08 0947</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP-Republicans, 4th Ld-Writethru a0857,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Overwhelms Dole in Dixie, Dole Braced to Absorb Shock</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 15 grafs new to update; picks up 10th graf pvs, Robertson
seemed</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush marched across the South on Tuesday,
overwhelming Sen. Bob Dole as he headed for a near-sweep in Super
Tuesday voting. Dole braced to absorb the shock and the campaigns
of the two remaining Republican presidential contenders were dealt
shattering blows.
   Tuesday's voting seemed likely to bury the struggling campaigns
of Rep. Jack Kemp and Pat Robertson, who had claimed the South as
his base of support.
   Bush won decisive victories throughout the region, capturing
more than 50 percent of the vote in many states, including
delegate-rich Florida.
   He also scored big wins in Tennessee, Kentucky, Georgia,
Alabama, Virginia, Mississippi, North Carolina and Massachusetts.
   Dole had pinned his Southern hopes on North Carolina, the home
state of his wife, Elizabeth..
   ABC and NBC also projected the vice president as winning Texas
and Maryland.
   Dole had hoped to pull out a win in North Carolina, the home
state of his wife, Elizabeth.
   However, early returns showed the Senate minority leader to be
ahead in only one state _ Missouri, which borders his home state of
Kansas.
   At stake Tuesday were 712 delegates to the Republican National
Convention. Virginia was alone among the 17 GOP contests holding a
``beauty contest'' that awards no delegates.
   Bush's national campaign chairman, Lee Atwater, predicted that
Bush would pick up more than 600 of those delegates _ a gain that
would give him a near-unassailable lead toward winning the GOP
presidential nomination.
   ``I would certainly hate to be in Sen. Dole's shoes after
tonight and especially if he loses in Illinois,'' Atwater said.
Battered in Tuesday's voting, Dole turned his sights to next week's
Illinois primary in hopes of staging a comeback in Midwestern and
Western states.
   Dole said earlier in Springfield, Ill., ``If we take a little
bath today, I am going to start my road to recovery in Illinois
just like I did 40 years ago.''
   Dole was referring to his recovery in an Illinois hospital from
wounds suffered during World War II.
   Kemp and Robertson were far outdistanced by Bush and Dole. Kemp
trailed Robertson in most Southern states, and was expected to drop
out by week's end. For Robertson, the voting throughout the South
was a replay of his third place finish in Saturday's South Carolina
primary, when he could muster no more than about 20 percent of the
vote.
   Robertson seemed less likely to abandon his dogged pursuit of
the presidency at this time. But the former television evangelist
conceded in advance that ``it would take some miracle'' for him to
beat Bush.
   Bush voted in Houston, and then told reporters, ``If we exceed
our expectations or live up to them, I think we'll be in good
shape.''
   Top campaign aides had said earlier that they thought Bush stood
a good chance of winning at least 12 or 13 states.
   Polls showed the vice president ahead in 16 of the 17 contests,
including those in delegate-rich Texas and Florida. His chief
rival, Dole, was ahead only in Missouri.
   ``It's going to be a little tougher as we go along, but I've
been in tough fights before,'' Dole acknowledged at a morning news
conference in Kansas City, Mo.
   He then traveled to Illinois and immediately challenged Bush to
a series of debates _ ``one-on-one, without moderator'' _ in that
state, which holds its primary next Tuesday.
   Bush's chief spokesman, Pete Teeley, scoffed at the idea when
asked about it in Texas.
   ``If Bob Dole was so serious about debating, he would have shown
up for the (Feb. 19) Dallas Morning News debate,'' Teeley said.
``We have a strategy which has been highly successful and we plan
to pursue it, and that doesn't include having one-on-one debates
with Bob Dole.''
   Dole campaign strategists had conceded in advance that Super
Tuesday would likely belong to the vice president.
   In fact, the question appeared to be not whether Bush would
emerge the victor, but by what kind of margin _ and whether the
drubbing would be fatal to Dole, who finished first in the Iowa
caucuses but lost strength in the ensuing contests.
   The Dole campaign had sought to keep Bush from picking up more
than 500 delegates Tuesday.
   Dole, though, was looking ahead to Illinois, where he promised
to ``issue a challenge or two'' to Bush.
   The Senate majority leader, a 1984 presidential contender and
GOP vice presidential candidate in 1976, was reportedly spending
$500,000 on television advertising in the state.
   A defeat there could all but end Dole's presidential efforts and
a strong showing for the Kanasan was by no means assured. Bush is
backed by Illinois Gov. James Thompson and 93 of the state's 102
Republican county chairmen.
   Kemp, dead last in the South Carolina primary last weekend, had
not been expected to see that flagging effort revived in Tuesday's
voting. Aides said the New York lawmaker and former pro-football
star would reassess his race later in the week. He was expected to
pull out.
   Robertson's chances as a serious contender seemed likely to be
all but ended if his losses in Super Tuesday states were as
decisive as his third-place finish in South Carolina, where he won
only 19 percent of the vote.
   Robertson's candidacy came to life with his strong second-place
finish the Iowa caucuses on Feb. 8. But in the primaries that
followed, his strength ebbed.
   Even so, he told a North Carolinia campaign audience as recently
as Monday: ``We will do very well in the South.''
</TEXT>
