<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 2142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OfficialEnglish     03-08 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Official English,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>English-Only Petitioners Say Signiture Drive Tops Minimum Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a constitutional amendment to make
English the state's official language gathered about 260,000 new
signatures Tuesday, easily topping the number required to get on
the November ballot, a spokeswoman said.
   ``We are feeling very good,'' said Patricia Fulton, spokeswoman
for the Florida English Campaign.
   Taking advantage of primary election day, volunteers stationed
near polling places throughout the state collected about 60,000
signatures of registered voters, and workers from a California
company collected nearly 200,000, Ms. Fulton said.
   The new signatures, added to the 236,000 already in hand, should
put the movement at well beyond the 342,939 needed for a
referendum. About 125,500 of the signatures already have been
verified.
   The signatures were obtained despite the efforts of the League
of United Latin American Citizens, which took out advertisements in
Hispanic newspapers around the state warning voters about the
proposed amendment and urging them to register so that they could
vote against it in the general election.
   ``We're accused of being racist or xenophobics, because people
think we are anti-immigrants,'' said Dr. Mark LaPorta, chairman on
the Florida English Campaign.
   ``Nothing could be farther from the truth. My father was an
immigrant,'' LaPorta said. He insisted the measure was designed to
spur immigrants to learn the language and the ways of the United
States.
   LULAC and other Hispanic groups oppose the Florida and U.S.
English campaigns because they believed they have racist elements.
   If enough signatures are verified, the proposed referendum would
be submitted to the state Supreme Court for review of its wording.
   The referendum would ask voters to designate English as the
official language, but would leave it up the state Legislature to
decide what, if any, government practices would be changed.
   Proponent of the referendum, for example, would like to see the
government increase funds for English-language education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
