<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DiplomatArrest     03-08 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diplomat Arrest,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Diplomat Says He Is Sorry About Hitting Protester</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African diplomat cited for
simple assault after his car struck a protester and a police
officer said Tuesday that he was sorry about the incident.
   South African Vice Consul Duke Kent Brown said during an
interview with radio station WJOY-WQCR that he did not expect the
group of anti-apartheid protesters to block his exit from a parking
lot near the radio station Monday.
   ``It's unfortunate that whole situation arose,'' he said.
   Brown was charged with simple assault, released on his own
recognizance and ordered to appear in court in April in connection
with the incident.
   The State Department said Brown had consular, rather than
diplomatic, immunity, meaning he was not automatically exempt from
prosecution. But he can claim immunity in court as an ``affirmative
defense'' on the grounds that the alleged acts were performed in
the exercise of his consular function.
   About 30 members of the Vermont Committee on Southern Africa had
gathered outside the station to protest Brown's participation in a
morning talk show, according to WJOY-WQCR news director Jim Condon.
   Brown said he had expected the protest to continue, but that ``I
would ignore them as I would leave.''
   Some of the protesters were on the hood of the car when it
accelerated, Condon said.
   Brown said he did not see the police officer, Todd Shepard, who
suffered bruises on his leg. ``I was very surprised to hear that a
policeman had been injured and I did apologize to him when I saw
him,'' Brown said.
   Brown said he was glad to hear that protester Laurie Larson of
Richmond was not badly injured. Larson suffered minor bruises.
</TEXT>
