<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Win</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Bush, Sarbanes, Blair winning, new
vote figures. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis ran away
with Maryland's Democratic presidential primary Tuesday, while Vice
President George Bush soundly defeated Kansas Sen. Bob Dole in the
Republican contest.
   Democratic Sen. Paul Sarbanes easily overcame two little-known
primary opponents in his bid for a third term. He will face Thomas
Blair, a millionaire newcomer to politics, who beat eight other
candidates for the Republican nomination.
   In the Democratic presidential race, with 643 of 1,574 precincts
or 41 percent reporting, Dukakis had 65,527 votes or 45 percent to
Jesse Jackson's 35,855 votes or 24 percent; Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. had 15,506 votes or 11 percent; and Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt had 12,024 votes or 8 percent.
   Former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart finished with 5,713 votes or 4
percent; and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon tallied 4,740 votes or 3
percent.
   In the Republican primary, Bush gathered 25,870 votes or 54
percent to Dole's 14,643 votes or 31 percent, with 426 of 1,574
precincts or 27 percent reporting.
   New York Rep. Jack Kemp and former TV evangelist Pat Robertson
was next with 3,260 votes or 7 percent, followed by New York Rep.
Jack Kemp with 2,861 votes or 6 percent.
   Bush won despite a late effort by Dole that included a day of
campaigning by the Kansas senator in what his staff considered one
of his better Super Tuesday states.
   At stake were 41 GOP delegates and 67 Democratic delegates.
   Sarbanes' opponents in the Democratic primary were A. Robert
Kaufman, 56, a socialist who wants to use the campaign as a
platform to express his concerns about the economy and social ills
in the United States, and B. Emerson Sweatt, 44, who says he has
masterminded federal drug control efforts since 1970, is owed $6
million by the federal government and claims to be the only man on
Earth with a ``valid legal right to subpoena the entire Congress to
testify in a civil suit against the government.''
   Blair, a Montgomery County millionaire who had never run for
office, was the pre-primary favorite.
   Maryland got scant attention from the presidential contenders
despite the switch to Super Tuesday from the traditional May
primary, which Democratic leaders hoped would help the state play a
bigger role in the nominating process.
</TEXT>
