<DOCNO> AP880308-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 2230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Iditarod     03-08 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iditarod,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Redington Leads In Iditarod Dog Sled Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROHN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Redington stole the lead of the
1,150-mile Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race on Tuesday as he and Herbie
Nayokpuk sailed past other mushers who had packed down a smooth,
fast trail for them.
   Redington, a Wasilla resident who is a founder of the
16-year-old race, and Nayokpuk, of Shishmaref, took their mandatory
24-hour layovers on Sunday. The race leaders passed them by, only
to get bogged down in freshly fallen snow as they crossed the
Alaska Range.
   The leading mushers then took their mandatory layovers at Rohn,
271 miles from the race's start in Anchorage. They watched
helplessly as Redington and Nayokpuk _ and less than two hours
later, Joe Garnie of Teller _ powered past them.
   ``I kind of have this feeling in the back of my mind that we're
going to see two Eskimos _ Garnie and Nayokpuk _ blazing across
this state,'' said Jerry Austin, one of the mushers taking a
layover at Rohn.
   Joe Runyan of Nenana was the first musher to leave Rohn, at
10:30 p.m. Monday. But he has not declared his 24-hour layover, and
so is behind Redington, who left Rohn at 7:20 a.m. Tuesday.
Nayokpuk left Rohn two minutes behind Redington. Garnie left at 9
a.m.
   Still at Rohn, in the order in which they arrived, were: Jan
Masek of Anchorage; Lavon Barve of Wasilla; defending champion
Susan Butcher of Manley; Jacques Philip of Thomery, France; Austin,
of St. Michael; Tim Moerlein of Kasilof; and, in 11th place,
two-time Iditarod champion Rick Swenson.
   From Rohn, the teams descend from the heights of the Alaska
Range into the timbered interior of the state for the longest
stretch between checkpoints in the race. Mushers must contend with
a bleak and treacherous area known as Farewell Burn before reaching
the next checkpoint, 93 miles away at Nikolai.
   The race is inspired by a 1925 dog sled relay that rushed
diphtheria serum to Nome during an outbreak of the disease. The top
20 mushers will split a purse of $150,000. The winner will get
$30,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
