<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Holds Off Dole; Gore Beats Jackson in North Carolina</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Gore declared Democratic
winner, results; Picks up 4th graf, `Eighty-two Democratic ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. edged Jesse
Jackson to win North Carolina's Democratic presidential primary
Tuesday, while Vice President George Bush held off a late surge by
Kansas Sen. Bob Dole in the Republican race.
   With 2,270 of 2,387 precincts or 95 percent reporting, Gore had
224,514 votes or 35 percent; Jackson had 212,833 votes or 33
percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 130,870 votes or 20
percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 37,978 votes or 6
percent; and former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 15,842 votes or 2
percent.
   In the Republican race, with 2,279 precincts or 95 percent
reporting: Bush had 117,846 votes or 45 percent; Dole had 104,093
votes or 40 percent; Pat Robertson had 25,356 votes or 10 percent;
and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 10,931 votes or 4 percent.
   Eighty-two Democratic delegates and 54 GOP delegates were up for
grabs in the third-largest of 14 Southern and border states holding
primaries.
   Dole strategists looked on North Carolina as one of their best
Southern prospects _ largely because the candidate's wife, former
transportation secretary Elizabeth Dole, is a native of Salisbury,
N.C.
   Polls published over the weekend showed Dole, who trailed by as
much as 15 percentage points two weeks ago, had pulled even with
Bush. A survey by the Charlotte Observer showed both with 38
percent.
   Kemp never developed a viable state campaign despite winning
support of the leaders of the National Congressional Club, Sen.
Jesse Helms' organization.
   Gore's appeal to Southern pride drew endorsements from Sen.
Terry Sanford, former Gov. Jim Hunt and dozens of state legislators
and local officeholders. Gore was in fourth place in a poll
published two weeks ago but appeared to be surging last week.
   Dukakis had the biggest paid North Carolina staff of any
candidate. Jackson announced his candidacy in Raleigh at the
convention of his ``Rainbow Coalition'' and reminded voters he had
attended college in the state.
</TEXT>
