<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Take R.I.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Bush, Dukakis winning.
Picks up 5th graf, `Bush came...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and
Vice President George Bush parlayed their neighborly ties into
overwhelming victories in Rhode Island's presidential primaries on
Tuesday.
   In the Democratic race, with 226 of 320 precincts or 71 percent
reporting, Dukakis crushed all challengers with 23,842 votes or 72
percent.
   Next came Jesse Jackson with 4,572 votes or 14 percent; Missouri
Rep. Richard Gephardt with 1,389 votes or 4 percent; Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. with 1,294 votes or 4 percent; Illinois Sen. Paul
Simon with 837 votes or 2 percent; and former Colorado Sen. Gary
Hart with 518 votes or 2 percent.
   In the Republican contest, with 223 of 320 precincts or 70
percent reporting, Bush tallied 6,449 votes or 65 percent; Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole had 2,222 votes or 22 percent; Pat Robertson finished
with 590 votes or 6 percent; and New York Rep. Jack Kemp was last
with 476 votes or 5 percent.
   At issue were 22 Democratic and 21 Republican delegates.
   Dukakis, the governor of a neighboring state, and Bush, a New
England native, had both worked the state long before their
presidential campaigns officially began, and each picked up
endorsements from his party's top local political figures.
   Bush came to the state in 1986 to help two fellow Republicans,
Gov. Edward D. DiPrete and Rep. Claudine Schneider, win re-election
that year, and DiPrete and Schneider repaid the favor with vocal
support this year.
   Gore got a burst of publicity and built a sizable organization
as the result of a January visit to the state. Jackson made
headlines in November, when he took a Scituate elementary school
teacher with him on a trip to the Persian Gulf to deliver
children's presents to U.S. servicemen there.
</TEXT>
