<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Corsica-Gunmen     03-08 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corsica-Gunmen,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Fire on Corsican Police Station, Killing One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AJACCIO, Corsica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen in a car shot at a police station
Tuesday, killing one officer, and to cover their escape threw a
grenade into a courtyard where children were playing, authorities
reported.
   They said two suspects were arrested shortly after the attack,
but the prisoners were not identified.
   No group asserted responsibility for the attack. It came less
than a day after guerrillas of the Corsican National Liberation
Front vowed to intensify actions to win independence from France
for the island in the Mediterranean 125 miles off the French
mainland.
   Security Minister Robert Pandraud, speaking at Lunel in southern
France, condemned the killing and said: ``We will fight against the
murderers without pity.''
   Police said three or four people in a car fired pistols at the
police station, fatally wounding an officer who was hit twice in
the stomach.
   As they fled, the killers threw a hand grenade into a courtyard
where several policemen's children were playing, and one of the
children was treated for shock, according to authorities.
   Police said the car used in the attack was found abandoned in a
ditch near the police station.
   One of four masked members of the National Liberation Front,
speaking to reporters Monday near the town of Bastiaa, said:
``There is no question of establishing a truce. We are going to
pursue and even intensify our actions.'' The group has claimed
responsibility for several assassinations, including the Sept. 13,
1983, shooting of a top government official for northern Corsica.
</TEXT>
