<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Wins Georgia; Jackson Beats Gore</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Jackson declared winner;
UPDATES results; Picks up 4th graf, `The Republicans ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson nudged Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
to win Georgia's Democratic presidential primary Tuesday, while
Vice President George Bush swamped his Republican rivals.
   With 2,002 of 2,571 precincts or 78 percent reporting, Jackson
had 174,003 votes or 39 percent; Gore had 149,180 votes or 34
percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had 62,987 votes or 14
percent; Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 31,828 votes or 7
percent; and former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had 13,116 votes or 3
percent.
   In the Republican race, with 1,922 precincts or 75 percent
reporting, Bush had 135,769 votes or 54 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole had 57,628 votes or 23 percent; Pat Robertson had 43,668 votes
or 17 percent; and New York Rep. Jack Kemp had 13,213 votes or 5
percent.
   The Republicans had 48 delegates up for grabs, with the
Democrats offering 77 delegates to their convention in Atlanta in
July.
   One of the state's best-known Democrats, former President Jimmy
Carter, withheld his endorsement. But another, Sen. Sam Nunn,
disclosed that he cast an absentee ballot for Gore because his
``views come closest to my own views as to the steps our nation
must take to meet our challenges at home and abroad.''
   GOP officials conceded Bush's association with Reagan and his
organization gave him the edge, but Robertson displayed
organizational strength in some precinct meetings last month.
   Jackson pulled off a surprise in 1984, winning southeastern
Georgia's 1st Congressional District, which includes Savannah.
Jackson's strong showing then was credited to a low Democratic
turnout combined with success in getting his supporters to the
polls.
   Dukakis made several other visits to the state, including stops
in Atlanta on the day he announced his candidacy and the day after
his victory in the New Hampshire primary.
   On Sunday, Dukakis stopped in for a half-hour visit with the
former president, who has met with all the other candidates at
various times.
   ``I think there's a great deal of compatibility between my basic
attitude towards government and that of Governor Dukakis,'' Carter
said afterwards.
   To encourage participation in the primary, state officials
included a referendum on broadening the eligibility for exemptions
for the elderly from some property and school taxes.
</TEXT>
