<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 2302EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SUP--Mississippi 2ndLd-Writethru   03-08 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Mississippi, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0901,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson, Bush Win Mississippi</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Jackson winning</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN EVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson elbowed past Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. to grab Tuesday's presidential primary in
Mississippi, while Vice President George Bush left the rest of the
Republican field in the dust.
   Democrats also waged a spirited primary battle for the Senate
seat John Stennis is leaving after 41 years.
   In the Democratic race, with 1,750 of 2,340 precincts or 75
percent reporting: Jackson had 118,652 votes or 44 percent; Gore
had 91,337 votes or 34 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
had 22,661 votes or 8 percent; and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt
had 14,996 votes or 6 percent. Former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart had
9,900 votes or 4 percent.
   In the Republican race, with 1,801 of 2,340 precincts or 77
percent reporting, Bush had won with 78,424 votes or 67 percent;
Dole had 19,547 votes or 17 percent; former TV evangelist Pat
Robertson had 15,115 votes or 13 percent; and New York Rep. Jack
Kemp had 4,289 votes or 4 percent.
   Forty Democratic delegates were at stake and 31 GOP delegates.
   In the Senate primary, Rep. Wayne Dowdy battled Secretary of
State Dick Molpus for the chance to run against Republican Rep.
Trent Lott in November for Stennis' seat. With 1,456 of 2,340
precincts or 62 percent reporting, Dowdy had 125,471 or 55 percent
to Molpus' 94,349 or 41 percent.
   Gilbert Founation, a Biloxi pipefitter, had 8,012 or 4 percent.
   Stennis, 86, announced last October that he would retire, making
this only the second time in 41 years that the state has had an
open U.S. Senate race.
   Dowdy, 44, who gained his congressional seat in a 1981 special
election, stressed his experience in Washington. Molpus, 38, touted
his record as director of federal-state programs under former Gov.
William Winter and his work as secretary of state since 1984.
   In recent weeks, Molpus made Dowdy's attendance record _ ranked
one of the five worst in the House according to Molpus _ a campaign
issue. Dowdy has countered that his voting mark is almost the same
as that of Stennis'.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
