<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SUP--Bush     03-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Bush,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Basks in Glow of Super Tuesday Wins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush jubilantly proclaimed
himself the man to beat in the Republican presidential sweepstakes,
saying his Super Tuesday performance ``exceeded my fondest
expectations.''
   Standing alongside his wife, Barbara, in a packed hotel ballroom
in his adopted home town, Bush said, ``As I said ... whoever wins
Super Tuesday convincingly is going to be the next president, and
I'll repeat it: I'm going to be the next president of the United
States.''
   ``This exceeded my fondest expectations,'' the vice president
said.
   ``You've given me and Barbara a big lift,'' Bush told
supporters. He and his wife had begun the day by casting their
ballots in the Texas GOP primary. Bush then went into seclusion in
the afternoon.
   Bush basked in the glow of his election triumphs only briefly,
giving a talk to supporters and greeting well-wishers in the
ballroom, which was decorated with Bush banners, the American flag
and red, white and blue balloons. His aides had said earlier Bush
would not accede to Sen. Bob Dole's demand that the vice president
appear in one-on-one, Lincoln-Douglas-style debates in Illinois.
   The vice president had awaited returns in a 21st floor penthouse
suite in the Westin Oaks Hotel, just a few blocks from the hotel
Houstonian, where he maintains a permanent residence. In
Washington, he lives in the official vice president's house.
   Bush brought to Houston two governors _ New Hampshire's John
Sununu and South Carolina's Carroll Campbell _ who had played
pivotal roles in his earlier victories in their states.
   Bush called his conquest of Dole and rivals Jack Kemp and Pat
Robertson ``a big, a major political victory. This is a national
victiory.''
   The vice president said he felt his performance Tuesday was a
reflection not of his campaign style but of his message ``to reduce
the deficit without raising taxes, to make progress toward peace
through strength, and making the United States strong ...''
   ``Reducing the threat of war is not a Republican issue and not a
Democratic issue,'' he said. ``It's a national issue.''
   Bush had no public activities scheduled for Wednesday and his
campaign aides planned to hold strategy sessins here.
   The vice president planned to fly to Chicago on Thursday for the
start of five days of intensive campaigning in the Illinois primary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
