<2ND_LINE>AM-SUP--Arkansas, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0652,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gore, Bush Win Arkansas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Gore, Bush winning.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. emerged
king of the Democratic hill in Tuesday's presidential primary in
Arkansas, while Vice President George Bush brushed aside Republican
rivals.
   With 1,311 of 2,762 precincts or 47 percent reporting, Gore had
79,145 votes or 37 percent; Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis had
40,285 votes or 19 percent; Jesse Jackson had 37,772 votes or 17
percent; and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt had 26,538 votes or 12
percent.
   In the GOP race, with 706 of 2,762 precincts or 26 percent
reporting, Bush had 14,527 votes or 48 percent; Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole had 7,913 votes or 26 percent; and former TV evangelist Pat
Robertson had 5,450 votes or 18 percent. New York Rep. Jack Kemp
had 1,387 votes or 5 percent.
   In the 1st Congressional District, veteran Democratic Rep. Bill
Alexander defeated political consultant Darrell Glascock, who went
to court to get on the ballot. Alexander had 41,552 votes, or 67
percent, to Glascock's 20,034, or 33 percent. No Republican sought
the office.
   Thirty-eight of Arkansas' 44 Democratic delegates and all 27 GOP
delegates were up for grabs.
   Turnout was expected to be low with the top state offices not on
the ballot because of a constitutional amendment that increased
terms from two years to four years beginning with the 1986
elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
