<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History 1stLd-Writethru Adv15 03-08 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, 1st Ld -Writethru, Adv15, b0128,0483</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, March 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 6th graf to read Andrew Jackson, sted Johnson.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Today in History</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, March 15, the 75th day of 1988. There are 291
days left in the year. This is ``Buzzard Day'' in Hinckley, Ohio.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On the Ides of March, 44 B.C., Roman Emperor Julius Caesar was
assassinated by a group of nobles that included Brutus and Cassius.
   On this date:
   In 1493, Christopher Columbus returned to Spain following his
first voyage to the New World.
   In 1767, the seventh President of the United States, Andrew
Jackson, was born in Waxhaw, South Carolina.
   In 1820, Maine became the 23rd state.
   In 1875, the Roman Catholic Archbishop of New York, John
McCloskey, was named the first American cardinal, by Pope Pius IX.
   In 1913, President Woodrow Wilson held the first open
presidential news conference.
   In 1919, the American Legion was founded, in Paris.
   In 1944, during World War II, the Italian town of Cassino was
devastated by Allied bombs.
   In 1956 the musical play ``My Fair Lady,'' starring Rex Harrison
and Julie Andrews, opened on Broadway.
   In 1964, Elizabeth Taylor married Richard Burton in Montreal. It
was her fifth marriage; his second.
   In 1965, before a joint session of Congress, President Lyndon B.
Johnson called for new legislation to guarantee every person's
right to vote.
   In 1966, rioting broke out in the Watts section of Los Angeles.
   In 1975, Greek shipping magnate Aristotle Onassis died near
Paris at the age of 69.
   In 1977, the House of Representatives began a 90-day test to
determine the feasibility of showing its sessions on television.
   Ten years ago: Israel routed Palestinian guerrillas from at
least seven strongholds in southern Lebanon. And Israel said it
would keep its troops in a ``security belt'' it seized along its
northern border until an agreement was reached to ensure that the
area could no longer be used for attacks against Israel.
   Five years ago: Israeli Foreign Minister Yitzhak Shamir said he
was leaving Washington more optimistic about prospects of an
agreement on withdrawing Israeli troops from Lebanon.
   One year ago: Peggy Say, the sister of kidnapped Associated
Press correspondent Terry Anderson, said President Reagan was being
``unjustly castigated'' for his arms-for-hostages deal.
   Today's Birthdays: Actor Macdonald Carey is 75. Former astronaut
Alan L. Bean is 56. Actor Judd Hirsch is 53. Beach Boy Mike Love is
47. Rhythm 'n' blues star Sylvester ``Sly Stone'' Stewart is 44.
Rock guitarist Ry Cooder is 41.
   Thought for Today: ``No man has a right in America to treat any
other man tolerantly, for tolerance is the assumption of
superiority.'' _ Wendell Willkie, American politician (1892-1944).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for Tuesday, March 15</NOTE>
