<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-08 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0529</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Born to Be Bad'' (Rounder) _ George Thorogood and the
Destroyers
   
   Albums are really superfluous for George Thorogood and the
Destroyers. This is a bar band, and a very good one, whose music is
best heard in a sweaty bar instead of a living room.
   But commerce calls. Thorogood must fulfill a record contract,
and ``Born to Be Bad'' is the latest product.
   If ``Born to Be Bad'' sounds a little familiar, it should. It
comes six years after ``Bad to the Bone.'' What's next _ ``Born to
Be Bone?'' Or ``Born in the Badlands?'' How about just plain
``Bad?'' Maybe that's too familiar.
   There aren't many things that distinguish ``Born to Be Bad''
from any other George Thorogood album since his 1977 debut. The
band's sound has become fuller over the years with the addition of
a saxophone player and a rhythm guitarist, but the content is
largely the same.
   ``Born to Be Bad'' has the obligatory Chuck Berry tune (``You
Can't Catch Me''), the traditional sinister guy song (title track),
the dance floor stomper (``Shake Your Money Maker''), paens to the
fairer sex (``I Really Like Girls'') and some blues to highlight
Thorogood's mean guitar.
   Familiarity doesn't have to breed contempt. The production is
crisp and the playing inspired, so most of side 1 genuinely cooks.
Side 2 flags considerably because of the repetition and one slow
blues song too many.
   Do yourself a favor. Save the money you may be inclined to spend
on ``Born to Be Bad'' until the Destroyers happen to come to town.
You shouldn't have to wait too long, although they may not
duplicate their 1981 feat of playing in 50 states in 50 days. Buy a
ticket to the concert, grab a dance partner, and have fun.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
   
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``If My Heart Had Windows'' (MCA) _ Patty Loveless
   
   Patty Loveless' new album consists of 10 songs, and the writing
credit is different on each. But Loveless' singing and the
production of Emory Gordy Jr. and Tony Brown make the album into a
cohesive set that's as country as grits.
   ``If My Heart Had Windows'' includes a honky-tonk waltz (the
title cut, by Dallas Frazier); country swing (Hank Williams' ``I
Can't Get You Off of My Mind''); and plenty of ballads.
   Loveless' full-throated alto really hits its stride on side 2,
climaxing on John and Johanna Hall's ``Fly Away,'' which lives up
to its name with a soaring chorus reminiscent of the Halls' defunct
pop group, Orleans.
   The arrangements, built around the solid rhythm section of
Leland Sklar and Eddie Bayers, include such nice touches as a steel
and fiddle playing in unison on the break of ``I Can't Get You Off
of My Mind.'' The material occasionally sags, but most of the album
contains strong and honest performances.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
