<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-08 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0565</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers have regained virtually all the
confidence they lost as a result of the October stock market crash,
according to a new survey.
   The Conference Board said Monday its Consumer Confidence Index
was 113.9 points in February, up from January's 109.9 points. The
index, which uses a 1985 base of 100, stood at 115.1 in October,
before the Oct. 19 stock collapse.
   In a separate report, the business research concern's Help
Wanted Index painted a somewhat less optimistic picture. The index,
which reflects the amount of help wanted ads in 51 major newspapers
across the nation, declined to 153 in January from 155 in December.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A significant number of American companies will
bolster hiring this spring, according to a leading temporary job
service.
   Manpower Inc. said Monday its Employment Outlook Survey
indicated 29 percent of respondents plan to raise employment rolls
in the April-June quarter, while 6 percent expect declines.
Sixty-two percent plan no change and 3 percent don't know, the
survey stated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $5.42 billion more in
installment debt than they paid off in January, the biggest monthly
increase in four months and the second strong month in a row, the
government says.
   The Federal Reserve said Monday that consumer credit grew at a
seasonally adjusted rate of 10.6 percent in January, following an
increase of $3.98 billion in December, which translated to an
annual rate of 7.9 percent.
   Growth in both months was greater than the 5.9 percent rate for
all of 1987, which represents a considerable slowdown compared with
recent years. The rate was 10.5 percent in 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover specialist Carl C. Icahn, Texaco Inc.'s
largest shareholder, has thrown his support behind the company's
plan to emerge from bankruptcy court protection.
   Icahn also promised Monday to drop his effort get himself and
four allies elected to Texaco's board of directors if its
management would agree to put the nation's third-largest oil
company up for sale for a minimum of $55 per share.
   Icahn is believed to have bought his 14.8 percent stake in
Texaco at prices averaging in the mid- to high-$30s per share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Corp. plans to sell its Montgomery Ward
division for $3.8 billion to an investor group led by the man
credited with restoring the 115-year-old department store chain to
profitability.
   A group headed by Montgomery Ward president Bernard Brennan will
acquire the nation's eighth-largest retailer in a leveraged buyout,
it was announced Monday.
   The proposal calls for Brennan's group to pay more than $1.5
billion in cash for the Chicago-based retailer and assume $2.3
billion of its debt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian tire manufacturer Pirelli has launched a
$1.86 billion offer for Firestone Tire & Rubber Co., urging
Firestone to scrap a plan to sell 75 percent of its tire-making
business to Bridgestone of Japan.
   Pirelli said Monday that its offer of $58 a share in cash for
Firestone's 32 million common shares outstanding was contingent on
Firestone's dropping the tentative agreement reached with
Bridgestone just three weeks ago.
   Chicago-based Firestone, which ranks third among U.S.
tiremakers, declined comment on the offer.
</TEXT>
