<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0502</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. is attempting to buy
Roper Corp., which only last month signed a merger agreement with
Whirlpool Corp.
   The GE offer, disclosed Monday, is $45 a share, or $423 million,
for Roper's 9.4 million common shares outstanding. Whirlpool had
bid $37.50 a share, or $352.5 million.
   The offer marks the first time GE, a major manufacturer with
interests in finance and broadcasting, has made an unsolicited
offer for a company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc. says its board of
directors will consider the latest hostile buyout offer from Black
& Decker Corp. and indicated it might sweeten its own alternative
plan a second time.
   American Standard, a plumbing and air conditioning maker, made
the announcement Monday after sweetening its defensive
recapitalization plan to $2.3 billion last week.
   Black & Decker is offering $73 a share for American Standard's
31 million common shares outstanding, or a total of about $2.26
billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lorimar-Telepictures Corp., a
television program supplier that has been losing money, says it is
discussing the possibility of being acquired by Warner
Communications Inc.
   Lorimar, the product of a merger two years ago, said Monday it
was approached by New York-based Warner and preliminary talks were
under way ``to explore the desirability of a business combination.''
   Lorimar said its board has made no decision as to whether such a
deal would be in the best interests of shareholders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has handed investors a
victory, placing a heavy burden of proof on companies sued for
denying they are holding merger negotiations after informal talks
have begun.
   By a 4-2 vote, the Supreme Court said Monday if companies
withhold important information affecting stock prices, it must be
presumed that investors who bought and sold the securities were
relying on that information.
   Separately, the high court agreed to hear a Reagan
administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to take a
bigger tax bite out of some corporate mergers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has cleared the way for the
regional Bell telephone companies to offer certain new computerized
information services, including voice storage and electronic mail.
   But U.S. District Judge Harold Greene, in a 66-page decision,
refused Monday to retreat from an earlier decision in which he said
phone companies could transmit information but could not generate
or manipulate the content of the information.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted aimlessly Monday in a quiet session
that saw the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slip 1.49 to
2,056.37.
   Bond prices moved modestly lower while interest rates were
little changed.
   The dollar drifted lower against most major currencies.
   Livestock and meat futures prices rose sharply, energy futures
fell, grains and soybeans were mostly higher and precious metals
retreated.
</TEXT>
