<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     03-08 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Futures Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures have retreated in response to
renewed fears of OPEC price discounting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled at $15.37 per
42-gallon barrel on Monday, down 22 cents from Friday's close of
$15.59.
   Among refined products, the April contract for wholesale No. 2
heating oil slid 0.13 cent to 43.41 cents. Wholesale unleaded
gasoline fell 0.57 cent to 43.94 cents a gallon.
   ``I think the catalyst behind today's decline is additional
rumors about OPEC individual nations offering discounts to
customers,'' said William Byers, an oil analyst with Bear, Stearns
& Co.
   Byers said the rumors of price discounting by members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries partly grew out of
reports that a delegation from the United Arab Emirates was
visiting Tokyo this week.
   ``The rumors are really all over the map,'' he said.
   Reports that OPEC might push for more production controls helped
boost prices on Friday.
</TEXT>
