<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-InterruptingMergers Bjt   03-08 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interrupting Mergers, Bjt,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bidders Trying To Undo Three Merger Agreements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Potential buyers from Italy, Canada and the
United States are setting their sights on several corporate
targets, apparently undaunted by merger agreements that the
managements of those targets have reached with other suitors.
   The moves by General Electric Co., Italy's Pirelli Societe
Generale SA and Canada's Campeau Corp. are somewhat reminiscent of
Texaco Inc.'s ill-fated purchase of Getty Oil Co. in 1984.
   Texaco has been in federal bankruptcy court since last April,
where it sought refuge rather than post a potentially ruinous bond
of more than $10 billion to appeal a Texas court's ruling that it
illegally had interfered in an agreement by Pennzoil Co. to buy
part of Getty.
   ``In the past, you fought tooth and nail up to when the company
accepted a bid, and once a company accepted a bid it was on to the
next game,'' said Daniel Schwartz, managing director of Ulmer
Brothers Inc., a merchant banking firm that specializes in mergers
and acquisitions.
   ``But clearly that doesn't seem to be the rule anymore,'' he
said.
   GE and Pirelli announced their offers Monday, while Campeau took
action last week.
   The new bidders feel they are on solid legal ground. They all
are appealing directly to shareholders of the target companies
instead of asking the companies' directors to back out of any
agreements.
   Texaco got in trouble because Getty was privately-owned, so for
Texaco to take it over it had to get the Getty directors to back
out of their deal with Pennzoil. Texaco argues that Getty's deal
with Pennzoil was not legally binding, but has reached a tentative
$3 billion out-of-court settlement of the dispute.
   The new offers include these deals:
   _Pirelli offered $1.86 billion for Firestone Tire & Rubber Co.
on Monday even though Firestone agreed last month to combine its
core tire-making operations with those of Japan's Bridgestone Corp.
in a joint venture. Pirelli said its offer was contingent on
Firestone calling off its deal with Bridgestone.
   _General Electric, making what it called its first unsolicited
takeover bid, offered $423 million Monday for Roper Corp., even
though the Augusta, Ga.-based appliance maker has agreed to be
acquired by Whirlpool Corp. for $352.5 million.
   _Campeau Corp., the Canadian retailing giant, is pressing its
months-long pursuit of Cincinnati-based Federated Department Stores
Inc., despite Federated's definitive agreement last week to be
acquired by R.H. Macy & Co. for $6.1 billion. Campeau has an
outstanding $6.18 billion offer.
   Because of Texaco's experience, ``Lawyers and their clients are
much more careful to not put themselves in a position where someone
could claim interference with someone else's agreement,'' said
Klaus Eppler, a partner in the law firm of Proskauer Rose Goetz &
Mendelsohn.
   By going straight to the shareholders, the bidders cannot be
accused of asking the directors to renege on previous agreements,
Eppler said.
   The three offers signify that deals actually are not complete
until a buyer's tender offer expires and the acquiring company can
actually buy the shares.
   ``I'm somewhat at a loss as to why all of a sudden this type of
behavior is now acceptable,'' Schwartz said.
   ``It used to be when you had a done deal, you didn't have people
coming in with tender offers. But you've got three of them right
here,'' he said.
   But although the flurry of such deals may be unusual, buyers and
sellers typically make arrangements for such eventualities. For
example, Macy's agreement to buy Federated requires Federated to
pay up $45 million in so-called ``breakup fees'' to Macy in the
event their deal falls through under certain circumstances.
   Such provisions typically are aimed at discouraging other
bidders from making a play for a company that has agreed to be
bought out by someone else.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
