<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Gillette-Coniston     03-08 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette-Coniston,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette Mails Annual Meeting Proxy Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. is urging its shareholders to reject
an attempt by a New York-based investment partnership to oust four
company directors at next month's annual meeting.
   Colman Mockler Jr., Gillette's chairman and chief operating
officer, said in a statement mailed Monday to shareholders that
Coniston Partners intended to sell or dismantle Gillette if the
hostile takeover succeeds.
   ``The principals of Coniston Group have no experience in
directing or running a worldwide manufacturing or consumer goods
company as an ongoing enterprise,'' stated Mockler. ``The board of
directors believes that the objective of Coniston Group is to force
the immediate sale or dismemberment of Gillette.''
   Coniston controls 6.76 million Gillette shares, or about 5.8
percent of the company's shares outstanding, and has indicated it
wanted the company to boost its stock price either by restructuring
or negotiating a merger with another party.
   Mockler contended the company's major restructuring in 1986, the
result of repeated takeover attempts by Revlon Group Inc., had
helped enhance shareholder values. Mockler said Gillette's earnings
per share rose a record 41 percent in 1987.
   Coniston, through two subsidiaries, is seeking to solicit a
majority of shareholders to elect four nominees to the Gillette
board at the April 21 meeting in Boston. One of the seats up for
election is Mockler's.
   Gillette shares rose 12{ cents to close at $40.75 Monday on New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Gus Oliver, a principal of Coniston Partners, said letters
explaining the group's proposal should be mailed to shareholders
later this week.
   Monday was the final day for shareholders to qualify to vote at
the annual meeting.
   Gillette underwent a major restructuring after rebuffing a third
hostile takeover bid by Revlon, which agreed not to seek to gain
control of Gillette under a 10-year pact signed in November 1986.
   Following the accord, Gillette laid off about 2,400 workers and
sold off a several sudsidiaries and discontinued unprofitable
divisions, including a line of high-quality writing instruments and
28 percent interest in Eye World stores.
   Gillette spokesman David Fausch said further cutbacks in some
international operations, such as cosmetics and beauty aids, are
planned as part of the restructuring.
   Coniston last year was instrumental in forcing a major
restructuring of Allegis Corp., the parent of United Airlines.
   Separately on Monday, Gillette said it had received notification
that New York real estate developer Donald Trump had received
Federal Trade Commission clearance to increase his holdings of the
company's stock.
   Trump now may purchase up to 24.9 percent of Gillette's stock.
Trump owns about 400,000 shares, which was less than three-tenths
of 1 percent of Gillette's 115 million common shares outstanding.
   A Gillette statement Monday said the company has not received
any communications from Trump.
</TEXT>
