<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Shoney'sRestructuring     03-08 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shoney's Restructuring,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shoney's Sets $730 Million Windfall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financial restructuring of Shoney's
Inc. means $730 million for stockholders who will receive one-time
dividends of $20 in cash and stock for each of their Shoney's
shares, officials said.
   ``This is not giving up, this is a fresh start,'' according to
Mitchell Boyd, vice chairman and chief executive officer of the
Nashville-based restaurant chain.
   Financing of the recapitalization will be through cash and about
$600 million in bank borrowings through a syndicate headed by the
Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, Boyd said Sunday.
   Shareholders will receive $16 per share in cash and a
subordinated debenture with a face value of $4 for each share of
Shoney's stock they own, and will retain ownership of the stock.
   Shareholders will not receive dividends but will receive
interest of 48 cents on each note, compared to the 18 cents per
share dividends received last year.
   Company chairman Ray Danner, who started the 1,400-restaurant
chain in 1959, stands to receive about $110 million in cash for his
6.9 million shares. Retired senior chairman Alex Schoenbaum,
founder of the concept, owns about 3.2 million shares and would
receive about $51 million.
   The two own 28 percent of the outstanding stock of Shoney's,
which had revenue last year of $694 million.
   Shareholder approval is not required for the plan, but the board
of directors decided Sunday to submit the proposal to shareholders
because of its massive scope.
   The recapitalization plan is designed to shift the company's
emphasis from growth through physical expansion to growth through
improved profit margins at existing locations, Boyd said.
   The plan will also allow the founders to cash out, while leaving
them as major owners of the stock for the next few years, and
provide incentives to the second generation of top management, Boyd
said.
   The plan permits executives to immediately cash in all
outstanding stock options and would set aside an additional 1
million shares for management stock options over the next several
years, allowing management to own up to 17 percent of the company.
</TEXT>
