<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0751EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mexico-Economy     03-08 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-Economy,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De la Madrid Urges Continued Fight Against Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Miguel de la Madrid urged producers
and businesses to hold down prices this month, saying it ``will be
decisive for the success'' of his anti-inflation program.
   ``Our goal is not only to reduce inflation in March, but to
continue dominating this harmful phenomenon the rest of the year,''
the president said Monday in a speech broadcast nationwide over
radio and television.
   De la Madrid said his program, called the Economic Solidarity
Pact, had brought down inflation, allowed for a budget surplus and
reduced government use of public credit, bringing down interest
rates.
   Inflation for February is expected to be about 8 percent, or
about half the 15.5 percent registered in January, he said.
Consumer prices rose 8.7 percent in the first half of February and
inflation was a record 159.2 percent in 1987.
   ``Today I can affirm with satisfaction that the basic
commitments of the pact are being fulfilled by ... workers,
businessmen and the government,'' he said.
   He said the government had increased its income while cutting
spending through reinforced austerity measures.
   The budget surplus, not counting debt service payments, meant
the government used less public credit and lightened pressure on
interest rates, he said.
   The minimal variation in the value of the peso currency against
the dollar from December 15 to February 21 also helped reduce
inflation, he said.
   The peso stood Monday at 2,330 to the dollar on the free market,
compared with 2,286 a month ago. The rate is used for tourism and
most border transactions. A second rate, the controlled rate, used
for 75 percent of all transactions, closed at 2,241 to the dollar,
compared with 2,205 a month ago.
   With the start of the second phase of the plan March 1, Treasury
Secretary Gustavo Petricioli announced that both rates, which had
been sliding against the dollar, would remain unchanged this month.
   Prices of government price-controlled items, which include
gasoline, electricity and basic foods, were frozen for the month
and a wage increase for the month held to 3 percent, below what had
been expected.
   The minimum wage rose March 1 to 8,000 pesos a day or about
$3.50.
   Budget Secretary Pedro Aspe told a meeting of state financial
officials on Sunday that the stabilization of the economy now was
``within reach.''
   Letting up on the inflation fight, he said, would mean a
reversal of the gains achieved so far.
   Aspe told the state financial officials that the government's
program did not constitute a ``shock'' plan, the name given to
drastic measures taken by Brazil and Argentina to rid their
economies of hyper-inflation.
   Mexico's plan, he said, does not include a ``generalized control
of prices and salaries'' such as other countries have imposed.
</TEXT>
