<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0806EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mulheren     03-08 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mulheren,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Extends Detention Order Two Days for Mulheren</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge will decide after reviewing a
psychiatrist's report whether an arbitrageur accused of plotting to
kill convicted stock speculator Ivan F. Boesky should be turned
over to a psychiatric facility in New Jersey.
   U.S. District Judge Whitman Knapp extended an order Monday
placing John A. Mulheren in Manhattan's Metropolitan Correctional
Center, a federal detention facility, until Wednesday, when Knapp
is to examine the report of the psychiatrist, Dr. Naomi Goldstein.
   Detention hearings were being held to determine if Mulheren
should be released on bail, held by federal authorities or turned
over to a psychiatric facility recommended by his attorneys.
   Late Saturday, U.S. District Judge Pierre Leval ordered Mulheren
to remain at the MCC after federal Magistrate Kathleen A. Roberts
ordered earlier in the day that Mulheren be released to the Carrier
Foundation in New Jersey.
   The government had argued that the New Jersey facility was not
secure enough to hold Mulheren, senior partner at Jamie Securities
Co.
   Mulheren, 38, of Rumson, N.J., was detained Feb. 18 on a federal
criminal complaint that he threatened to kill Boesky, a central
figure in the government's investigation of insider trading on Wall
Street, and Michael Davidoff, Boesky's former head trader.
   According to police reports, Mulheren was carrying weapons and
ammunition while making threats against the men, who might be
witnesses against Mulheren.
   ``We feel he has to be in a secure facility. There's a real
possibility Mr. Mulheren will get out and do it again,'' the
assistant U.S. attorney handling the case, Robert Gage, told the
court.
   Mulheren's lawyers argue that he is a manic-depressive who had
failed on the day of his arrest to take Lithium, a drug prescribed
to control extreme mood swings and impulses.
   At the hearing, they presented testimony from the arresting
police officers who had grown up with Mulheren and other testimony
that indicated Mulheren was a model citizen and not a threat to
society.
   Defense attorneys also said they were concerned about Mulheren's
health and wanted him where he could receive better care.
   Knapp initially appeared to be against having Mulheren examined
by a psychiatrist. But he later changed his mind and ruled that
Mulheren should be examined by Goldstein, a Manhattan psychiatrist
with whom Knapp is familiar and whom the government had suggested.
   Goldstein will be allowed to review Mulheren's records and
interview his attorneys and wife. However, Knapp stipulated that
information from the psychiatrist would not be used in a court
unless the trial judge so ordered. Information from the wife was
not to be used in court at all.
   At the 2 p.m. hearing Wednesday, Knapp will review the initial
impressions of Goldstein about Mulheren's behavior potential and
decide whether to send the case back to Roberts or send the
defendant to the New Jersey facility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
