<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0821EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UAW-Election     03-08 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW-Election,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Order New UAW Southwest Region Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says he'll order new delegate
elections at 68 United Auto Workers local unions in the Southwest
following reports of irregulatites in the campaign and election.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Suhrheinrich said Monday new
elections will be ordered in the contested 1986 race between
incumbent UAW Region 5 Director Kenneth Worley and his top
assistant, Jerry Tucker.
   Tucker was fired after he announced in May 1986 that he was
entering the race against Worley. Tucker lost by two-tenths of a
vote, but nearly 27 votes in the contest were challenged.
   The U.S. Department of Labor investigated the election and filed
three lawsuits against the UAW, charging that some illegal
delegates voted in the August election, that Tucker was fired
illegally and that Worley illegally used union money for an
individual campaign.
   Worley spent $13,000 in union money to buy jackets for delegates
to the UAW's constitutional convention in August 1986, where they
voted for regional directors and other union officers. The jackets
bore the region's number and Worley's name.
   Members in other regions bought their own jackets, as did
Tucker's Region 5 supporters, said Tucker's attorney, Joseph
Yablonski.
   The Labor Department investigation also found that Worley sent
out campaign fliers typed on a UAW typewriter on UAW stationary in
a UAW office, which also is illegal for an individual's campaign,
said Labor Department attorney Janet Graney.
   The UAW declined comment until it receives the order.
   The order, requiring new delegate elections in the eight-state
region, would end at least part of a 21-month legal battle by
Tucker and the Labor Department.
   Region 5 includes UAW locals in Missouri, Kansas, Oklahoma,
Arkansas, Texas, Louisiana, Colorado and New Mexico. After new
delegates are elected for each local, they will vote at a
mini-convention for a regional director.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
