<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PM-Perdue-CEO     03-08 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-PM-Perdue-CEO,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frank Perdue Steps Down as CEO of Perdue Farms Inc.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALISBURY, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Perdue, the 67-year-old head of
Perdue Farms Inc., is stepping down from his post, but says he will
remain directly involved in managing the large poultry company.
   Donald W. Mabe, a 30-year veteran of the company who most
recently served as vice chairman and president, has replaced Perdue
as president and chief executive officer, according to a company
statement.
   The change will relieve Perdue, associated by many television
commercial watchers with his motto, ``It takes a tough man to make
a tender chicken,'' from many day-to-day executive duties, the firm
said late last week. But he plans to work directly with Mabe.
   In other appointments, Perdue's son, James A. Perdue, vice
president of the company's quality improvement division, was named
to the chairman's committee, the top policy-making body, and Pelham
B. Lawrence, vice president and chief financial officer, was
elected to the board of directors.
   Mabe, who joined Perdue in 1957 as a broiler service supervisor,
has been broiler marketing specialist, director of broiler sales
and service, director of the hatching-egg program and production
manager of the firm. In 1967 he was named vice president and
general manager of processing and in 1972 he was appointed
executive vice president of the company. Elected to the board of
directors in 1963, he was named president in 1979 and vice chairman
in 1984.
   James Perdue joined the family business in 1983 as a management
trainee. He has served as a foreman, quality control coordinator
and plant manager in Salisbury, as well as quality control manager
for the company's Delmarva operations. He was named vice president
of quality improvement in 1987 and has been on the board of
directors since 1979.
</TEXT>
