<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PhiladelphiaElectric     03-08 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philadelphia Electric,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Electric Chairman To Retire, Board Elects New
President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philadelphia Electric Co. chairman James L.
Everett III is retiring and will be replaced by Joseph F. Paquette
Jr., a former Philadelphia Electric executive who is currently
president of a Michigan utility.
   The changes, announced by Philadelphia Electric on Monday, came
as the utility struggles to restart its Peach Bottom nuclear plant
that was shut down by the federal government last year.
   Everett, 61, said Monday he would retire at Philadelphia
Electric's April 13 board meeting, when Paquette is to be elected
his successor. Paquette will serve as Philadelphia Electric's
president until Everett's retirement.
   Everett will remain on the utility's board as chairman of the
executive committee.
   Paquette, 53 is president and chief operating officer of CMS
Energy Corp., the Jackson, Mich.-based parent of Consumers Power in
Jackson, Mich. He previously spent 30 years at Philadelphia
Electric and held a number of management positions.
   Everett's job had been in jeopardy since the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission decided last March 31 to close the Peach Bottom plant
after control room operators were found sleeping and playing video
games on the job.
   His pending retirement follows the departure last month of
Philadelphia Electric president John H. Austin.
   William Shane, chairman of the Pennsylvania Public Utility
Commission, had called for Everett's resignation. He said Monday he
was delighted with the latest changes.
   The utility also announced Monday that Corbin A. McNeill Jr.
will become its executive vice president for nuclear operations
next week. McNeill, 48, will be responsible for directing the
company's nuclear operations, including the nuclear department's
reorganization and efforts to get NRC approval to restart the York
County power plant.
   Philadelphia Electric must assure the NRC that it can operate
the plant safely before the agency will allow Peach Bottom's two
reactors to restart.
   Philadelphia Electric submitted part of a new restart plan on
Nov. 25, outlining management changes at Peach Bottom and at the
Limerick nuclear plant in Montgomery County. On Feb. 12,
Philadelphia Electric submitted the second half.
   In the plan, the company promised to provide more and
better-trained plant operators, a new management team at the plant
and a better employee value system.
   The NRC has found a list of deficiencies in the plant's
operations, including the release of mildly radioactive water into
the Susquehanna River, misclassification of radioactive waste
shipment and poor implementation of fire requirements.
   The shutdown is costing Philadelphia Electric and its three
partners in the plant about $14 million a month to buy replacement
power.
   Peach Bottom was opened in 1974 and is owned by Philadelphia
Electric, Public Servcie Electric & Gas Co., of Newark, N.J.;
Atlantic Electric Co., of Atlantic City, N.J.; and Delmarva Power &
Light Co., of Wilmington, Del.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
