<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0293</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose today in active trading, influenced
by dividend-related buying and selling strategies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 13.09 points
to 2,069.46 by 11 a.m. EST.
   Among broader market barometers, the New York Stock Exchange's
composite index measuring all listed issues rose 0.76 to 151.29.
The American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 1.07 to
295.21.
   Wall Street analysts said the market's strength was a good sign
that reflected a desire by institutional investment managers to put
unused money to work before the end of the first quarter March 31.
   ``The one thing insitutions want to avoid is lack of performance
at end of a quarter,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager of
institutional trading at Dillon Read & Co. in New York.
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by nearly 3-to-1 on the NYSE,
with 922 up, 384 down and 471 unchanged. Volume on the Big Board
totaled 86.55 million shares after the first 90 minutes of trading.
   Nearly a third of that volume came from trading in stocks that
carry dividend yields of at least 9 percent: Chemical New York,
Detroit Editson, Pacific Gas & Electric and McDermott International.
   Investors who buy Detroit Edison's stock before Thursday will
capture the right to receive the next quarterly dividend payment.
The deadline to capture the dividend in the other three issues
expires today.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 1.49 to
2,056.37.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 6 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 845 up, 710 down and 416 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 152.58 million shares, down from 201.41 million in the
previous session.
