<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ArgonneBeam 1stLd-Writethru   03-08 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argonne Beam, 1st Ld-Writethru,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists To Meet To Design Machine To Generate Bright X-Ray</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede and 5th graf to replace ``brightest'' and ``most
brilliant'' with ``most intense''; picks up 6th graf, Industry has
....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of scientists plan to gather Wednesday
to help design a $456 million machine that will generate the most
intense X-ray beams in the world, the laboratory's director says.
   The scientists, who are coming from some of the nation's major
industries and universities, will gather at Argonne National
Laboratory near suburban Lemont.
   Alan Schriesheim, Argonne's director, said President Reagan
allotted $12.6 million in his proposed fiscal 1989 budget to the
research, development and construction at Argonne of the machine _
called a synchroton.
   Congress has not yet passed the funding for the project. But
Schriesheim said he is optimistic lawmakers will approve the
funding because of the synchroton's ``extraordinary variety'' of
applications in pure science and industry.
   The machine would produce the most intense and powerful X-ray
beams ever generated and will be used to help scientists explain
the interior of matter, Schriesheim said in a telephone interview
Monday night.
   Industry has taken a keen interest in the development of the
machine, named the 7GeV Advanced Photon Source.
   ``The machine has already attracted more industrial
participation in the planning and design stages than any basic
research machine ever built in the country,'' said David Baurac, an
Argonne spokesman.
   Some of the 7GeV Advanced Photon Source's applications would be
in the petroleum, bio-medical, semiconductor, computer and airplane
industries, Schriesheim said.
   Future applications might include the creation of a plastic
stronger than steel, faster computer chips and improved diagnosis
of heart disease, he said.
   International Business Machines Corp of Armonk, N.Y, American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. of New York, Boeing Co. of Seattle, and
Exxon Corp. of New York are among the businesses expected to attend
the two-day meeting to help design the machine to meet their needs,
Schriesheim said.
   Three hundred scientists are expected to attend the meeting,
Baurac said.
   Argonne hopes to begin constructing the machine in late 1988 or
early 1989. The machine will take about seven years to build, and
its construction would generate 1,500 jobs, Baurac said.
   Once built, 300 scientists and technical staff members would run
the machine, and about 1,000 scientists from industry, universities
and other laboratories would use it each year, Baurac said.
   The synchroton works by taking positrons and accelerating them
almost to the speed of light. The synchroton then uses
sophisticated arrays of magnets to wiggle the beam violently to
generate ``the brightest beams of X-rays in the world'', Baurac
said.
   Positrons are ``like electrons with positive charges,'' Baurac
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1211EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-08 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean futures showed the greatest strength, gaining from
follow-through buying from Monday and from a lack of farmer selling
overnight, analysts said.
   Soybeans got an additional boost from the Agriculture
Department's announcement that last week's U.S. soybean exports
totaled nearly 22 million bushels, more than the market had
expected, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst for G.H. Miller & Co. in
Chicago.
   Corn futures advanced on news that the Soviet Union had
purchased 300,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery in the
current marketing year, which began Sept. 1.
   Wheat prices rose slightly in reaction to a mixed bag of news
surrounding the USDA's auction of government-owned wheat, Gidel
said.
   The positive news was that the agency had sold just 1.6 million
bushels of wheat in Friday's auction. But the USDA also said it
would continue its schedule of thrice-weekly auctions, each with a
target of 10 million bushels, through March 25.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.05{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1 cent higher with March at $2.01} a bushel; oats were } cent to
1 cent higher with March at $1.91{ a bushel; soybeans were 1\ cents
to 2{ cents higher with March at $6.15 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .80 cent higher with April at 72.35
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .73 cent higher with
March at 80.80 cents a pound; hogs were .18 cent to .60 cent higher
with April at 43.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20
cent lower to .50 cent higher with March at 54.50 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed sharply higher on Monday.
</TEXT>
