   Wall Street analysts said the market's strength was a good sign
that partly reflected a move by investment managers to put unused
money to work before the end of the first quarter March 31.
   ``The one thing insitutions want to avoid is lack of performance
at end of a quarter,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager of
institutional trading at Dillon Read & Co. in New York.
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 2-to-1 on the
NYSE, with 999 up, 427 down and 428 unchanged. Volume on the Big
Board totaled 139.26 million shares in the morning session, sharply
higher than the 74.69 million traded Monday morning.
   More than one-third of the volume today came from trading in
stocks that carry dividend yields of at least 9 percent: Chemical
New York, Detroit Edison, Pacific Gas & Electric and McDermott
International.
   Investors who buy Detroit Edison's stock before Thursday will
capture the right to receive the next quarterly dividend payment.
The deadline to capture the dividend in the other three issues
expires today.
   Among other notable actively traded stocks, IBM rose } to 118,
Texaco rose | to 46, and Reebok rose 1| to 18].
   Metals and forest product stocks were broadly higher. Alcoa rose
1{ to 47}, Phelps Dodge rose 1| to 42[ and Louisiana Pacific rose ~
to 29|.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 1.49 to
2,056.37.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 6 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 845 up, 710 down and 416 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 152.58 million shares, down from 201.41 million in the
previous session.
