<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1258EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Firestone-Pirelli 1stLd-Writethru f0012 03-08 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firestone-Pirelli, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0012,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone's Snub Made Buyout Offer Only Option: Pirelli Chief</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new grafs 13-14 with Pirelli suit in district court;
picks up 13th graf pvs bg'ng, Acquisition of ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. management's
rejection of a merger with Pirelli in favor of a venture with
Bridgestone Corp. set the stage for the Italian tiremaker's $1.86
billion tender offer for Firestone, Pirelli's chief says.
   Pirelli Societe Generale SA, the world's fifth-largest tire
maker, began negotiating at Firestone's request over a merger of
their tire operations in October 1986, Pirelli chief executive
Gianbattista DiGiorgia said Monday.
   The talks broke up with no agreement last March but resumed
early last month, DiGiorgia said in a telephone interview from New
York.
   ``We had a talk with them in the beginning of February, making a
proposal that seemed to us to have been accepted,'' DiGiorgia said.
``A couple days later they announced the preliminary agreement with
Bridgestone.''
   Pirelli said its offer Monday of $58 cash a share for
Firestone's 32 million common shares outstanding was contingent on
Firestone's dropping the tentative agreement reached with
Bridgestone on Feb. 16.
   That agreement, calling for the Japanese tire manufacturer to
buy 75 percent of Firestone's tire-making business for $1.5
billion, left Pirelli ``no choice'' but to make an offer directly
to Firestone's shareholders, the Italian company said in a
statement.
   Pirelli's offer also was conditioned on Pirelli's acquiring at
least two-thirds of Firestone's shares in the tender offer and on
the removal of Firestone's anti-takeover defenses, Pirelli said.
   If Pirelli acquires control of Firestone, it will sell certain
segments of the company to French tire manufacturer Michelin.
   John J. Nevin, chairman of Chicago-based Firestone, stated late
Monday that the company's board was reviewing the offer and asking
shareholders to await its recommendation before deciding whether to
tender their stock to Pirelli.
   The board will complete its review by March 18, Nevin said.
   Firestone stock shot up $13.50 a share to $63.12{ in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading Monday, topping Pirelli's
$58-a-share offer in reflection of speculation that a higher offer
might emerge.
   Pirelli had been regarded as a possible suitor for Firestone,
and just before Firestone announced its Bridgestone agreement
speculation was rampant that a bid was about to be made.
   Lawyers for Pirelli on Monday went to U.S. District Court in
Cleveland to try to stop Firestone from enforcing the Ohio Takeover
Act and from using its ``poison pill'' anti-takeover measures. A
poison pill is a move by a takeover target company to make its
stock less attractive to a potential acquirer.
   Judge Alice Batchelder denied Pirelli's request for a temporary
restraining order and set a hearing for next Monday to review the
constitutionality of the Ohio takeover laws.
   Acquisition of Firestone, the world's fourth-largest tiremaker,
substantially would increase Pirelli's current 1.5 percent share of
the U.S. tire market, the world's largest. It also would give the
Italian company its first U.S. manufacturing facilities.
   ``It is known in our strategy that we need production facilities
in the States,'' DiGiorgia said.
   ``We are present in eight countries so far,'' he said. ``It can
be good for us to have a major presence in the States in order to
improve our overall presence in the marketplace.''
   Analysts said acquiring Firestone's U.S. tire business would be
the easiest way for a foreign manufacturer to establish a solid
foothold in the U.S. market and remain a contender in the fiercely
competitive global industry.
   ``Firestone is the only game in town for a tire company located
outside the United States that wants to get in in a big way,'' said
Donald DeScenza of Nomura Securities International Inc. in New York.
   ``Firestone's got the plants, the distribution system and the
relationships with General Motors, Ford and Chrysler,'' he said.
   Firestone has about 21 percent of the lucrative U.S.
original-equipment market for passenger cars, said Ed Noga, editor
of Rubber & Plastics News, an Akron, Ohio-based trade journal.
   Goodyear holds 34 percent of that market, Uniroyal 20 percent,
General 13 percent, and Michelin 11 percent, Noga said.
   Firestone ranked fourth among tiremakers worldwide in 1986 sales
of tires alone, behind Goodyear, Michelin and Bridgestone, Noga
said.
   Pirelli, based in Milan, was fifth with 1987 sales of $3.65
billion.
   Under the plan to spin off parts of Firestone to Michelin, the
French group would pay about $650 million for Firestone's Brazilian
holdings and its Master Care Inc. auto service business, Pirelli
stated.
   Michelin also would have an option to buy 50 percent of
Firestone's synthetic rubber and diversified product holdings in
the United States for about $150 million.
   On Feb. 16, Bridgestone and Firestone said they intended to form
a new Akron-based business called Firestone Tire Co. that would own
Firestone's worldwide tire-making operation.
   Bridgestone would own 75 percent of the joint venture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
