<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Egypt-Oil 1stLd-Writethru f0043 03-08 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Egypt-Oil, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0043,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting of Non-OPEC Oil Producers Set For Wednesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Norway declining to attend; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Non-OPEC oil-producing countries are
scheduled to meet in London on Wednesday to consider ways of
stabilizing world oil prices, Egypt's top petroleum official said.
   In a statement distributed Tuesday by the state-run Middle East
News Agency, Oil Minister Abdel-Hady Kandil said Egypt called the
conference to discuss ``deteriorating conditions in the world oil
market.''
   He said conferees planned to discuss ``means of halting the
decline in prices and the best way to help producing countries,
both inside and outside OPEC, maintain a steady income.''
   Kandil said it was not known how long the meeting would last. He
also said it was not directed against the 13-member Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   Besides Egypt, participants will include the Soviet Union,
China, Norway, Angola, Malaysia, Brunei, Oman and Mexico, Kandil
said.
   In Stockholm, however, a Norwegian oil ministry spokesman was
quoted as saying that Norway had declined an invitation to attend
the meeting.
   The spokesman said Norway remained resolute in its commitment to
support OPEC in seeking stable oil prices, despite the recent
downturn on world markets.
</TEXT>
