<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Tandon-WesternDigital     03-08 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tandon-Western Digital,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Digital Buys Tandon Disk Drive Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tandon Corp. said Tuesday it has sold off the
disk-drive business on which the company was founded to Western
Digital Corp. for $49 million in cash and other considerations.
   Western Digital, of Irvine, a leading maker of computer storage,
communications, video controller and logic-processing units, also
will assume about $28 million in Tandon liabilities, the companies
said.
   The deal, which was agreed to in December and completed Tuesday,
involves Tandon's Winchester disk drive engineering and
manufacturing facilities in Santa Clara and San Jose, Calif., and
Singapore, as well as plated media operations in Santa Clara.
   Tandon, based in Chatsworth, will be left with its fledgling
business of manufacturing its own line of personal computers.
   As part of the deal, Tandon agreed to buy Western Digital
products to meet its production needs for at least two years.
   The acquisition of Tandon's disk-drive operations gives Western
Digital a business whose revenues grew to $280 million in 1987 from
$78 million in 1985.
</TEXT>
