<DOCNO> AP880308-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     03-08 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0453</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose broadly today in heavy trading,
strengthened by dividend-related buying strategies, takeover
speculation and a desire by institutional money managers to improve
first-quarter portfolio performances.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 16.74 points
to 2,073.11 by 2 p.m. EST.
   Among broader market barometers, the New York Stock Exchange's
composite index measuring all listed issues rose 1.07 to 151.41.
The American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 1.56 to
295.70.
   Wall Street analysts said the market's strength was a good sign
that partly reflected a move by investment managers to put unused
money to work before the end of the first quarter March 31.
   ``The one thing institutions want to avoid is lack of
performance at end of a quarter,'' said Philip C. Puccio, manager
of institutional trading at Dillon Read & Co. in New York.
   Others said speculators who had sold stock on the hunch the
market would decline were aggressively buying, a phenomenon known
as short-covering which can boost prices dramatically.
   Activity in stocks subject to takeover speculation also helped
strengthen prices. Still, there was an underlying feeling that Wall
Street remains deeply affected by the uncertain aftermath of the
October crash.
   ``We're still in that bear market mentality,'' said Hank
Streifler, senior vice president on the trading floor at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. ``We haven't moved over that hump.''
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 2-to-1 on the
NYSE, with 1,031 up, 489 down and 431 unchanged. Volume on the Big
Board totaled 182.6 million shares with two hours of trading left.
   More than one-third of the volume today came from trading in
stocks that carry dividend yields of at least 9 percent: Chemical
New York, Detroit Edison, Pacific Gas & Electric and McDermott
International.
   Investors who buy Detroit Edison's stock before Thursday will
capture the right to receive the next quarterly dividend payment.
The deadline to capture the dividend in the other three issues
expires today.
   Among notable blue-chip stocks, IBM rose | to 117~, Texaco rose
| to 46, General Electric rose 1] to 44} and Philip Morris rose 1
to 93].
   Reebok rose } tp 17{ in heavy trading, a sign of takeover
speculation. The company said it knew of no reason for the
activity. Salomon rose { to 24\ after indications that Revlon
Chairman Ronald Perelman, who has expressed interest in Salomon,
would make a major acquisition soon.
   Metals stocks were broadly higher, reflecting rising commodity
prices. Alcoa rose 1{ to 47}, Asarco rose | to 24| and Phelps Dodge
rose 1[ to 41|.
</TEXT>
