<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 1441EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Gulf-Western     03-08 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Gulf-Western,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf & Western Posts 8.9 Percent Decline in 1st-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf & Western Inc., the entertainment,
publishing and financial services giant, said its first-quarter
profit slipped 8.9 percent compared with strong results a year
earlier.
   Martin S. Davis, chairman and chief executive, said Tuesday the
results were in line with the company's expectations and that he
expected improvement for all of fiscal 1988.
   The company said its profit fell to $63.1 million, or $1.05 a
share, in its first fiscal quarter ended Jan. 31 compared with
earnings of $69.3 million, or $1.11 a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the first quarter rose 8.3 percent, to $1.18 billion
from $1.09 billion a year earlier.
   Operating income from motion pictures for the quarter was down
from record results for the Christmas holiday quarter a year
earlier, when the company had the movies ``Star Trek IV: The Voyage
Home,'' ``The Golden Child'' and ``Crocodile Dundee'' in U.S.
theaters and ``Top Gun'' in foreign release.
   This year, the company had the movies ``Eddie Murphy Raw'' and
``Fatal Attraction'' in U.S. theaters and ``Beverly Hills Cop II''
and ``The Untouchables'' in international release.
   Television operations reported higher operating income. Gulf &
Western produces television programs such as ``Cheers,'' operates
the Madison Square Garden cable TV network and owns 50 percent of
the USA cable network.
   Consumer publishing results were strong, but the costs of
product development depressed results from educational publishing
and professional information services.
   Consumer and commercial finance operations improved, as a result
of increased finance charge revenue and gains from insurance
operations as well as gains in credit card receivables and real
estate lending.
   Davis said one reason for his optimism about prospects for
earnings growth later this fiscal year is the planned release of
the films ``Crocodile Dundee II'' and ``Coming to America'' with
Eddie Murphy and revenue from syndication of the television shows
``Cheers,'' ``Webster'' and ``Family Ties.''
   The company also announced it had boosted its quarterly dividend
to 35 cents a share from 30 cents a share, payable April 1 to
shareholders of record March 18. In addition, Gulf & Western
declared a two-for-one stock split in the form of a 100 percent
stock dividend, payable May 2 to shareholders of record April 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
