<HEAD>Corning Glass To Acquire Clinical Labs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORNING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works said Tuesday that it
has agreed to acquire International Clinical Laboratories in a cash
deal valued at around $260 million.
   Chairman James Houghton said he hoped the merger would broaden
Corning's laboratory services. The company said it planned to
combine Nashville-based International Clinical with its laboratory
subsidiary, MePath Inc.
   Corning said it offered $26 a share for 3 million unissued
shares of International Clinical stock and has an option to buy all
of the shares owned by certain directors and officers of the
company.
   The deal, which is set to expire by March 28, is subject to
federal approval and to Corning acquiring a majority of
International Clinical's shares.
   International Clinical operates 13 major laboratories, mainly in
the South and West, and had sales of $205 million last fiscal year
and net income of $4.8 million.
   Besides laboratory services, Corning makes consumer housewares,
optical fibers and other telecommunications equipment, and
specialty glass and ceramics.
   Its MetPath subisidiary, which is based in Teterboro, N.J., has
about a dozen testing labs nationwide.
</TEXT>
