<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat, Corn Futures Close Lower; Soybeans Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, with wheat and corn futures
ending lower while soybeans advanced.
   The substantial losses in wheat futures were due to heavy
speculative selling stemming from a lack of major new export
business, analysts said.
   An Agriculture Department report showing the U.S. winter wheat
crop in good to fair condition was also seen as bearish for wheat
prices.
   And the USDA announced late Monday it would continue through
March 25 its thrice-weekly auctions of government-held wheat,
another negative factor for wheat prices.
   Soybean futures advanced on indications of rising world demand
for vegetable oils, analysts said.
   Most corn futures contracts finished fractionally lower in quiet
trading.
   ``I guess corn was kind of trapped between beans being up and
wheat being down,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst for G.H. Miller &
Co. in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 6 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3 a bushel; corn was 1\ cent
lower to } cent higher with March at $2.01{ a bushel; oats were {
cent lower to 1\ cents higher with March at $1.92 a bushel;
soybeans were 1{ cents to 4} cents higher with March at $6.17 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
