<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Stocks,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares End Lower on Thatcher Rejecting Rate Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
lower Tuesday but above their worst levels after Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher ruled out an early cut in bank base lending rates.
   The market's attention once again was dominated by the strength
of the British pound on foreign-exchange markets. Trading volume
was light in most shares.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was down 3.2 points at 1815.0. The index fell as much as 9.4 points
in response to Mrs. Thatcher's statements, but then recovered
somewhat on the strength of early gains on Wall Street.
   Volume was 420.9 million shares, up slightly from 404.8 million
on Monday.
   The pound's strength sparked concern about the competitiveness
of British exports.
   But Mrs. Thatcher told the House of Commons the government
didn't intend to lower interest rates to curb the pound's strength,
for fear of spurring inflation.
</TEXT>
