<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-08 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Cocoa Price-Support Scheme On Shaky Ground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for future delivery of cocoa rose Tuesday as a new
price-support scheme emerged from an international meeting in
London, but analysts said the plan was unlikely to halt the slide
in prices.
   On other markets, cattle futures advanced sharply while the pork
complex was mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed; precious metals
retreated; energy futures were mostly higher; and stock-index
futures advanced.
   The International Cocoa Organization's failure to reach
agreement on a new price-support plan after five days of meetings
triggered the automatic implementation of a scheme allowing the
ICCO to withhold up to 120,000 metric tons from the market.
   But the organization lacks sufficient funding to finance the
plan and its members, representing consumer and producer nations,
were sharply divided on what intervention price should trigger the
withholding mechanism, analysts said.
   ``It's very questionable whether the withholding program will
have any impact on the market,'' said Kim Badenhop, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   The spot price for cocoa has fallen more than $400 a metric ton
since July due primarily to abundant supplies and rising production.
   The ICCO intervened with a buffer-stock buying program that
began in January, but the organization exhausted the program's
250,000-metric-ton allocation within two months.
   The first news of the new price-support plan sparked a rally on
New York's Coffee Sugar & Cocoa Exchange, where the contract for
March delivery settled $17 higher at $1,600 a metric ton.
   But Badenhop said trading enthusiasm flagged on later reports
explaining the problems with the plan.
   Cattle futures posted impressive gains for the second
consecutive session on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in reaction
to higher cash prices for cattle, carcasses and boxed beef,
analysts said.
   The cattle market had been depressed due to a Lenten-season drop
in consumer demand for meat. But a wave of packing plant closings
last week has reduced beef supplies to the point where wholesale
prices have begun to rise, said William J. Arndt, an analyst in
Chicago for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Some concern remains that the drop in slaughters will lead to a
backlog of slaughter-ready animals but ``right now we're trading
the cash and the cash is strong,'' Arndt said.
   Hog futures followed cattle higher while frozen pork belly
futures retreated on an exchange report showing an unexpectedly
steep increase in supplies, he said.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to 1.37 cents higher with April at
72.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .55 cent to .85 cent higher
with March at 81 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to .42 cent
higher with April at 43.72 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.75 cent lower to .25 cent higher with March at 53.95 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures ended mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade with wheat and corn finishing lower while soybeans advanced.
   The substantial losses in wheat were due to heavy speculative
selling linked to a lack of major new export business, analysts
said.
   An Agriculture Department report showing the U.S. winter wheat
crop in good to fair condition also was seen as bearish for wheat
prices.
   And the USDA announced late Monday it would continue through
March 25 its thrice-weekly auctions of government-held wheat,
another negative factor for the wheat market.
   Soybean futures advanced on indications of rising global demand
for vegetable oils, analysts said.
   Most corn futures finished fractionally lower in quiet trading.
   Wheat settled 4\ cents to 6 cents lower with March at $2.99} a
bushel; corn was } cent lower to } cent higher with March at $2.01{
a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 1\ cents higher with March at
$1.92 a bushel; soybeans were 3\ cents to 4{ cents higher with
March at $6.17 a bushel.
   Most energy futures prices rose slightly on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in response to calls for meetings among
oil-producing nations, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 15 cents
higher with April at $15.45 a barrel; heating oil was .07 cent to
.19 cent higher with April at 43.49 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .23 cent lower to .41 cent higher with April at 43.71
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled .80 point higher at 269.10. The underlying
spot index closed 2.05 points higher at 269.43.
</TEXT>
