<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-08 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0621</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose strongly Tuesday in a rally powered
by takeover speculation, dividend-related buying and increased
interest in blue chips, sending the Dow Jones average to its
highest finish since the October crash.
   The closely watched average of 30 industrial stocks, which had
been lagging behind the broader market recently, finished at
2,081.07, up 24.70, the best post-crash close since 2,071.62 on
Feb. 29. Other market indices also advanced.
   Wall Street analysts said the rally partly reflected a desire by
managers of institutional investment funds to put unused money to
work, especially because the first quarter is drawing to a close in
three weeks and the best-possible portfolios must be presented to
clients.
   ``We're coming into show-and-tell time, the window-dressing
period,'' said Lawrence Wachtel, an analyst at Prudential Bache
Securities Inc. ``These guys can't sit there with piles of cash in
a boiling market and not get called down by the people who pay them
to manage money.''
   Others said the increased interest in stocks reflected true
buying interest and waning anxiety by investors over the impact of
the Oct. 19 collapse, along with indications that the economy is
thriving.
   ``As we move further away from the October break, more people
have thrown away their bear market caps and put bull market caps
on,'' said Joseph Barthel, technical trading strategist at the
Butcher & Singer Inc. investment firm.
   Others agreed that the potential for a stronger rally exists and
some predicted the Dow Jones industrials would soon surpass the
2,100 barrier, but many professional strategists were reluctant to
declare that the underlying post-crash nervousness has evaporated.
   ``We're still in that bear market mentality,'' said Hank
Striefler, senior vice president on the trading floor at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. ``We haven't moved over that hump.''
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading, gaining issues
outnumbered losers by 2-to-1, with 1,072 up, 535 down and 404
unchanged. Volume on the nation's largest stock market totaled
237.68 million shares, vs. 152.98 million in the previous session.
   Buying interest in selected stocks to capture high-yielding
dividends accounted for about 25 percent of the volume, which was
the highest since Jan. 25, when 275.25 million shares were traded.
   Among notably higher blue chip stocks, Procter & Gamble rose 1{
to 82\, Du Pont rose 2} to 87{, and General Electric rose 1{ to 44~.
   Oil stocks were boosted by takeover speculation in that
industry. Unocal rose 1~ to 37~, Kerr-McGee rose | to 36{ and
Phillips Petroleum rose { to 15].
   Digital Equipment fell 4 to 120] after the company unveiled a
line of powerful computers to challenge IBM. Analysts lowered their
earnings estimates for the company because it didn't introduce new
software for the computers.
   Metals stocks rose broadly, reflecting increased prices in the
metals markets. Reynolds rose 2 to 45], Asarco rose | to 24| and
Alcoa rose 1{ to 47}.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 267.02 million shares.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index of all listed issues
rose 1.09 to 151.62.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 2.90 to 312.42,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index rose 2.05 to 269.43.
   The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, which measures the
market value of all U.S. stocks, rose $19.12 billion.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 1.90
to 296.04.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
closed at 376.93, up 2.39.
</TEXT>
