<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FordProfit-Sharing     03-08 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Profit-Sharing,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Workers Receive 1987 Profit-Sharing Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIVONIA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Peabody didn't crack a smile as the
vice chairman of Ford Motor Co., surrounded by cameras and
microphones, leaned across the assembly line to hand him a check in
an envelope.
   ``I was kind of nervous _ all those TV cameras,'' he said after
Harold Poling chatted with him and gave him the check, Peabody's
share of Ford's industry-record $4.6 billion in 1987 profits.
   On Tuesday, Ford distributed $653 million in profit-sharing
checks averaging more than $3,700 to 156,479 hourly and salaried
workers _ a record in profit-sharing for any U.S. corporation.
   Most checks were distributed earlier in the day, but Peabody and
his pals on the main transmission assembly line at Ford's Livonia
Transmission plant agreed to wait until Poling could distribute
their checks in a ceremony recorded for posterity.
   ``It's not only the politicians who can call this Super
Tuesday,'' Poling told a crowd of cheering workers, adding that the
plant's 4,500 employees received $17.6 million, or an average of
$4,450 each.
   The Livonia Transmission workers' checks were higher than the
company average because the workers have high seniority and the
work force at the plant has remained stable for the past few years,
said Peter Pestillo, vice president for employee and external
affairs.
   Workers on Peabody's line assemble transmissions for
front-wheel-drive cars such as the popular Taurus-Sable and the new
Lincoln Continental. Most of them, Peabody included, said they are
lucky to be there at all.
   Most were on layoff from other plants and had enough seniority
to be called to work at Livonia when Ford added the line three
years ago.
   More than 160,250 Ford workers in the United States received
previous record profit-sharing checks averaging $2,100 for 1986,
when Ford earned $3.29 billion.
   Ford workers took home an average $2,100 in profit-sharing for
1985, $2,000 for 1984 and $400 for 1983, when the company
distributed the first checks.
   In the past five years, Ford said it has given out more than
$1.6 billion to its workers.
   General Motors Corp. workers received no share of GM's $3.56
billion in 1987 profits at the same time that the corporation said
it would distribute $184.6 million in stock bonuses to executives.
   GM workers also received no 1986 profit-sharing, although
executives received millions of dollars in cash and stock bonuses,
angering GM workers heading into national contract negotiations.
   GM, the nation's largest automaker, switched to the Ford
profit-sharing formula for 1988, but the company said that formula
still would have generated no profit-sharing had it been used for
1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880308-0315 </DOCNO>
