<HEAD>Pontiac Adds LeMans to Incentive Program, Ford Extends Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pontiac is offering $500 cash rebates on its
$6,399, Korean-built Pontiac LeMans and, for those buying their
first new car, an additional $600 discount, the General Motors
Corp. division said Tuesday.
   Pontiac said it will offer the $500 rebate on all LeMans
delivered through April 30.
   Pontiac also added LeMans to the first-time buyer program
announced Friday. The program also offers $600 discounts to
first-time buyers of the Sunbird, Grand Am, Fiero and some Firebird
models and expires Sept. 30.
   With both discounts, the suggested base price of the LeMans for
a new buyer falls to $5,299.
   Also on Tuesday, Ford Motor Co. announced it was extending its
incentive campaign until May 11. The program offers rebates of up
to $1,000 on nine car models and up to $500 on seven trucks.
   ``Even though our combined car and truck sales during January
and February increased 26 percent over the year-ago period, the
incentive program is being extended to keep our dealers in a
competitive position,'' said Robert Rewey, Ford vice president for
sales.
   The campaign includes $500 rebates on Ford Escort,
manual-transmission Tempo, Mustang (except 2.3-liter engine model),
Bronco II, Aerostar, and F-150, F-250 and F-350 pickup trucks and
Mercury Lynx, Tracer and manual-transmission Topaz.
   It also offers rebates of $600 on most Ford Thunderbird and
Mercury Cougar models and $750 on the 2.3-liter engine Mustang, on
all Mustang models in California and Hawaii, and on Ford Taurus and
Mercury Sable.
   A $1,000 rebate is available on the Ford Thunderbird Turbo Coupe
and Mercury Cougar XR7.
</TEXT>
