<2ND_LINE>AM-Black & Decker,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Standard Plans Negotiations With Black & Decker, Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc. said Tuesday it plans
enter negotiations with hostile suitor Black & Decker and other
potential purchasers, but will continue developing its defensive
recapitalization plan.
   In a release issued late Tuesday, American Standard said it
would pursue alternatives that include a sale of the company.
   ``American Standard expects to provide confidential information
to, and to engage in, discussions and negotiations with Black &
Decker and other potential purchasers of the company,'' American
Standard stated in the release.
   American Standard had been vehemently resisting Black & Decker's
overtures since the Towson, Md.-based company made its initial
buyout offer in late January.
   On Monday, New York-based American Standard had indicated it
would consider Black & Decker's latest offer of $73 a share for
American Standard's 31 million common shares outstanding, a total
of about $2.26 billion.
   American Standard, a plumbing and air conditioning manufacturer,
also said it was considering sweetening its own recapitalization
plan for a second time.
   The $2.3 billion recapitalization would pay shareholders $64 in
cash, $5 in securities and one share of stock in the recapitalized
company for each old share. The plan was revised last Friday from
an earlier proposal that had a cash portion of $59 a share.
   American Standard shares fell 25 cents to $73 a share Tuesday in
New York Stock Exchange trading. Black & Decker fell 25 cents to
$17.75 a share.
   Analysts had said Monday they expected American Standard to come
up with another sweetened proposal before the March 19 deadline for
the Black & Decker tender offer.
</TEXT>
