<HEAD>Dollar Edges Higher, Stocks Up Early In Tokyo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with morning stock closing</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose marginally against the
Japanese yen Wednesday morning in Tokyo, while stock prices gained
following an overnight advance on Wall Street.
   The dollar traded at about 127.95 yen at late morning in Tokyo,
up from its opening of 127.80 yen. The dollar had dropped 1.07 yen
to 127.80 yen on Tuesday.
   Trading was quiet in foreign exchange, where dealers awaited the
outcome of U.S. presidential primary elections. The ``Super
Tuesday'' election results were expected Wednesday afternoon in
Japan.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average,
down 150.85 points on Tuesday, rose 103.62 points, or 0.41 percent,
to close the morning session at 25,465.73. Volume was a light 5.5
million shares.
   Michio Katsumata of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage
house, said Tokyo stock prices were supported by Tuesday's rally on
the New York Stock Exchange and by stabilization of the foreign
exchange market.
   Investors also appeared to be buying shares deemed to be at
bargain prices after the Tokyo market's decline on Tuesday, dealers
said.
